<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DroughtRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0776 07-07 1343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought Rdp, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0776,1370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Water Restrictions Tighten, Mississippi Still Blocked</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 6 grafs for 3rd graf, ``Rain fell ...'' to UPDATE with
possibility of diverting water to Mississippi River, Perpich's
comments after returning from Washington, and crop analyst's
comments. Picks up 4th graf pvs, ``Temperatures hit ...'' INSERTS 2
grafs after 6th graf pvs `The temperature ...'' for details on
circus train. Picks up 7th graf pvs, ``Salt concentrations ...''
INSERTS one graf after 10th graf `Cooper, deputy' to explain impact
on plants. SUBS 19th graf pvs, ``Leonard made ...'' to conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROGER PETTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal official warned Thursday that two more months of
drought could close plants along three rivers in Alabama, Florida
and Georgia, as temperature records continued to fall, and circus
elephants were taken to a river to cool off in 101-degree
Pittsburgh.
   One official in drought-stricken Ohio warned Thursday of likely
statewide water restrictions. Low water again kept barges from
moving on the lower Mississippi River and part of the Ohio was
closed.
   An official of the Minnesota Department of Natural Resources
said the river dipped closer Wednesday to a level that would
trigger a recommendation to divert water from lakes in northern
Minnesota.
   Minnesota Gov. Rudy Perpich, upon returning from Washington
Thursday night, said he persuaded U.S. Agriculture Secretary
Richard Lyng to allow farmers to donate their hay on Conservation
Reserve Program land without forfeiting any of their payment's
under it.
   ``This is a very critical time for livestock and dairy farmers.
These people are on the verge of bankruptcy,'' Perpich said at the
Minneapolis-St. Paul International Airport. ``But it won't work
unless we get the farmers to donate the hay and the private and
commercial truckers to donate the transportation. I'll contribute
my time and drive one of those trucks.''
   Private crop analyst Conrad Leslie of the Leslie Analytical
Organization in Chicago said corn yields from irrigated fields of
Nebraska and parts of Iowa could be good, but some other fields in
the Midwest already are ``beyond recovery.''
   ``This is a disaster under development,'' said Leslie. ``We're
in uncharted waters. The great difficulty is that we don't know
what the moisture situation will be a year from now and whether we
can make a recovery.''
   Rain fell on some dry sections of Minnesota, but Pennsylvania
officials declared a statewide drought watch Thursday, triggering
voluntary reductions in water use and a ban on open fires in state
parks and forests.
   Temperatures hit record highs for the date Thursday in at least
28 cities from the Great Lakes to the East Coast, including 102 at
Fort Wayne, Ind., the National Weather Service said.
   Detroit's high of 100 degrees toppled a record that had been on
the books since 1874, when thermometers reached 97. In the normally
cool mountains of West Virginia, Elkins hit a record 93, the ninth
record temperature there since June 1.
   The temperature at Pittsburgh hit a record 101 degrees and four
elephants from the Syria Temple Shrine Circus were taken to the
Allegheny River for a cooling wallow. Only one of the animals,
natives of hot climates, got in and rolled around in the water.
   The drought also knocked the steam out of the annual railroad
journey transporting vintage, restored circus wagons to Milwaukee
for the city's Circus Parade.
   Officials said Thursday that the steam locomotive used to pull
the train won't make the run this year because of the danger of
setting track-side fires from sparks.
   Salt concentrations in Mississippi River water climbed higher
Thursday at drinking water intakes of the nearest downriver suburb
of New Orleans, and officials of St. Bernard Parish began reserving
barges to float in fresh water. The river's reduced flow is not
strong enough to push the dense salt water back into the Gulf of
Mexico.
   Lower Plaquemines Parish is already bringing fresh water by
barge to mix with the salty flow at its intakes 30 miles downriver
from New Orleans. The salt concentration there is already strong
enough to taste.
   A continuation of the drought for two more months could threaten
municipal water supplies and close plants along three major rivers
in Alabama, Florida and Georgia, Lt. Col. Garry Cooper of the Army
Corps of Engineers said Thursday.
   Cooper, deputy district engineer for the Corps' Mobile District,
addressed a drought management meeting of the
Apalachicola-Chattahoochee-Flint Drought Management Committee, made
up of the Corps, the three states and other organizations. The
committee announced that navigation on Florida's Apalachicola River
would virtually end on July 13 because of low water.
   Cooper referred to both plants that use water to run turbines
and generate electricity and those that use water for industrial
purposes, such as rinsing textiles and cooling machinery. The lack
of rain already has forced Alabama Power to shut down nearly all
hydroelectric production and have coal-burning plants make up the
difference.
   The Mississippi River remained closed at Black Hills, Miss.,
about 20 miles south of Natchez, Miss., where water had been as low
as five feet.
   ``Hopefully by this weekend we will have the river open if
somebody doesn't mess up,'' L.C. Fumbanks, chief of navigation for
the Army Corps of Engineers, said in a radio-telephone interview
from aboard the dredge Jadwin.
   The Jadwin worked south of Greenville, Miss., where traffic
resumed Wednesday, while another dredge pumped sand from the
blockage at Black Hills.
   The Coast Guard decided Thursday to close the Ohio River at
Mound City, Ill., for 12-hour shifts to clear a build-up of sand
and silt from the channel, said Coast Guard Lt. j.g. Jim Clifton.
   He said the affected two-mile stretch would be opened for six
hours Friday morning, closed for 12 hours, then reopened for six
hours. ``It will just alternate back and forth like that until they
get it cleared through,'' Clifton said, adding that he had no
estimate how long that would take.
   Traffic on the Missouri River is normal, although barges are
carrying lighter loads, thanks to reservoirs upstream, said Paul
Johnston, director of public affairs for the Army Corps of
Engineers at Omaha, Neb.
   Ohio Lt. Gov. Paul Leonard said Thursday that voluntary water
conservation measures are not working.
   ``Most of the cities we're checking with regularly indicate the
program is not paying dividends,'' Leonard said in Dayton. ``My
guess is that if the drought continues for another two weeks to 30
days, we're going to need (statewide) mandatory water
restrictions.''
   Leonard made his remarks before leaving for Washington, where
he, like Perpich and officials from seven states met with Lyng.
   Richard Shank, director of Ohio's Environmental Protection
Agency, has asked the state's 2,500 largest water systems to aim
for a a minimum 25 percent reduction in water use by all customers,
and some cities have already banned lawn sprinkling.
   Georgia's Department of Natural Resources fined Gwinnett and
Cobb counties $75,000 each Wednesday for taking too much water in
June and told them they must cut consumption, possibly including
round-the-clock bans on outdoor water use.
   Up to 1.5 inches of rain fell on parts of west-central and
northern Minnesota late Wednesday and early Thursday, somewhat
easing drought conditions, the National Weather Service said today.
   ``Every little bit helps,'' said Clay County extension agent
Eddie Bernhardson. However, he added: ``the rain's been really
limited in most areas of the county, and high temperatures are
complicating'' the situation.
   Wheat, Clay County's biggest crop, ``is getting to the point
where in some areas they'll get 8 to 10 bushels an acre maximum''
compared to a normal average of 40 to 50 bushels, he said.
   Approximately 545 bales of hay from Elon College, N.C., arrived
Thursday at Shelbyville, Ky. It was a ``gesture of thanks'' for the
2,300 tons of hay Kentucky farmers sent by train to North Carolina
two years ago, said Roger Nesbitt, a spokesman for the Kentucky
Department of Agriculture.
   ``I gave about 50 bales two years ago. Now it's my turn to
receive,'' said O.L. Jeffries, who farms near Shelbyville. ``I
don't know which way to turn. It's pitiful.''
</TEXT>
