<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson     07-07 0450</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Criticizes Bush Stance On Plane Downing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson is calling for a period of
mourning for the victims of the U.S. missile attack on an Iranian
jetliner, and urging the United States to pay reparations to the
victims' families.
   He also criticized Vice President George Bush for statements the
likely Republican nominee made this week in response to the deaths
of 290 people in the downing of the Iranian commercial jet.
   ``I thought it was a bit in bad taste, if not downright vulgar,
to be running around on July 4, getting applause lines, talking
about the honor of the Navy, as if it were in question, and not
expressing the profound sense of humanity that the American people
have and our sense of sharing the grief of the tragedy,'' Jackson
said at the United Nations.
   Bush expressed his deep regrets on Monday as he campaigned
through the Midwest, saying, ``Obviously, as we celebrate our great
national holiday our hearts go out to the loved ones and families
of those who were lost and also (hearts) go out to those kids,
those young Americans who are defending freedom halfway around the
world.''
   However, Bush also said he could identify with the captain of
the Navy cruiser, who made the decision to fire because he believed
his ship was in danger. And Bush said he did not believe U.S.
policy in the region would change as a result of the incident.
   ``Life goes on,' the vice president said.
   Jackson, who met with Arab leaders at the United Nations,
emphasized that the downing of the Iranian plane was ``an accident,
an error ... No one assumes that the Navy is without compassion,
that it moved to engage in an act of war.''
   ``We should say to Iran that we sincerely regret the accident
occurred, that we offer reparations or compensation to the families
of the victims, if they will accept them,'' said Jackson, repeating
a call he made over the holiday weekend in the wake of the incident.
   At the U.N., Jackson met with envoys of the Arab League,
including Iraq, Djibouti, Mauritania, Sudan, Libya, Somalia, Syria,
Yemen, Saudi Arabia, Oman, Democratic Yemen, Algeria, Morocco,
Lebanon and Qatar.
   He repeated his plea for the release of U.S. hostages and all
other captives in Lebanon.
   Jackson also said he favored a new international naval
peacekeeping force in the gulf. ``I hope the United Nations will
hav a much more prominent rule in the gulf in the future,'' Jackson
said.
   Earlier, when asked if he had any interest in becoming U.S.
ambassador to the United Nations, Jackson replied, ``None
whatsoever.''
</TEXT>
