<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Reagan'sPollster     07-07 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan's Pollster,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Presidential Pollster Says Democrats Would Do Well To Pick Glenn
For Veep</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's pollster says Ohio Sen.
John Glenn is ``far and away'' the strongest choice for the
Democratic vice presidential nomination.
   Richard Wirthlin, more accustomed to giving advice to
Republicans than to Democrat Michael Dukakis, told reporters at a
luncheon Wednesday that Glenn would help Dukakis ``play the
patriotic theme'' in the general election campaign.
   He contended the question of the Republican vice presidential
choice was less clear for Vice President George Bush.
   Among the prospects he cited were Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas and
his wife, former Transportation Secretary Elizabeth Dole, as well
as Gov. Jim Thompson of Illinois and former Gov. Richard Thornburgh
of Pennsylvania.
   Wirthlin, who has done polling for Reagan for more than 20
years, worked for Dole during the Kansas senator's unsuccessful bid
for the 1988 GOP presidential nomination.
   He said he thought Dole would help Bush in the Midwest farm belt
and among blue collar workers. But he conceded that Dole's acerbic
personality could be damaging if he went on the attack.
   Wirthlin also said he thought it would be a mistake to have
President Reagan on the stump attacking Dukakis.
   ``People do not approve of an incumbent president attacking a
candidate trying to succeed him,'' he said.
   In addition, he said, Reagan ``is not a good attack candidate.''
   Wirthlin also said the resignation of Attorney General Edwin
Meese III doesn't erase the ``sleaze factor'' for Bush in the fall
presidential campaign, but makes it easier for him to deal with it.
   During a luncheon session with reporters, Wirthlin said only
about 3 percent of the voters he has surveyed cite ethics in
government as the most important issue, a figure that is no higher
than a year earlier.
   The issue that outstrips all others in importance in the minds
of voters is drugs, said the pollster.
   ``There are now 21 percent who tag drugs as the single most
important problem facing the nation,'' he said. No other issue was
named by more than 10 percent of people interviewed.
   While Meese was under investigation by independent counsel James
McKay, Bush was peppered with questions about whether he thought
the attorney general should resign. Bush aides at one point
described Meese as a ``liability,'' a description the vice
president disavowed.
   Wirthlin said the departure of Meese would put the ethics issue
``in a different context'' and would ``enable Bush to talk about
ethics without implicitly criticizing Ed Meese.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
