<1ST_LINE>r p PM-ConventionProtests Bjt   07-07 0583</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Convention Protests, Bjt,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Demonstrators of All Stripes Get Soapbox Time At The Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the Democratic National Convention opens
here this month, protesters from animal rights activists to AIDS
victims will be on hand to try to grab a bit of the spotlight.
   But convention organizers, who carefully orchestrate many of the
events inside the convention hall, are also seeking to bring order
to what could otherwise be a chaotic crush of demonstrations.
   The city is supplying a stage across the street from the
convention site that will serve as a soapbox for a variety of
causes. Protesters are being offered two-hour time slots over five
days to air their views.
   The city will provide a stage and sound equipment in the lot,
which authorities estimate can hold about 30,000 people.
   The demonstrators will be within sight and earshot of the
delegates as they arrive and depart during the gathering July 15-18.
   However, the plan is being challenged in federal court by a
coalition of groups seeking expanded space for demonstrations. A
decision was possible as early as today.
   Generally, potentially antagonistic groups have not been
scheduled together, although a gay rights group follows a white
supremacist organization onto the stage one afternoon.
   By Wednesday, 25 of the 40 slots were filled, four of them by
one organization, the Committee for Fair Elections. At least four
other groups with ties to that committee also have reserved time.
   The group is the vehicle for the independent presidential
campaign of Leonora B. Fulani, who says she will bring 10,000
backers to the convention. She has qualified for the ballot in all
50 states and is eligible for federal matching funds.
   Demonstrations coinciding with those on the stage supplied by
the city will be permitted in the parking lot, but their organizers
cannot use powerful sound equipment.
   Local organizations with demonstration time include a
neighborhood group that opposes the construction of a domed stadium
in the neighborhood near the convention site.
   The Nationalist Movement, a Mississippi-based white supremacy
group, has been given a parade permit and a two-hour slot on Sunday
afternoon in conjunction with its annual convention.
   Other groups given protest time in the parking lot include:
   _ The Committee on Latin America, a liberal Washington-based
foreign policy lobby.
   _ No Business As Usual, which opposes the Strategic Defense
Initiative, known as Star Wars.
   _ Disabled In Action, a group advocating better access for the
handicapped, which has ties to the Fulani campaign.
   _ U.S.-Congo Friendship Committee, which opposes the regime of
President Mobuto Sese Seko of Zaire.
   _ Rep. Gus Savage, a Democratic congressman from Chicago.
   _ Castillo Cultural Centers, a New York City-based performing
arts group specializing in working-class history and progressive
politics.
   _ The People's Independent Democratic Club, a Bronx, N.Y.-based
pro-Fulani organization.
   _ People With AIDS Coalition and March on AIDS.
   _ Arts Pluribus Unum, an Atlanta artist and activist group
specializing in liberal political performances.
   _ Compassion Campaign `88, an animal rights organization.
   _ LEGAL, a national gay rights organization.
   _ Greater Lowell Environmental Campaign, a Massachusetts-based
group specializing in hazardous waste issues.
   _ Illinois Solidarity Party, a former splinter Democratic group
now run by Fulani backers.
   _ Prisoners of War@Missing in Action, which advocates further
investigation into cases of servicemen listed as missing from the
Vietnam war.
   _ The New Alliance Party, a national group that led the drive to
get Ms. Fulani's name on the ballot.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
