<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis     07-07 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Keeps Up Attack On Administration Ethics Despite Meese
Move</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis, resuming his criticism of Reagan
administration ethical standards, said the nation regained ``a
measure of self-respect'' through the resignation of Attorney
General Edwin Meese III.
   But he said Meese's departure does not change the
administration's record of ethical breaches.
   ``The way to clean up Washington is to clean out those people
who are indifferent to breaches of the public trust and the public
laws,'' the Democratic presidential nominee-to-be told a friendly
audience of Greek Americans on Wednesday.
   ``Yesterday we lost an attorney general, but we gained a measure
of self-respect,'' he said.
   Dukakis, the Massachusetts governor, was spending most of today
in his Statehouse office before heading West for three days of
campaigning. Awaiting his review was a proposed fiscal 1989 budget
compromise worked out Wednesday evening by legislators.
   Passage of that plan would help Dukakis at home, where budget
problems have prompted questions about his ability to govern while
seeking the White House. It would also make life easier for him on
the campaign trail, where he has used competent fiscal management
as a selling point.
   Dukakis ended his day Wednesday with a speech to the Greek
Orthodox Ecumenical Congress. The presumed Republican nominee, Vice
President George Bush, was to address the same group today.
   ``Next year, if all goes well, we're going to have a president
who will insist that those who accept the privilege of public
service must understand the meaning of public service,'' Dukakis
told the group. ``If someone in my administration is caught
breaking the law, we won't make excuses for him, we'll prosecute
him.''
   Before that appearance Dukakis met for more than an hour with 20
national civil rights leaders, including NAACP executive director
Benjamin Hooks, National Urban League President John Jacob, the
Rev. Joseph Lowery of the Southern Christian Leadership Conference
and Coretta Scott King, the widow of Martin Luther King Jr.
   Several participants described the session as positive and more
substantive than a meeting the same group had recently with Bush.
   ``I cannot recall an issue he disagreed with us on,'' Hooks said.
   Whether blacks will support Dukakis without Jesse Jackson on the
ticket is largely up to Jackson, Hooks said.
   ``I think that they basically will follow _ though some will be
disappointed _ will follow his leadership,'' he said.
   Dukakis began his day by meeting with Indiana Rep. Lee Hamilton,
the eighth potential running mate to meet face-to-face with
Dukakis. One of them, Georgia Sen. Sam Nunn, took himself out of
the running.
   After a 50-minute meeting with Dukakis at the Statehouse,
Hamilton fired back a quick ``yes'' when asked if he would accept
the vice presidential nomination.
   Hamilton said he had a ``very relaxed and wide-ranging
discussion'' with Dukakis, with the main topics being the vice
presidency and foreign policy.
   Others being considered for the No. 2 spot on the ticket are
Jackson, Sens. Albert Gore of Tennessee, John Glenn of Ohio, Lloyd
Bentsen of Texas and Bob Graham of Florida, and Rep. Richard
Gephardt of Missouri.
   Paul Brountas, Dukakis' campaign chairman, was in Washington
through Friday, gathering information on the contenders and talking
with party leaders.
</TEXT>
