<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Hefner     07-07 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Hefner,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hugh Hefner's Former Girlfriend Alleges He Supplied Her With Drugs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hugh Hefner's former girlfriend has accused
the Playboy founder and celebrity divorce lawyer Marvin Mitchelson
of supplying her with enough drugs to make her an addict.
   ``(Hefner) supplied me with almost every drug that I ever took
in that house. He had for about two years,'' Carrie Leigh, 24, told
the television show ``Entertainment Tonight'' in a two-part
interview beginning Wednesday.
   ``I was addicted to pills ... painkillers, sleeping pills,
Quaaludes and he had them under lock and key and he supplied me
with these pills every day,'' she said.
   Miss Leigh filed a $35 million palimony suit against Hefner
earlier this year, claiming he defrauded and deceived her by
allegedly abandoning promises to support her and father a child.
She later dropped the lawsuit.
   ``As the original palimony suit proved, Carrie Leigh had a very
vivid imagination, and whatever she says, should be viewed with a
certain amount of skepticism,'' Hefner said Wednesday.
   ``I spent the last three years of the relationship trying to
curb her abuse of both drugs and alcohol, and she very well knows
it,'' he said of their five-year relationship that ended earlier
this year. ``Please remember that I had a stroke in March 1985 that
dramatically changed the focus of my life. It ended my use of all
recreational drugs.''
   In Wednesday's segment, Miss Leigh accused Mitchelson, who
represented her in the palimony lawsuit, of also supplying drugs
and making a pass at her.
   ``At the time when I started the lawsuit, I was still addicted
to some pills and he supplied me with them,'' Miss Leigh said.
   Mitchelson, who handled divorces of such celebrities as Joan
Collins of ``Dynasty,'' is under investigation by the California
State Bar for alleged misconduct.
   ``I completely deny all of the allegations. I don't want to
attack Carrie Leigh,'' Mitchelson told the television program.
   ``She told me during the case I was a wonderful lawyer. For the
last 31 years, I've never heard any criticisms like these until
recently,'' he said. ``I've spent my life defending women, not
attacking them.''
</TEXT>
