<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Unrest Bjt   07-07 0669</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Unrest, Bjt,0698</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Say They Crush Protest in Armenia, Deny Deaths</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet authorities acknowledge that paratroopers
crushed a protest by thousands of people who shut down a major
airport in Armenia. But they deny activists' claims that soldiers
killed as many as five protesters.
   The activists, pushing for annexation of a predominantly
Armenian region of the neighboring republic of Azerbaijan, charged
Wednesday that Red Army troops killed demonstrators at the airport
in Yerevan, the Armenian capital.
   The latest round of protests began Monday with a general strike
and intensified Tuesday night with the airport clash, officials and
Armenian activists said.
   On Wednesday, the situation did not appear to be stabilizing.
   The evening television news program ``Vremya'' said hundreds of
thousands of Armenians thronged Yerevan's streets as the strike
continued.
   The government daily Izvestia said mass transit was still shut
down and the situation had worsened since Tuesday, when 26
factories and economic agencies in the southern republic were idled.
   Since February, Yerevan has been the scene of massive
demonstrations by Armenians demanding annexation of the
Nagorno-Karabakh region of Azerbaijan. Until now, the protests had
reportedly been peaceful.
   On Wednesday, Foreign Ministry spokesman Vadim Perfilyev told a
news conference ``the rumors that Armenians were killed are
groundless.''
   But he acknowledged that Soviet troops late Tuesday routed about
2,000 people from in and around the Zvartnots Airport. He said 36
people ``had to seek medical assistance'' after the clash.
   On Wednesday, the Communist Party daily Pravda said that during
a Tuesday rally in Yerevan's Theater Square, someone began calling
for a blockade of the airport and a large column of people headed
toward it on foot.
   Pravda said planes were allowed to land, but demonstrators
``grossly disrupted order'' and prevented them from taking off
again. Hundreds of passengers were stranded, it said.
   ``Vremya'' said 3,000 people took part in the protest and 60
flights were grounded along with 14,000 passengers.
   Perfilyev said about 400 people occupied the airport's terminal;
another 1,500 gathered outside, according to the official Tass news
agency.
   The demonstrators impeded the sale of tickets and the collection
of luggage, entered the landing strip and stopped passengers from
coming into the terminal, Perfilyev said.
   Security troops then moved in to evict the protesters, who began
hurling rocks and bottles _ and that's when the 36 casualties
occurred, he said.
   In Moscow, Armenian activists said witnesses had telephoned them
from Yerevan to say army troops carrying machine guns and backed by
tanks had begun firing without warning on the protesters.
   ``All of a sudden, they started shooting,'' artist Kuryun G.
Nagapetyan told about 50 people who gathered for a rally outside
Moscow's red-brick Armenian church. ``They were carrying clubs,
like policemen in the West, and they beat people right and left.''
   Three students were killed, he said, and 37 people reportedly
were hospitalized.
   Alexei Mananikov, an editor of the unofficial Moscow journal
Glasnost, said at least one man was killed and as many as 40 people
wounded by soldiers at the airport.
   Lev. G. Gambaryan, another Armenian who lives in Moscow, told
the rally that two children, ages 6 and 10, had also died of
gunshot wounds.
   But he and Nagapetyan said it was not certain whether the two
reported deaths were new or among the three previously reported.
   Ethnic Armenians make up the majority in Nagorno-Karabakh. They
have long been demanding that the mountainous region be transfered
to Armenia.
   Armenia supports the demand, but Azerbaijan has rejected it and
the issue has gone to officials in Moscow.
   In February, rioting in the Azerbaijani city of Sumgait left
dead 32 people _ 26 Armenians and six Azerbaijanis.
   On Tuesday, newspapers reported that a general strike began in
Yerevan following a large meeting Sunday on the city's main square.
   The meeting Sunday was with delegates who had attended last
week's Communist Party conference in Moscow.
   Apparently dissatisfied with the Armenian delegation's
presentation of the Nagorno-Karabakh dispute, activists called a
strike.
</TEXT>
