<DOCNO> AP880707-0020 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 0038EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a BC-Opera     07-07 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Opera,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NY City Opera Opens with `Merry Widow'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New York City Opera opened its season in
mirthful fashion Wednesday with Franz Lehar's waltzing operetta
``The Merry Widow.''
   Soprano Leigh Munro sang the title role with credit, from the
poignant ``Vilia'' to her more rousing turns. Baritone Richard
White was splendid as Count Danilo, fond of the can-can girls at
Maxim's, fated to be landed as husband by the Merry Widow. White
conveyed Danilo's manly charm, whether his character was intending
to charm or making a fool of himself with jealousy. His singing was
robust without bluster and his only problem was some weak high
notes.
   The second romantic couple in the plot were more noticed than
usual because they sang so well. Ruth Gordon was Natalie, wife of
Baron Popoff, and Paul Austin Kelly made his debut as Vicomte de
Jolidon, her secret lover. Kelly doesn't sing ``The Merry Widow
Waltz,'' of course, but he has some of the evening's most romantic
music. As he sang about the little pavilion into which he's taking
Natalie, he sounded quietly romantic. Miss Gordon joined in, in
bittersweet tones. The audience lavished them with applause.
   James Billings, as the baron's flunky, Nisch, has the timing to
make the oldest jokes funny again. Richard McKee (Baron Popoff) had
delivery nearly as good.
   The production was in English at the New York State Theater.
   We did miss the kick line in Act 2 when seven men, five
Marsovians and two Frenchmen, sing ``Girls, Girls, Girls.'' In the
current staging, they march off.
   A song from another Lehar work, ``Girls Were Made To Love and
Kiss,'' has been inserted and given to Count Danilo. It's in the
brief third act and he is singing it _ with demonstrations _ to the
can-can girls when the Merry Widow makes her entrance into Maxim's.
   Imre Pallo conducted.
   The season's second night, Thursday, moves firmly into opera
territory, with ``La Boheme.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880707-0021 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 0056EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-MexicoElection 4thLd-Writethru a0406 07-07 0955</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico Election, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0406,0984</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Accuses Government of Fraud in Elections</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 8th graf, `The party ...,' to UPDATE
with quotes from PRI officials. PICKS up 9th graf, `This year .. .'
EDITS to conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ISAAC A. LEVI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition candidates accused the government
of fraud in presidential elections Wednesday and met jointly with
federal officials to protest. A journalist reported that an
8-year-old boy voted in one town.
   There appeared to be little doubt, however, that Carlos Salinas
de Gortari of the governing Institutional Revolutionary Party,
would win a six-year term as president in an unbroken tradition
dating to 1929.
   Official returns were not expected before Sunday.
   Salinas de Gortari's most visible opponent, Cuauhtemoc Cardenas
of the leftist coalition National Democratic Front, told a news
conference the government ``is intending to have a fraud.''
   ``We have begun to receive information nationwide that is not
favorable for the government party,'' he said, before leaving for
his meeting with Manuel J. Clouthier of the conservative National
Action Party and Rosario Ibarra de Piedra of the radical
Revolutionary Workers Party.
   The three scheduled a news conference after their meeting with
Interior Secretary Manuel Bartlett.
   ``I want to tell you that all of these irregular acts, all of
these repeated acts throughout the country, have created a
situation of irregularity,'' Cardenas said.
   The party in power, known as the PRI, has won every presidential
election since its founding in 1929 and has controlled the congress
and governorships in all 31 states.
   Juan Enriquez, Salinas de Gortari's spokesman, said in an
intervew that any incident of fraud ``has been less than one tenth
of one percent of polling booths, and we're very pleased,''
   ``This has been a peaceful election in which the vote has been
respected,'' he said.
   This year, a clear deterioration of the PRI's influence was
evidenced by the strong campaigns waged by Cardenas and Clouthier.
   In addition to president, voters will elect 500 members of the
Chamber of Deputies to three-year terms and 64 senators to six-year
terms.
   All of the country's nearly 55,000 voting places closed by 6
p.m. (8 p.m. EDT) except for those where people were still lined up
to vote.
   The Federal Election Commission, which supervises the balloting,
said it received more than 50 complaints of voting irregularities,
most of them minor, from political parties. Complaints ranged from
missing ballots to a sailor who tried to vote repeatedly at
different polls in the port of Acapulco.
   The most flagrant incidents of purported fraud were reported in
Salinas de Gortari's adopted home town of Agualeguas, about 80
miles north of Monterrey near the U.S. border.
   Petra Hernandez, a reporter for the Monterrey daily El Norte,
said election officials ``let a lot of people vote for the whole
family. They voted for their wife, their kids, their mom who
couldn't come.''
   She said her paper had a picture of an 8-year-old boy who voted
with his father's voting card.
   Although opposition parties by law are allowed to have
representatives at each polling place, Ms. Hernandez said only PRI
representatives were at the town's three precincts.
   ``The president of one precinct also was filling out ballots. I
saw him get up nine times and put ballots in the boxes,'' she said.
   She said that when voters unfamiliar with the process would ask
the president of the precinct how to vote, ``he said, `Just take
the ballots and mark where it says PRI.'''
   Presidents of precincts are appointed by the government and are
always from PRI.
   PRI officials said they doubted the reports of fraud in
Agualeguas. ``It was a very peaceful vote ... obviously with a
preference for Salinas,'' said Enriquez.
   Almost all industry and commerce in Mexico closed for the day.
Traffic on normally bustling city streets was light.
   The commission issued no immediate figures on turnout among the
38 million eligible voters. But long lines were reported at polling
stations in major cities and towns.
   Outgoing President Miguel de la Madrid voted at a school across
from the presidential residence in Mexico City. His term expires
Dec. 1 and under the constitution he cannot be re-elected.
   De la Madrid won 70 percent of the vote in 1982. The victory
margin was not expected to be as wide for his likely successor,
Salinas de Gortari.
   Clouthier's conservative National Action Party and Cardenas'
National Democratic Front coalition have weakened the PRI's popular
support.
   Clouthier, Cardenas and Ibarra de Piedra signed an agreement
last week to fight fraud and pledged to challenge the results if
tampering was suspected.
   On Saturday, assassins with shotguns killed Francisco Xavier
Ovando, a long-time Cardenas collaborator and strategist in his
campaign, and an Ovando aid.
   Police said Tuesday the shootings were not politically
motivated. They said Ovando was killed in revenge for fighting
organized crime while serving as Michoacan attorney general when
Cardenas was governor of the state.
   Cardenas called the slayings ``a provocation'' and said it
showed how far ``some of the most reactionary sectors'' within the
PRI will go. He did not identify any group.
   The 54-year-old Cardenas ran on a platform of renewed
nationalism and was aided by the affection Mexicans still feel for
his father, the late President Lazaro Cardenas.
   Salinas de Gortari, a 40-year-old Harvard-educated economist,
was handicapped by having been de la Madrid's budget director and
author of his economic austerity program. He has pledged to
modernize the country's economic and political systems.
   Clouthier, a wealthy 54-year-old rancher and businessman from
northwestern Sinaloa state, said he would return even more
state-owned companies to the private sector and ask farmers if they
want the current system of cooperative farms or private property.
</TEXT>
