<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Taiwan     07-07 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Taiwan,0596</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nationalists Open Party Congress With Tough Talk On Communists,
Violence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHIRLEY LAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LINKOU, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Lee Teng-hui opened a key
congress of the ruling Nationalist Party today with a cautious
promise of more democratic change and tough talk on rival Communist
China.
   The landmark meeting began at a suburban Taipei sports stadium
packed with more than 10,000 people.
   Behind the podium hung three huge portraits of the 94-year-old
party's three previous leaders _ Sun Yat-sen, Chiang Kai-shek and
his son, Chiang Ching-kuo, who died in January.
   The congress, the party's 13th, is the first in which delegates
were not handpicked by top party officials and in which a Central
Committee election was not restricted to candidates proposed by the
party leader.
   It comes at a time of increasing political liberalization in
Taiwan, a nation slowly emerging from its authoritarian past.
   The congress' 1,209 delegates are expected to elevate a new
generation of party leaders to replace aging conservatives who came
from the mainland with Chiang Kai-shek after the Communists forced
the Nationalists from mainland China in 1949.
   An overhaul of the Cabinet also is expected after the congress,
with speculation centering on the fate of 74-year-old Premier Yu
Kuo-hwa, who is viewed as the leading conservative.
   Lee, the acting party chairman since Chiang's death, said in his
speech that the Nationalists ``should accelerate the implementation
of the reforms initiated by late Chairman Chiang Ching-kuo with an
even more active and responsible attitude.''
   But he cautioned that ``extremism and violence are the greatest
enemies of democracy,'' an apparent reference to recent street
demonstrations for accelerated political change. Those protests
have occasionally turned violent.
   In his final years, Chiang Ching-kuo ended Taiwan's 38-year-old
martial law, tolerated the formation of opposition parties, opened
the door to unofficial contact with rival Communist China and
relaxed controls on the press.
   In cautiously pushing more reform, Lee's speech appeared
tailored to placate both aging Nationalist conservatives, some of
whom may step down during the congress, and younger party members
who support more political, social and economic liberalization.
   Winston Chang, a party delegate, described Lee as ``a man of
tolerance'' with elements of a good party leader. Indeed, Lee is
expected to be named the party's permanent chairman on Friday.
   ``He accepts different opinions and absorbs them,'' said Chang,
an illegitimate son of Chiang Ching-kuo who took his mother's
surname.
   Lee spent much of his 30-minute speech reiterating Taiwan's
hardline policy of no official contacts with the Chinese Communists.
   Both the Nationalists, or Kuomintang, and Communists claim to be
the rightful ruler of mainland China and Taiwan.
   Lee accused Beijing of having ``blind ambition to destroy'' the
Nationalist government. ``We have no illusions about the Chinese
Communist regime and will make no compromise of any kind with
them.''
   The Nationalists have rejected Beijing's call for reunification
under a ``one country, two systems'' policy in which Taiwan could
retain its capitalist economy.
   Unofficial contact between the two sides has increased recently,
particularly with Chiang Ching-kuo's decision last year to end a
ban on travel to the mainland to allow family reunions.
   Indirect trade also has increased and many businessmen are
seeking permission to invest and trade directly with China's 1
billion people.
   The future China policy of this nation of about 20 million
people is expected to be a hot topic at the congress, with some
delegates pushing for increased trade and exchanges.
</TEXT>
