<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BeachClosings     07-07 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Beach Closings,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Health Hazard Along 25 Mile Stretch Of Beach</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINEOLA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Swimming along a 25-mile stretch of Long
Island's South Shore was prohibited Wednesday after medical waste,
including blood vials and syringes, washed ashore, officials said.
   State, county and town beaches were advised to forbid swimming
until health inspectors determine that the waters are safe, said
Shelly Domash, a spokeswoman for the Nassau County Health
Department.
   Beaches were closed from Long Beach in southwest Nassau County
east to Robert Moses State Park in southwest Suffolk County, she
said. The area includes the popular Jones Beach State Park.
   Officials were trying to determine the origin of the debris.
Domash said it may have been illegally dumped by a hospital or
laboratory.
   The discovery came just as a heat wave moved over the region,
with forecasters predicting temperatures in the 90s through the
weekend. Hundreds of thousands of people usually flock to the
beaches on the weekends.
   Two syringes were spotted at Nassau Beach on Tuesday, Domash
said. On Wednesday as the tide came in, a vial of blood, empty
vials and a medical scrub brush were found at Lido Beach, then two
more syringes at Nassau Beach, she said. At East Atlantic Beach, a
glass container and surgical sutures washed up.
   Two truckloads of debris _ including a red waste bag, apparently
carrying infectious hospital waste, filled and empty vials and
syringes, bandages, grease balls, seaweed and firecrackers _ were
removed from the beaches at Lido Beach, Domash said.
   Ronald F. Foley, the regional director of the New York State
Parks, said Jones Beach State Park and Robert Moses State Park were
closed after a handful of debris, including plastic wrappers and
what appeared to be parts of syringes, were found at the parks'
beaches Wednesday.
   ``It's the unknown _ you don't know what it is or what it's
carrying,'' Foley said. ``We wanted to be on the safe side.''
</TEXT>
