<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 0232EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-PlantClosing Bjt   07-07 0805</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Plant Closing, Bjt,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats Have Votes to Override Veto of Plant-Closing Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Holding enough votes this time to override a
veto, Democrats are forcing a second election-year showdown with
President Reagan over giving workers advance notice of plant
closings and large layoffs.
   On a 72-23 vote Wednesday, the Senate passed a bill requiring
companies to give 60 days' notice before shutting down any
operation or instituting a layoff affecting more than 50 people or
a third of the work force.
   President Reagan cited the mandated notices as his primary
reason for vetoing a massive overhaul of the nation's trade laws
two months ago, saying advance notices would reduce U.S.
competitiveness and stifle new job creation.
   But with polls showing more than 80 percent voter support for
the measure and Democrats using the issue to attack the economic
policies of Reagan and Vice President George Bush, 19 Republicans _
including seven up for re-election _ broke with the White House on
Wednesday's vote.
   Wednesday's vote was the biggest legislative victory for
organized labor since it helped return the Senate to Democratic
control in the 1986 election after Republicans held the majority
the first six years of Reagan's presidency.
   Just nine Senate Republicans supported the mandatory notices a
year ago, when they were made a part of the trade bill. And only 10
broke ranks last month when the Senate, on a 61-37 vote, fell five
votes short of the necessary two-thirds for overriding Reagan's
veto.
   ``I'm certain that it's going to become law,'' lamented Sen.
Phil Gramm, R-Texas, a leading opponent of the notice bill. ``The
tragedy is that we're doing this all because of politics.''
   A White House official said after the vote that Reagan has not
stated definitely that he will veto it. The official, speaking on
the condition of anonymity, said the president's advisers were
divided on the issue even though the administration put out a
statement prior to the vote saying they would urge him to veto it.
   ``I don't know what the president's going to do when he gets
this bill,'' said Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., who
complained earlier about labor leaders ``wielding a lot of clout in
this body.''
   Both supporters and opponents of the legislation raised the
possibility that Reagan might allow the bill to become law after
the expected House approval without signing it. Under the
Constitution, a president has only 10 working days to veto a bill
after passage by both houses.
   ``I would hope that the president would see there are sufficient
votes to override a veto and that will mean that he won't veto
it,'' said Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, the bill's chief author.
   Had the measure been law the past two years, more than 800,000
workers who were laid off each year in 1986 and 1987 would have
received advance notices, he said.
   A 1985 study by the Bureau of Labor Statistics showed that more
than half the 2.2 million workers caught up in mass layoffs
annually received one day's notice or less before losing their jobs.
   House Majority Leader Thomas Foley, D-Wash., said the
Senate-passed bill will be taken up in the House early next week,
to be followed immediately by House action on a revised trade bill
that doesn't include the plant-closing notices.
   The House has never voted on the plant-closing issue itself. But
its 308-113 vote in May to override Reagan's veto of the trade bill
is viewed as assuring veto-proof passage there as well.
   The AFL-CIO made the layoff notices its top legislative priority
the past two years and vowed to withdraw its pivotal support for
any trade legislation desired by major business groups if the
measure were not included or enacted separately.
   AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland called Wednesday's vote margin
overwhelming and a ``welcome message for American workers.''
   GOP opponents won a minor political skirmish along the way. They
stalled the vote for two weeks, effectively denying Democrats a
chance to override a Reagan veto before the Democratic National
Convention in Atlanta.
   A year ago, the mandatory notices were opposed by four Democrats
and 36 Republicans. The four Democrats _ Dale Bumpers and David
Pryor of Arkansas, David Boren of Oklahoma and Fritz Hollings of
South Carolina _ had all switched sides by the time of the vote
last month on overriding Reagan's veto.
   So had five Republicans, three of them up for re-election this
year _ John Chafee of Rhode Island, John Danforth of Missouri and
William Roth of Delaware.
   By Wednesday's vote, another seven Republicans switched sides _
David Karnes of Nebraska, Nancy Kassebaum of Kansas, Bob Kasten of
Wisconsin, John McCain of Arizona, Alan Simpson of Wyoming and John
Warner of Virginia. Of that group, only Karnes is up for election
this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
