<DOCNO> AP880707-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 0235EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Competitiveness Bjt   07-07 0607</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Competitiveness, Bjt,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Decline In Dollar Helps Cut US Labor Costs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With the smallest wage increases of any
industrial nation and help from a sinking dollar, U.S. factories
outperformed their foreign rivals last year in reducing labor costs
and making their goods more competitive on world markets.
   Measured in devalued American dollars, labor costs in the United
States declined 1.5 percent in 1987, compared with increases of 7.5
percent in South Korea, 7.7 percent in Canada, 13.5 percent in
Japan and 23.9 percent in West Germany, the Labor Department said
Wednesday.
   But even before the dramatic devaluation of the dollar against
major European and Asian currencies, the United States outperformed
all but Japan in keeping a lid on labor costs.
   Measured by their own currency, the yen, Japanese manufacturers
reduced their labor costs by 2.5 percent. Excluding France, labor
costs rose for nine other major industrial powers.
   ``Clearly there's a definite improvement in out competitiveness
vis-a-vis our trading partners,'' said Allen Sinai, chief economist
for the Boston Co., a New York consulting house. ``But we still
have a long way to go to restore the competitiveness we lost over
the past decade.''
   The government data showed that labor costs, measured in
American dollars, rose an average 3.3 percent annually from 1979
through 1985 while falling 2.3 percent in Japan, 1.8 percent in
Korea, 4.8 percent in West Germany and 2.4 percent in Great Britain.
   Wage increases in the United States averaging 6.9 percent
annually those years also outpaced the gains enjoyed by workers in
all of the other countries when measured in dollars.
   U.S. manufacturers, however, held hourly wage and benefit
increases last year to just 1.3 percent, the lowest of any of the
industrial powers, according to the government data.
   Japan was close with wage and benefit increases averaging 1.4
percent. But wages rose 4 percent in West Germany and 4.5 percent
in Canada while soaring 8.2 percent in Great Britain.
   But with civilian unemployment in the United States now hovering
in the range of 5{ percent, Sinai noted that wage increases have
been escalating rapidly the past two months.
   ``That suggests that our labor costs are rising at the same time
that the dollar has quit falling,'' Sinai said. ``This year we will
not repeat the experience of last year.''
   For one thing, he said, declines in the industrial sectors of
Japan, Great Britain and West Germany have all bottomed out and
they are begining to enjoy the same rebound in manufacturing that
the United States has experienced in the past year.
   The Labor Department figures, in fact, showed that manufacturing
growth last year was slower in the United States than in Canada,
Korea, Italy and Great Britain.
   U.S. productivity improvements at 2.8 percent also were smaller
than 4 percent gains of Japan, France and Italy, 7 percent increase
in Great Britain and nearly 8 percent improvement in Norway.
   While five of the nine countries had larger 1987 productivity
increases than the United States, only Great Britain and Norway
exceeded the U.S. rate of improvement over the past two years, the
government said.
   However, only the United States and Canada experienced any
employment growth in manufacturing last year. The U.S. increase was
only one-half of 1 percent, but it reversed two straight years of
declines.
   Factory jobs remained about the same in Germany and Sweden and
fell by 1 percent to 2.5 percent in the other countries.
   For France, 1987 was the 13th consecutive year of manufacturing
employment declines and in Great Britain factory jobs have been
falling in number for the past 10 years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
