<HEAD>International Politicians to Attend Democratic Convention</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 300 politicians from at least 104
countries are to attend Democratic National Convention in Atlanta,
according to the National Democratic Institute for International
Affairs.
   ``As a party with a historical commitment to an internationbal
vision, we also want to learn from our guests' experiences - to
join with them in a dialogue to deepen our shared commitmern to
democratic values and pratcices,'' said former Vice President
Walter Mondale, chairman of the institute.
   An International Visitors Lounge will be set up at the Georgia
World Congress Center, adjacent to the hall where the convention
meets. The visitors will get simultaneous translations of
convention proceedings in Spanish and French.
   Prominent guests who have accepted the institute's invitiation
include John Hume, member of the British parliament from Northern
Ireland; Kazuo Tanikawa of the Japanese Diet, former Premier Adolfo
Suarez of Spain; Markus Aaltonen, chairman of the Foreign Affairs
Committee of the Finnish parliament and Guatemalan first lady
Raquel Cerezo; Leonel Brizola.
   On July 21, as the convention ends, there will be a special
program for members of the Washington diplomatic corps who will go
to Atlanta for the day. The institute said 108 have accepted the
invitation.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Coalition to Press Presidential Candidates to Appoint More Women</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A coalition of women activists is urging the
presidential candidates make a commitment to appoint more women to
executive positions in the new administration.
   The Coalition for Women's Appointments said Wednesday it will
conduct a bipartisan effort to recruit and recommend qualified
women for presidential appointments, said Irene Natividad,
chairwoman of the National Women's Political Caucus.
   ``We're looking beyond the campaign to show the next
administration that the gender gap does more than deliver votes;
it's also bulging with talent,'' said Natividad.
   Too often, men have voiced a ``we-can't-find-any syndrome,''
said Rep. Lynn Martin, R-Ill., co-chairman of Vice President George
Bush's presidential campaign.
   She and other participants in a news conference said the goal of
about 50 women's groups in the coalition is to counter that
syndrome by making known the names and resumes of women who have
qualifications for high government posts.
