<HEAD>South Dakota Democratic Convention Begins</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PIERRE, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic State Convention this week
will feature a speech by former Sen. George McGovern and some
battles for two important party posts.
   Only one nomination for a statewide office is up for grabs at
the three-day convention in Huron, where delegates planned to begin
preliminary work today. The incumbent national committeeman and
national committeewoman both face challenges as they seek new
four-year terms, said state Democratic Party Executive Director
Rick Hauffe.
   Republicans currently hold a two-thirds majority in both the
state House and Senate, but Democrats for the first time in years
are fielding candidates for nearly every one of the 105 legislative
seats.
   ``We're on the brink of what could be a very successful era for
the Democratic Party because there's a need for change,'' Hauffe
said. ``They (voters) want new faces, new leaders, new directions.''
   McGovern, and two members of South Dakota's congressional
delegation, Sen. Tom Daschle and Rep. Tim Johnson and Eisnach will
speak to the convention delegates on Saturday. Hubert Humphrey III,
Minnesota's atttorney general and a candidate for the Senate, will
deliver the keynote address at the Saturday night banquet that will
wrap up the convention.
</TEXT>
