<1ST_LINE>r a PM-EscapeeCaught     07-07 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Escapee Caught,0238</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Wanted In Kentucky Prison Breakout Caught In Texas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EL PASO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI arrested a Kentucky prison escapee
who also was wanted on murder charges following a breakout by eight
inmates.
   Billy Hall, 25, of Paducah, Ky., surrendered without incident to
FBI agents at a Western Union office Wednesday, agent Terry Kincaid
said.
   Hall and seven others escaped June 16 from the Kentucky State
Penitentiary in Eddyville. Only two escapees remain at large,
authorities said.
   Hall, who was serving a 23-year sentence for burglary and
assault, may have been in Mexico and crossed the border trying to
get money, Kincaid said.
   ``We had developed information that he may be in the area. We
were alert for his presence,'' he said.
   Hall and two other escapees were indicted Friday by a Stewart
County, Tenn., grand jury for the shotgun slayings of a Dover,
Tenn., couple, Buford Vester, 71, and Myrtle Vester, 69. Their
bodies were found a few days after the prison break.
   The breakout and slayings were the subject of this week's
television episode of ``America's Most Wanted.''
   Hall was in the El Paso County Jail awaiting a warrant from
Kentucky, Kincaid said.
   The two remaining escapees are: James Blanton, 29, of Farler,
Ky., who was serving time for murder; and Derek Quintero, 26, of
Clarksville, Tenn., serving 37 years for kidnapping and robbery.
</TEXT>
