<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     07-07 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Administration Planning To Sell Stinger Missiles To Greece</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon says Reagan administration
officials have told Congress it intends to sell 1,000 Stinger
anti-aircraft missiles to Greece.
   In addition to the missiles, the sale will include training and
training equipment, and devices known as ``identify friend or foe''
components to discern friendly from enemy aircraft, the Pentgon
said in its announcement Wednesday.
   The prime contractor for the handheld Stinger missiles worth
$124 million will be the General Dynamics Corp. Valley Systems
Division of Rancho Cucamonga, Calif, the Pentagon said.
   Greece, a member of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization, will
``have no difficulty absorbing these systems into its armed
forces'' and the sale ``will have no adverse impact on U.S. defense
readiness,'' the announcement said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>House Passes SBA Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House has rejected a call by President
Reagan to end direct loans under the Small Business Admnistration
in passing by a vote of 42-40 a bill to continue the agency's
subsidy program.
   The measure passed Wednesday includes provisions giving aid to
firms seeking to sell overseas, and banning SBA assistance for
firms engaging in business with South Africa.
   The bill authorizes $470 million in SBA spending next year, $514
million in fiscal 1990 and $566 in fiscal 1991. It also authorizes
spending as necessary for disaster assistance loans.
   Total SBA-supported loans would reach $3.7 billion next year,
under the bill, up from about $3.2 billion this year.
   The now goes to the Senate.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>FDIC Fails To Sell Continental Loans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials of the Federal Deposit Insurance
Corp. say the agency has been unable to sell nearly $1 billion in
bad loans acquired in the largest-ever government bank bailout.
   Steven Seelig, associate director of the FDIC's division of
liquidation, said Wednesday a plan approved by the FDIC board in
February to publicly offer the loans from Continental Illinois
Corp. in six large portfolios failed, but he said the agency would
begin immeditately trying to sell the loans in smaller packages.
   The Chicago-based bank, then the seventh largest in the nation,
in 1984 ceived $4.5 billion _ $3.5 billion of it borrowed from the
Federal Reserve System _ in an unprecendented move by the FDIC.
   As part of the rescue, the FDIC took over many of Continental
Illinois' problem loans and acquired ownership of the bank's stock.
It expects to recoup all but $1.7 billion of the bailout money by
selling the loans and the stock.
   The FDIC insures accounts in commercial banks up to $100,000.
</TEXT>
