<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 0312EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Airliner-Gulf     07-07 0620</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Airliner-Gulf,0641</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iranians Mourn Dead; U.S. Team Hunts For Clues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-Airliner Rdp, Bjt
^By MONA ZIADE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Black-clad mourners shook fists in anger
as they marched behind Iranian flag-draped coffins, vowing to
avenge the U.S. Navy's downing of an Iran Air passenger jet with
290 people aboard.
   The mourners waved banners and shouted ``Revenge, Revenge'' and
``Down with Reagan'' as 24 of the victims were buried on Wednesday.
   A team of U.S. military experts, meanwhile, arrived in Bahrain
and began their inquiry into the attack by questioning senior
officers of the Navy cruiser that fired the fatal missiles, U.S.
sources said.
   In Iran, the manager of the airport where the Iran Air Airbus
A300 originated was quoted as saying the Navy failed to use the
proper frequency when it issued a warning before firing two
missiles at the plane.
   Iran said 200 bodies had been recovered from the Persian Gulf
since the USS Vincennes destroyed the plane Sunday. All but 38 of
those aboard were Iranians.
   Fourteen were buried Wednesday in Bandar Abbas and ten others
were buried at Zahedan, in southeastern Iran, Iranian television
reported.
   The television broadcast 15 minutes of scenes from the funerals.
   In Bandar Abbas, women clad in black chadors marched behind
coffins and carried banners, some of which read: ``America: You
fight with weapons and we with our belief in God, and your defeat
is imminent.''
   Men waved their fists, shouting ``Death to America!'' Coffins
were draped with the green, white and red Iranian flag.
   Iran says the Vincennes intentionally shot down the Airbus over
the Strait of Hormuz, gateway to the gulf.
   The United States says the Vincennes fired because the vessel's
combat information center identified the approaching aircraft as an
F-14 fighter on an attack bearing.
   The aircraft, on a scheduled flight to Dubai from Bandar Abbas,
was shot down while the Navy ship was engaged in battle with
Iranian gunboats, U.S. officials said.
   A six-member military investigating team arrived from the United
States late Tuesday and began probing the tragedy.
   U.S. military sources said the team planned to interview Capt.
Will C. Rogers III, skipper of the Vincennes, and other officers
present during the crisis.
   The Bandar Abbas airport manager, Hossein Peroussi, was quoted
in today's Chicago Tribune as saying he was in the control tower
when the plane left for Dubai on Sunday.
   ``The situation was quite normal. The airplane was right on
course.'' he was quoted as saying.
   The Iranian government let more than 100 foreign correspondents
into Iran Wednesday to interview airport personnel and view bodies
of victims.
   Peroussi was quoted as denying Pentagon claims the Vincennes
sent warnings to the plane on both ultra-high frequency and
very-high frequency radio channels. He said the Navy uses only UHF
channels to warn approaching aircraft.
   ``That is useless for the Airbus, because he is on VHF,'' he
said. ``We heard the Navy every day; they did not announce a
warning on VHF.''
   Peroussi said transponders on the plane emitted signals ``only
in a civilian mode, not a military mode.''' The Pentagon said the
Vincennes received both types of signals from the plane.
   A plane carrying the remains of 71 of the victims had to abort
its takeoff on Wednesday when some of the coffins toppled over
inside the plane, the Tribune reported. It said about 12 Western
reporters were aboard.
   The pilot of the C-130 braked to a halt just before takeoff, the
newspaper said. The plane was en route to Tehran, it said.
   Iranian officials showed the bodies of the victims to reporters,
including cutting open one body bag and displaying a woman holding
a baby in her arms, the paper said.
</TEXT>
