<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     07-07 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks And Dollar Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices fell on the Tokyo Stock Exchange today and
the dollar slipped.
   Dealers attributed the yen's rise to fears that the U.S. trade
deficit may grow and Japanese official statements against letting
the dollar appreciate further.
   The dollar closed at 132.40 yen, down 1.13 yen from Wednesday's
close. Its high for the day was 132.98 yen and its low was 131.65.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues lost 38.47 points or 0.13 percent to move to
27,728.13. It had gained 189.43 points Wednesday on near-record
trading volume of 2.8 billion. Today's volume was 2 billion shares.
   A broker for Vickers da Costa, who spoke on condition he not be
identified, said concerns about U.S. trade figures to be released
next week put pressure on the dollar.
   He also said there was more confidence in the market after
Japanese officials said they wouldn't let the dollar appreciate
much more.
   ``If the dollar gets much stronger, you could well see
intervention,'' he said.
   An exchange dealer at the Bank of Tokyo said the market's mood
was bearish toward the dollar amid relatively quiet trading.
   ``The exchange rates are moving toward adjustment,'' said the
dealer, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The dollar hit 134.85 yen Monday, its highest closing rate since
Nov. 24. It had risen rapidly by nearly 10 yen in the previous
three weeks.
</TEXT>
