<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     07-07 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0488</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORTHGLENN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Baby, the eight-foot Burmese python
missing for three months, has been found, much to the shock of a
new tenant in the apartment that Baby's owner had vacated.
   ``I guess (she) opened up the drawer to do something and thereal control
officer Paul Ranes said
Wednesday.
   Ranes answered the call and was greeted by two shaken women.
   Baby was a bit more calm.
   ``It just looked at me,'' Ranes said. ``It didn't do anything.''
   It took police several hours to track down Baby's owner, Molly
McCoy.
   It all began in April, shortly after McCoy's boyfriend gave her
the python as an Easter gift. The snake was given the run of the
apartment while McCoy arranged to have a 100-gallon custom tank
built for the snake. But Baby vanished.
   Animal experts scoured the apartment, but they found no trace of
the 60-pound snake. They guessed that Baby had slithered down the
toilet or found her way under some cupboards and into the walls.
   For days, police answered calls from mothers who were afraid to
let their children outside.
   Officer Mark Forsyth said the mothers had little to fear because
anything larger than a poodle is probably not on a python's menu.
   After a while, McCoy gave up Baby for lost and moved out of the
complex in early May.
   Police said Wednesday the python had not eaten in four or five
months.
   McCoy finally retrieved her pet, but the reunion was subdued.
McCoy remarked that Baby was thin and told reporters that she might
try to sell her to a breeder.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ASHFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials from the towns of Ashford and
Willington couldn't see the boundary markers for the trees, but are
still hoping to ``walk the line'' to settle a longstanding border
dispute once fall arrives.
   Officials of the rural northeastern Connecticut towns decided to
resort to the method used for centuries by New England farmers to
re-establish property lines each spring after being told that an
engineer's survey of the 20 acres of disputed land would cost about
$40,000.
   They tried Wendesday night, but had to abandon the effort when
they discovered heavy woods made it too difficult to get their
bearings.
   ``If we're going to actually do any walking, we've decided we
have to do it when there aren't any leaves on the trees, because
it's just too hard to see anything at all,'' said Ashford First
Selectwoman Paula Faulkner.
   The officials did locate one of the key markers during their
abbreviated walk Wednesday night. They expect to continue the
exercise in September or October, said Willington First Selectman
Carlton Csiki.
   ``It's a country problem, we're country people and we'll most
likely resolve it in a country fashion,'' he said.
</TEXT>
