<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0557</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Showers, Thunderstorms Boom Over North Dakota</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Due to computer problems, the temperatures and weather
conditions from key cities around the nation are not available. A
lead to PM-Weatherpage Weather will move when and if they become
available.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showta today as
scattered thunderstorms fell from the central High Plains to New
Mexico.
   But a high-pressure system anchored over the lower Ohio Valley
kept skies mostly clear from the parched Plains to the East Coast.
   The rain fell over western and central North Carolina, and from
extreme western Nebraska and eastern Colorado to central and
southern New Mexico. Golf-ball size hail fell in Sutherland, Neb.
   Spotty showers fell along the Gulf Coast, scattered showers fell
along the central New England coast and thunderstorms were
clustered over extreme southern Florida.
   On Wednesday night, North Dakota thunderstorms dropped
baseball-size hail on Dickinson, while in Glen Ullin small hail and
gusty winds accompanied more than an inch of rain in less than an
hour.
   In Montana, thunderstorms dropped up to 3 inches of rain and
generated strong, gusty winds that broke windows and leveled a barn
near Ekalaka. Winds gusted to nearly 60 mph in Pueblo, Colo.
   The hot weather baking the Midwest spread into the Northeast on
Wednesday, as temperature records for July 6 up to 114 years old
were broken in 30 cities and tied in seven.
   The epic drought continued to plague much of the nation. Severe
to extreme drought conditions exist in much of California, sections
of Nevada, Oregon and Washington, the northern Plains, the upper
half of the Mississippi Valley, the lower Missouri Valley, much of
the Great Lakes region and the lower Ohio and Tennessee valleys.
   Although much-needed rain fell across the Plains late last week,
it only put a small dent in the dry spell. Parts of the northern
Rockies, the northern Plains, the Mississippi and lower Missouri
valleys, the Ohio and Tennessee valleys and the Gulf Coast have had
less than 75 percent normal rainfall.
   The worst-hit aras are the middle and lower Mississippi Valley,
the western lower Ohio Valley and the Tennessee Valley, where
rainfall has been less than half normal.
   No relief is in sight in the forecast for the next six to 10
days. Below-normal rainfall is expected for much of the nation,
with above-normal precipitation expected only along the central
Gulf Coast.
   Today's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
in northern Minnesota, the Great Plains, the southern Rockies, the
lower Mississippi Valley, Florida and the northern Atlantic Coast
states, with rain heaviest in Louisiana, southeast Texas and
southern Florida; hazy skies from New England to the Great Lakes;
and sunny skies prevailing in the rest of the nation.
   High temperatures were expected to be in the 80s or 90s in most
of the nation; near records of 95 to 100 degrees in the Great
Lakes; 100 to 110 degrees in the desert Southwest and California's
inland valleys; and in the 70s across parts of Montana, northern
Idaho and Washington state.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 38
degrees at Lake Yellowstone, Wyo., to 97 degrees at Phoenix, Ariz.
</TEXT>
