<1ST_LINE>r a PM-VesselSeized     07-07 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vessel Seized,0508</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coast Guard Captain Says Pot Ship Crew Destroyed Records</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATIA BLACKBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The captain of a Panamanian-registered vessel
carrying more than 72 tons of marijuana stalled a U.S. Coast Guard
boarding party as long as possible to destroy records, said the
captain of the Coast Guard cutter.
   The converted oil-rig supply ship Encounter Bay was towed into
Seattle by the Coast Guard cutter Boutwell and placed under tight
security Wednesday. The street value of the cargo was estimated by
the Coast Guard at $280 million.
   The Encounter Bay seemed to be heading for the Strait of Juan de
Fuca, the entry to Puget Sound and the main channel to Victoria and
Vancouver, British Columbia, said Cecil Allison, captain of the
Boutwell.
   The Boutwell's crew could read the word Panama in obscured
letters, and a few hours later, those aboard the 378-foot cutter
had permission from the Panamanian embassy to board the Encounter
Bay, Allison said.
   The Encounter Bay's crew yielded to a boarding party only after
the Boutwell fired machine guns at its rudder and engine room and
threatened to use cannon fire, Allison said.
   ``In my opinion,'' he said, the Encounter Bay captain ``was just
trying to prolong the engagement so he could destroy all the
records he could.
   ``It was a very organized operation, from the packaging all the
way through to the control of the ship and the cleaning out of the
boat's records.''
   Allison said they found no records indicating the origin or
destination of the vessel or who was in charge of the operation.
   The 180-foot Encounter Bay was not flying a flag when it was
spotted late last week about 600 miles offshore.
   The owner of the Encounter Bay was listed as Countess Shipping
Corp. of Panama, and the 18-member crew included three Americans,
one from England, one from New Zealand and 13 from Indonesia,
Thailand and Singapore.
   Sixteen appeared Wednesday before U.S. Magistrate John Weinberg
and were advised of their rights and possible charges against them,
and two others were to appear for the same purpose today when a
Thai interpreter would be available.
   All are held in custody pending a detention hearing on Monday,
when bail, if any, will be set, said deputy clerk Karen Lamborn.
The magistrate at that time would try to determine whether there
was probable cause to send the case to a grand jury, she said.
   If it can be proved the ship was headed for the United States,
crew members could prison terms of a few
years to life, said Gary Liming, U.S. Drug Enforcement
Administration special agent-in-charge.
   The Encounter Bay's crew was cooperative but not talkative,
Allison said. He estimated there was 72 tons of high-grade
marijuana on board in about 8,000 ``bales'' packed into four large
shipping containers.
   Each ``bale,'' in a blue nylon sack, contained eight packets of
marijuana vacuum-sealed in double plastic wrappings.
</TEXT>
