<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     07-07 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls, Gold Rises In Europe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against major currencies in
moderate trading in Europe today. Gold prices were higher.
   Foreign exchange dealers said hectic dealings in East Asia had
calmed down before European markets opened and had not affected
dollar exchange levels.
   Investors in Japan were switching to Japanese yen in a flurry of
buying, dealers said.
   With the dollar trading in Europe at 1.80 West German marks to
1.83 West German marks, dealers said they did not expect much to
happen as the American currency was comfortable at that level. But
they said if the dollar moved higher than that, the central banks
were likely to intervene and sell dollars to bring exchange rates
back down.
   Italian markets reported currency dealing was very active with
many large commercial orders.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends before Europe's begins,
the dollar fell to a closing 132.40 Japanese yen from 133.53 yen at
Wednesday's close. In London later, the dollar was trading lower at
131.75 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Wednesday:
   _ 1.8162 West German marks, down from 1.8217
   _ 1.5090 Sw5135
   _ 6.1135 French francs, down from 6.1315
   _ 2.0481 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0515
   _ 1,347.00 Italian lire, down from 1,351.75
   _ 1.2050 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2168
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7190, more expensive for
buyers than Wednesday's late $1.7130.
   Gold opened in London at $438.75 an ounce, up from $436.75 bid
late Wednesday. At mid-morning, the city's five major bullion
dealers fixed a recommended price of $439.15.
   London bullion dealers described trading as moribund, blaming
uncertainty about inflation and the unlikelihood of much change in
dollar exchange rates.
   In Zurich, gold opened at $438.50 bid, up from Wednesday's late
$437.50. At noon the price had moved higher to $438.90 bid.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed higher at $441.62 bid, up from
$441.05 late Wednesday.
   Silver bullion rose in London to a bid $6.94 a troy ounce, up
from $6.77 late Wednesday.
</TEXT>
