<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 0705EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Blind-Airlines     07-07 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Blind-Airlines,0463</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blind Want To Be Treated Like Everyone Else On Airlines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH SHOGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A blind woman who was removed from an airplane in
a dispute over seating and safety instructions says she wral rules may
not prevent other blind people from
being harassed.
   ``When I walk in an airport, I don't know what's going to
happen, but I know that it's likely to be demeaning and
humiliating,'' Peggy Pinder, an officer of the National Federation
of the Blind, said Wednesday at the federation's annual meeting.
   The U.S. Transportation Department has proposed nine rules to
end airline discrimination against disabled people. The rules were
outlined at the conference by Matthew Scocozza, the department's
assistant secretary for policy.
   But Ms. Pinder challenged Scocozza, saying a clause in one of
the rules could make it possible for airlines to continue barring
blind passengers from sitting in emergency exit rows _ a practice
the federation has criticized as discriminatory.
   Under one proposed rule, no passenger could be required to sit
in a certain area of the plane, ``except where required by an FAA
(Federal Aviation Administration) safety rule,'' Scocozza told a
predominantly blind audience of more than 1,000.
   Scocozza said in a speech to the convention that he agreed with
the federation's position that many blind people are capable of
sitting in an exit row and handling an emergency situation.
   But United Airlines spokesman Joe Hopkins said his airline does
not seat blind passengers in an exit row because of fears they
could not assess an emergency situation as well as a sighted person.
   ``Let's say there's a fire on the other side (of the door), a
blind person wouldn't be able to see that,'' Hopkins said.
   In April, James Gashel, an officer of the federation, was taken
into custody on a charge of criminal trespass after he refused to
leave his seat in an emergency exit row of an United flight.
   Ms. Pinder said she was removed from a Midway Airlines plane on
March 31 and arrested because she refused to move from a seat in
the smoking section to the front of the plane.
   But Sandra Allen, a spokeswoman for Midway, said Ms. Pinder was
arrested because she refused to listen to a special safety briefing
the airline requires for all disabled passengers.
   The federation's executive director, Kenneth Jernigan, told the
convention that, ``no blind person anywhere in the country can
board a plane without fear of harassment, public humiliation and
possibly arrest and bodily injury.''
   Scocozza said the department's new rules may help to change that
situation.
   ``If nothing else, it's a start that's 30 years too late,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
