<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 1228EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--GasLeak     07-07 0194</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Gas Leak,0198</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gas Leak Sickens 190 People</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Benzene gas leaked from a factory in a
residential part of Shanghai and sickened more than 190 people,
including nine who had to be hospitalized, an official report said
Thursday.
   Most complained of feeling dizzy, weak and short of breath after
the toxic gas spread Wednesday over Shanghai's Shenjiadu
neighborhood, the China Daily said.
   Doctors said the nine taken to the Putuo Central Hospital were
not seriously ill, the paper said.
   About 300 families live in the neighborhood, which is surrounded
by half a dozen chemical factories. The report said a preliminary
investigation pinpointed the Shanghai No. 9 Chemical Fibre Factory
as the likely culprit.
   It said Shenjiadu residents have been complaining about air
pollution for a long time, and the city has agreed to move them
from the area. However, construction of new housing has been slowed
by lack of money, the paper said.
   China's cities are among the most seriously polluted in the
world due to an intermingling of factories and apartment buildings,
frequent lack of emission controls and heavy reliance on coal for
home heating and to run machinery.
</TEXT>
