<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Sununu-Bush     07-07 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sununu-Bush,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>N.H. Governor Says ``Refugees'' Fleeing Dukakis' Massachusetts</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Gov. John Sununu of New Hampshire
asserted Thursday that tens of thousands of ``refugees'' are
fleeing neighboring Massachusetts each year to escape the policies
of Democratic Gov. Michael Dukakis.
   ``You ought to stand at the border and talk to them when they
come into New Hampshire,'' Sununu, who is active in Republican
George Bush's presidential campaign, said in remarks at the
National Press Club.
   ``The state of Massachusetts in fact has the reality of between
50,000 and 100,000 leaving the state in the last five or six years.
We in New Hampshire in fact get 10,000 to 20,000 refugees a year
who escape with their families,'' Sununu said.
   Sununu said people are leaving Massachusetts, where the likely
Democratic presidential nominee is governor, because ``they have
perceived mismanagement, they have perceived a propensity to tax,
they're not happy with the quality of service they receive.''
   The New Hampshire governor has been speaking around the country
on Dukakis' record as Massachsuetts governor as part of Bush's
surrogate speaker program.
   ``If Michael Dukakis fulfills his promise to do for the rest of
the nation what he did for Massachusetts, then we are in serious
trouble,'' Sununu asserted, saying Massachsetts ranks low in job
creation.
   ``Massachusetts is also the stolen-car capital of the United
States. I wouldn't run around bragging about that,'' he said.
   On another matter, Sununu said in response to a question that
``there would be a plus to considering a woman'' for the No. 2 spot
on the Republican ticket. He contended that the Democrats have
excluded women from consideration this year on their ticket.
   Sununu said Sen. Nancy Kassebaum, R-Kan., former Transportation
Secretary Elizabeth Dole and former United Nations Ambassador Jeane
Kirkpatrick as three Republican women who would make outstanding
vice presidents.
   At the same time, Sununu said ``there would be a plus'' to
considering a GOP vice presidential choice from a particular region
of the country _ New England.
   Asked if he were seeking the vice presidential post, or a
Cabinet job in a Bush administration, Sununu said: ``I have a very
short horizon. My horizon now is getting George Bush elected. After
that, I'll get my resume in order.''
</TEXT>
