<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0432 07-07 0820</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0432,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Won't Promise To Put Blacks, Women In Cabinet, Despite
Hispanic Pledge</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 5 grafs after 4th graf pvs, `He said,' with comment
from Hispanic House members; edits for transition.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush says he will not
promise to put blacks, women and other minorities in his Cabinet if
elected president, even though he has made that commitment to
Hispanic Americans.
   ``I feel strongly there should be an Hispanic in a Bush
Cabinet,'' the vice president said Wednesday after addressing a
Hispanic convention in Dallas.
   ``Other groups have been represented in the Cabinet and
Hispanics have not,'' said Bush, certain to be the Republican
presidential nominee.
   He said his promise to Hispanics was a one-shot pledge and that
he would not go around the country making promises to special
interest groups.
   On Capitol Hill, a group of Hispanic House members today
denounced Bush's promise to name a Hispanic to his cabinet.
   ``George Bush is making a last-ditch effort to make up for eight
years of Republican neglect,'' said Rep. Albert Bustamante,
D-Texas, chairman of the Congressional Hispanic Caucus.
   Rep. Matthew Martinez, D-Calif., said he had no confidence in
Bush making a meaningful appointment, saying the problem with the
current administration is who they name to visible government posts.
   ``They are tokens, people who they're able to manipulate and
control. They do not believe in civil rights,'' he said.
   Bustamante said likely Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis, who
also has promised to name Hispanics to high government posts, ``can
back up his statement with his record.''
   Today, Bush invades Dukakis' backyard to woo an ethnic group
close to the heart of the Massachusetts governor. The vice
president will speak in Boston tonight before a Greek Orthodox
diocesean dinner. Aides said he would talk about the importance of
religion.
   Underscoring the political importance of Hispanics, Bush spoke
in Dallas before the convention of the League of United Latin
American Citizens (LULAC), the largest and oldest Hispanic civic
group.
   Although Bush does not speak Spanish, he arranged for his son,
Jeb, to fly in from Florida to make a pitch for him. Jeb Bush, who
speaks Spanish and is married to a woman from Mexico, is popular
with Hispanic groups.
   Pledging to put a Hispanic in his Cabinet, Bush said, it was
``good to acknowledge that some things are, at this point, owed.''
He said his promise was something ``I have never made before, to
anyone, to any group.''
   However, he said, ``It is time. It is time and it's long
overdue, and that is a solemn pledge.''
   Dukakis said Bush's vow to name a Hispanic to the Cabinet was
``about a year too late.'' Dukakis made the same pledge in June
1987 to the LULAC convention, held last year in Corpus Christi,
Texas. Dukakis was to address the group on Thursday, followed by
Jesse Jackson on Friday.
   At a news conference, Bush said he would not make similar
promises to other groups.
   ``I will be very open-minded and broad-based in who I select to
serve in my Cabinet, but I'm addressing myself to righting a wrong
that has been out there for many years.''
   Asked if he would make a similar promise to Asian Americans,
Bush said, ``I'd have to go back there and research that out.''
   Oscar Moran, the Hispanic group's president, said of Bush, ``He
attracted the attention of some voters who already decided on
Dukakis. Now they will pay attention to him.''
   But Tony Bonilla, an influential Democrat whom Bush singled out
by name as a person he had tried to recruit for the GOP, was
unmoved by the vice president's promise to put a Hispanic in the
Cabinet.
   Bonilla said it was ``a little patronizing'' for Bush to make
such a statement after serving eight years in the Reagan
administration without a Hispanic in the inner circle.
   ``The vice president needs to say to the president right now,
`We have goofed. We have not reciprocated to the Hispanic
community''' for their support, said Bonilla, a former chairman of
LULAC and the head of the National Hispanic Leadership Conference.
   Bush said he had discussed the idea of a Hispanic in the Cabinet
with President Reagan, but he added, ``I'm not president of the
United States.''
   His commitment was a measure of the political importance of
Hispanics, particularly in key battleground states like Texas,
California and Florida which have a large Spanish-speaking
population.
   Since 1980, the number of Hispanics in the United States has
increased 30 percent, to 19 million, accounting for about 7.9
percent of the nation's population.
   Urging Hispanics to switch to the Republican Party, Bush said,
``I think you belong with us. And don't let anyone take you, or
your support, for granted.''
   Many people in the audience did not applaud, an indication they
were not swayed by his appeal.
</TEXT>
