<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 1255EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ElNinoPrediction     07-07 0687</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-El Nino Prediction,650</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For Release 6:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<HEAD>Scientists Report Successful El Nino Predictions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Last year's mild El Nino, a puzzling
phenomenon in which global weather disruptions follow a warming of
the Pacific, was predicted by three different climate models,
according to scientists who hope they can now serve distant warning
of future recurrences.
   ``Looking at the results ... we feel there is a good chance of
being able to assess these things as much as a year ahead. And over
time we expect to get better,'' said Stephen Zebiak of the Columbia
University's Lamont-Doherty Geological Laboratory.
   ``Time will show how much value these kinds of models and
predictions can have. Until there is a consensus on that, we don't
expect to see governments taking action readily based on them,
although I do think that eventually that will happen,'' Zebiak said
Thursday in a telephone interview.
   ``It's a new kind of game, really, a lot of people are still
quite skeptical about it.''
   The successful predictions of the 1986-87 El Nino are being
formally reported in Friday's edition of Science magazine.
   El Ninos, still not fully understood, are events that appear to
affect weather around the world. One that occurred in 1982-83,
described as the strongest in this century, was blamed for an
estimated 1,500 deaths and damage of $2 billion to $8 billion
worldwide.
   The 1986-87 El Nino had much less impact, although some unusual
weather was reported, including heavy rains in coastal Peru and
drought in India and the Pacific Northwest of the United States.
   The events are preceded by unusually warm water temperatures in
the Pacific and changes in barometric pressure over that ocean.
   Zebiak said the climate studies currently show cooler than
normal Pacific Ocean temperatures _ the opposite of an El Nino _
for at least the balance of this year. These cold events do not
seem to have the climate impact of the warmer El Ninos, he added.
   El Ninos take their name from the Spanish word for child, a
reference to the Christ Child. This was coined by Peruvian
fishermen to refer to the recurring phenomenon, which sharply
reduced their fish supply and was often first noticed at Christmas
time.
   Scientists, combining that name with a reference to changes in
Pacific and Indian Ocean air pressure, usually use the term ENSO,
for El Nino-Southern Oscillation.
   The three different climate models that predicted the 1986-87 El
Nino were:
   _The Lamont-Doherty model developed by Mark Cane, Zebiak and
Sean Dolan. This model uses a computer to calculate changes in the
ocean and atmosphere, and their relations with one another. Termed
a ``dynamic'' model, meaning it uses mathematical formulas to
calculate changes, it predicted the El Nino more than a year ahead
of time.
   _A model based primarily on changing ocean conditions, coupled
with unusual wind currents, developed by James O'Brien and D.
Legler of Florida State University. This combined dynamic and
statistical information and can issue predictions a few months in
advance, Zebiak explained.
   _A statistical model using wind patterns and sea-level air
pressure readings over the Pacific and Indian oceans, which can
give predictions with lead times of 3 to 9 months. This pair or
related models was developed by Timothy Barnett and Nicholas E.
Graham at Scripps Institute of Oceanography in La Jolla, Calif.
   In the case of the 1986-87 El Nino, all three models wound up
making the same prediction, just at different times, Zebiak said.
   ``It is interesting that different models, which are based on
quite different kinds of approaches, are showing consistency. I
think it is basically encouraging, another piece of evidence that
there really is a robust kind of signal here, which we are
capturing in different ways.''
   ``The fact is that these kind of forecasts are a reality now,
they will continue. We and the other people are doing it sort of
routinely now. What remains to be assessed is the kind of feeling
for exactly how reliable they are going to be in the situations
that nature throws our way,'' Zebiak said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880707-0066 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 1256EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SeattleRing     07-07 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Seattle Ring,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seattle Opera Won't Revive Ring Cycle Before 1991</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Seattle Opera is putting off its next
mounting of Richard Wagner's four-opera Ring Cycle for at least two
more years, company officials have announced.
   ``Der Ring des Niebelungen,'' a staple of the company since
1975, won't be revived before 1991, general director Speight
Jenkins said Wednesday.
   Instead, the Seattle Opera will mount a production of Wagner's
``Die Meistersinger'' next year and Prokofiev's ``War and Peace''
in 1990, he said.
   He also announced the company balanced its 1987-88 budget ``with
a slight surplus.''
   Jenkins had planned to revive the Ring Cycle _ ``Das
Rheingold,'' ``Die Walkure,'' ``Siegfried,'' and
``Gotterdammerung'' _ next summer after a one-year break in annual
productions that had made the Opera House a mecca for Wagner
devotees from around the world.
   The Kennedy Center in Washington, D.C., is in the final stages
of negotiation to host the Deutsche Oper Berlin's production of the
operas next June. In May, the Metropolitan Opera of New York will
present its new Ring.
   As a result, Jenkins said, Wagner fans would be drawn east next
year.
   In 1990 the San Francisco Opera plans to revive its highly
successful 1985 production of the operas.
   ``We will do the `Ring' in 1991, unless a cataclysm strikes me
or this company,'' Jenkins pledged.
   The production of the rarely heard ``War and Peace'' is planned
in a collaboration with the Soviet Union in conjunction with the
Goodwill Games. Negotiations for that production have yet to be
concluded.
   An extended absence of the Wagnerian retelling of Teutonic
legend won't mean the loss of Seattle's reputation as a center for
Wagner, but the expensive production can't be taken for granted,
either, Jenkins said.
   ``The Ring is not just going to be there, like Mount Rainier,''
he said. ``You have to work to earn and fund a Ring.''
   He said it would be twice as expensive to revive the Ring cycle
as to produce ``Meistersinger,'' which is expected to have a budget
of about $1.2 million. The last new production of the opera in the
United States was in 1977.
   To open its 25th season, the company is giving four performances
this month of ``Satyagraha,'' an account of Mohandas Gandhi's years
as a young lawyer in South Africa by the minimalist composer Philip
Glass.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
