<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Cuba-Dissident     07-07 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cuba-Dissident,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuban Human Rights Activist Allowed to Visit United States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In an unusual gesture, the Cuban government
has allowed a human rights activist and former political prisoner
to make a monthlong visit to the United States.
   Elizardo Sanchez, head of the Cuban Human Rights and National
Reconciliation Commission, said that he believes he is the first
dissident to be given permission to leave Cuba for purposes other
than emigration since the start of the revolution 29 years ago.
   The main purpose of Sanchez's U.S. visit is to meet with his
wife and children, who came to the United States aboard the Mariel
boat lift in 1980. He plans to return to Cuba in August.
   Sanchez discussed the human rights situation in Cuba in measured
terms because he believes that strong language could jeopardize his
hopes for positive changes on the island.
   ``We don't want to corner the government,'' he said.
   Sanchez spoke to a reporter Thursday shortly after his arrival
in Washington from Miami.
   Sanchez, 44, is a former professor of philosophy and the history
of philosophy who was stripped of his job in 1968 because of his
unorthodox political views.
   Since then, he has spent seven years in prison because of his
activities as a dissident. He now works in a municipal library in
Havana, although for many years the only jobs he could find were as
a mechanic and a laundry employee, he said.
   He was last imprisoned in the fall of 1986 after speaking with
reporters from two West European news agencies. The reporters were
expelled from the country, and Sanchez said he spent eight months
in solitary confinement before his release last summer.
   Sanchez said he had applied repeatedly for permission to leave
the country over the past eight years but his requests were
ignored. In April, he finally got the go-ahead after he sent a
telegram to President Fidel Castro seeking his assistance.
   Asked if he is grateful for Castro's help, Sanchez said that
permission to leave one's homeland is a right specified in the
Universal Declaration of Human Rights and that an expression of
gratitude would therefore not be appropriate.
   ``It's a right that all should have,'' he said.
   During his U.S. visit, Sanchez said he expects to meet with
representatives of the human rights groups, including Amnesty
International and Americas Watch, but he added that he is not
seeking publicity.
   He described the human rights situation in Cuba as
``precarious'' and said the lack of individual freedoms is the most
difficult problem.
   ``The current administration (in Cuba) has a lot to do to
improve the situation,'' he said.
   Asked why he doesn't plan to remain in the United States,
Sanchez said there are enough Cubans outside the island who call
attention to human rights practices there.
   ``The most important thing (for me) is to remain inside Cuba,''
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
