<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Teachers-Notebook Bjt   07-07 0794</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teachers-Notebook, Bjt,0827</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>REPORTER'S NOTEBOOK: Teacher Conventions _ Two Styles, Similar
Directions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Federation of Teachers and
archrival National Education Association wound up their annual
conventions apparently closer than ever to agreeing on workable
approaches to school reform.
   But don't tell that to NEA President Mary Hatwood Futrell or AFT
President Albert Shanker, who seem far more comfortable nursing
their rivalry than contemplating a ceasefire.
   NEA's 8,227 delegates meeting here this week, and AFT's 3,000
delegates in San Francisco, endorsed reform proposals aimed at
freeing teachers to experiment. The separate schemes differed in
detail, not spirit.
   The AFT proposed creating thousands of ``schools within
schools'' where small clusters of teachers could try out their
ideas. The NEA would designate at least one entire school district
in each state as ``learning laboratories.''
   Asked if her plan signaled a rare consensus with the AFT,
Futrell flinched.
   The AFT plan was ``not a new idea,'' she said, and was ``more
narrow than what we proposed.''
   And Shanker ridiculed NEA officials who he said still believe
that money alone will solve education's problems.
   The AFT-NEA war goes on.
</TEXT>
