<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WildfiresRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0571 07-07 0689</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wildfires Rdp, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0571,0702</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wildfires Scorch Wilderness Lands in West, Alaska</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `Firefighters in ...,' with 1 graf to UPDATE
progress in fighting Zion National Park blaze; INSERTS 2 grafs
after 9th, `On Sunday ...,' with 3,500-acre fire in southern Utah.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Rushmore Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Wildfires crackled through the country's parched forests,
including a 10,000-acre blaze that threatened Mount Rushmore
National Memorial and an 118,000-acre fire that burned within 10
miles of the trans-Alaska oil pipeline.
   More than 1,000 people had been evacuated by early today from
the Custer State Park fire in South Dakota near the granite
monument to four presidents.
   In Alaska, hundreds of firefighters battled three of the state's
more serious wildfires as weather forecasts continued to offer
scant hope for rain.
   The fire burning near the pipeline on the Yukon Flats National
Wildlife Refuge grew from 110,000 acres on Monday, Bureau of Land
Management spokeswoman Sue Mitchell said. About 80 firefighters
were assigned to the fire that is one of three the BLM either
manned or monitored on the refuge.
   ``What they're trying to do is stop it from getting any closer
to the pipeline,'' Mitchell said.
   The pipeline is made of heavy-gauge steel and ``is not
susceptible to serious damage from a fire of that nature,'' said
Tom Brennan, a spokesman for Alyeska Pipeline Service Co. But, he
said, ``We would rather not have it in the area of a pump station,
because those are manned, for one thing.''
   Firefighters in Utah finished cutting fire lines today around an
850-acre blaze that has blackened oak, brush and Ponderosa pine in
Zion National Park. They expected to have the fire contained by
tonight, officials said.
   The fire began June 19 and was allowed to burn in a small
``conditional area'' in accordance with park policy allowing
natural fires to take their course, said Chief Ranger Bob Andrew.
   On Sunday, however, winds gusting to 60 mph fanned the flames
out of the conditional area, and up to 200 firefighters were
brought in.
   In southern Utah, 45 firefighters battled a 3,500-acre fire that
broke out late Wednesday on Bureau of Land Management and private
land about three miles north of Beryl near the Nevada border.
   Spokeswoman Eulail Pickering said the fire was 85 percent
contained and crews anticipated full containment later today.
   Another fire in wilderness area that also began June 19, was
being held in check at 3,400 acres in south-central Montana. The
lightning-caused fire was allowed to burn in the Absaroka Beartooth
Wilderness until it flared up over the Independence Day weekend and
burned more than 1,600 acres.
   Smokejumpers worked the north face of the fire Wednesday while
four helicopters dropped water and foam, said information officer
Jo Barnier in the Billings Interagency Fire Center.
   Wyoming firefighters, aided by cooler temperatures and a drop in
winds overnight, contained a 1,300-acre fire in the Bridger-Teton
National Forest at 6 a.m. today, forest officials said.
   Two volunteer firefighters were injured, one seriously, battling
the blaze, said forest spokesman Fred Kingwill.
   ``We still have a ways to go before we'll call it controlled,''
he said, adding that the wind in the next few days will determine
the future of the fire.
   Officials originally said the fire had burned up 1,500 acres but
downgraded the acreage to 1,300 after fire lines were dug and the
blaze could be reassessed.
   In Yellowstone National Park, three fires covering nearly 1,900
acres of backcountry still were burning Wednesday. The fires, one
covering 1,800 acres in the northwestern corner of the park and two
others near Shoshone and Lewis lakes in the southern part of the
park, were not threatening any structures and were being allowed to
burn themselves out.
   Farther east, six small forest fires burned on in northeast
Pennsylvania. Three of the fires were caused by weekend fireworks
and three by arson, said Lackawanna District Forester Anthony
Santoli in Scranton.
   The largest fire burned more than 75 acres of woodland on
Montage Mountain, near Moosic, Santoli said. The other large fire
charred about 60 acres at Campbells Ledge, near Duryea.
</TEXT>
