<1ST_LINE>r a AM-OrphanedPorpoise     07-07 0204</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Orphaned Porpoise,0210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Zoo Workers Try To Save Orphaned Porpoise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers at the Point Defiance Zoo and
Aquarium are trying to keep alive a newborn harbor porpoise
orphaned on a beach.
   The pup, named ``Indy'' because it was discovered on
Independence Day, is believed to be only the second immature harbor
porpoise kept alive in captivity, said Lily Moore, zoo information
officer.
   A pup found last year at Point Defiance died within four months,
and zoo officials said chances for the new baby porpoise's survival
also are slim.
   Two young girls playing on the beach at the Necanicum River
estuary near Seaside, Ore., found the pup.
   The umbilicus _ the navel which quickly disappears _ was evident
and the pup's dorsal fin was flaccid, which indicates a young age,
Moore said.
   ``It's in very good shape, considering all that it's been
through,'' she said. ``It conceivably could have been born on the
day the girls found it.''
   The porpoise arrived at the zoo Tuesday afternoon, measuring 33
inches long and weighing 16 pounds. Harbor porpoises will grow to
about 5 feet long, Moore said.
   Visitors can't see the harbor porpoise because officials are
trying to minimize stress on it.
</TEXT>
