<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 1333EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LightningSurvivor     07-07 0205</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lightning Survivor,0208</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman: Lucky After Twice Being Thrown By Lightning Strikes Near
Her</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW PORT RICHEY, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's enough to make you swear off
water.
   Mildred Forney was in her kitchen six years ago, with her hand
on the faucet when lightning struck just outside. ``I guess it went
through the pipes or something, but it threw me all over the
kitchen, into the refrigerator and the table and onto the floor.''
   On Wednesday, Mrs. Fortney, 63, was outside placing a pail to
catch rainwater for her plants, when ``I felt a force pick me up
and it threw me across the carport. I don't know what the lightning
hit, if it was the ground next to me or the bucket. But it really
threw me, and I wound up on my hands and knees facing the opposite
direction.''
   Mrs. Fortney was treated at HCA-New Port Richey Hospital for
knee and ankle injuries and released. She also complained of a hot
and tingling sensation in her arm, and paramedics said her blood
pressure was high.
   ``It really shakes you up,'' she said. ``It's a terrible feeling
because you have no control over it. That was definitely an
expensive bucket of rainwater.''
</TEXT>
