<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Greece-Heat     07-07 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-Heat,0472</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heat Blamed for 15 Deaths, Sends More Than 400 to Hospital</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK QUINN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A five-day heat wave blamed for 15 deaths
combined with heavy smog in the Athens basin Thursday to send more
than 500 people to hospitals, most with heart and breathing
problems.
   Hospitals around the country were place on alert. Temperatures
in Athens reached 106 degrees Fahrenheit at 2:45 p.m. for the
second straight day.
   Yugoslavia, Greece's northern neighbor, reported at least 26
people dead in a heat wave that has gripped Belgrade for a week.
The temperature soared to 104 degrees Wednesday.
   The Greek national weather service said temperatures were not
expected to drop until Sunday.
   ``The smog of Athens sent 496 people to hospital with cardiac
and respiratory problems as pollution reached murderous levels,''
said a statemment by the Panhellenic Center for Ecologic Studies.
   A report from the National Center for Emergency Help said 404
people were treated as outpatients for heart or breathing
difficulties and 92 were hospitalized. It said hospitals admitted
25 people suffering from heat stroke.
   Nikos Benardis, the Athens coroner, said the heat contributed to
the deaths of 15 elderly people.
   ``Most of them had previous heart conditions and were on
medication,'' he said. ``The heat certainly aggravated the
condition of those with cardiac problems that caused their deaths.''
   Soaring temperature have caused a shortage of electric fans and
hundreds of people lined up at appliance stores for the few that
remained.
   ``We had 60 fans in the store and sold them all within minutes
of opening. There are people who have been waiting two or three
days to buy one,'' said Efthimios Arevas, sales manager of a large
appliance stores.
   He reported receiving orders from ``hospitals and even the army
for 30 fans that we don't have. It's worse than last year.''
   One year ago, more than 900 people died in a 10-day heat wave.
Lack of air conditioning in city hospitals was blamed for many of
the deaths.
   Sismanogleion Hospital said crews were installing more
air-conditioning units and the medical staff was on 24-hour alert.
   The environmental study center said smoke, nitrogen dioxide and
total suspended particles in the Athens atmosphere were four to
five times danger levels.
   No figures were available from the government Center for
Pollution Control because a bomb wrecked its offices early
Wednesday. The leftist group Revolutionary Popular Struggle said it
planted the bomb to protest environmental pollution.
   Athens has been plagued for years by the brown mass of
pollutants that forms in the lower atmosphere on warm, still days
and is known as the nefos, the Greek word for cloud. Government
anti-pollution measures introduced in January have failed to
eliminate it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
