<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 1340EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-GOP-Family     07-07 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-GOP-Family,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Republicans Introduce Family Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Republican leaders unveiled an
``American Family Act'' on Thursday, saying they hoped the bill
would win Vice President George Bush's backing and influence issues
ranging from child care to gang-busting.
   ``It is not enough for Republicans to deride the failures of the
Great Society programs. We must provide a framework for change,''
House Republican Leader Bob Michel, R-Ill., said at a news
conference.
   The $2 billion package would provide federal support for
promising state, local and private programs designed to strengthen
the American family.
   Though they'll introduce the legislation in August, sponsors are
really shooting for action in the next Congress, said Rep. Dan
Coats, R-Ind., the principal author of the bill.
   Sponsors also want to make the bill part of the GOP platform and
are hoping Bush, the all-but-certain GOP presidential nominee, will
endorse it in whole or in part. One of the sponsors is Rep. Jerry
Lewis, R-Calif., co-chairman of the Republican Convention Platform
Committee.
   Specifically, the bill contains the following initiatives:
   _Up to $50 million to states for experiments in school-based
management, in which teachers play a major management role and
districts have greater budget and curriculum flexibility.
   _$50 million to promote unrestricted school enrollment policies
aimed at forcing schools to compete.
   _Up to $450 million for ``bootstrap schools'' which have
predominantly minority or low-income students.
   _$600,000 for ``character education'' pilot programs and
promotion. Grants would be available only to schools that require
the Pledge of Allegiance daily.
   _College savings bonds, with tax-exempt interest if proceeds
were used for tuition and other costs associated with higher
education of the taxpayer, spouse, child or dependent. Such
legislation has already been introduced with the backing of Reagan
and Bush.
   _A $1.3 billion proposal targeting aid to low-income working
families, already introduced by Rep. Tom Tauke, R-Iowa,
   _A multimillion-dollar program to fight gang warfare, including
$5 million to encourage states to adopt restitution laws, $7
million to states with laws allowing courts to find parents liable
for restitution, $3.5 million for law enforcement areas that want
to set up a tracking system for juvenile offenders. Also, there
would be grants for community reclamation and other projects.
   _Child support enforcement initiatives, including mandatory
automatic wage withholding and a requirement that at least 17
percent of a non-custodial parent's income go to support one child.
   _Allowing public housing authorities to charge no more than
fair-market rent for housing. Currently, families pay 30 percent of
their gross incomes.
   _$10 million in start-up money for projects that coordinate
services to high risk children.
   The Republicans said they are planning a second family package
to address the issues of housing, work and family, and possibly
health. It is unclear, they said, whether the next bill will
include a provision guaranteeing new parents job-protected leave.
   ``There's a lot of controversy about it,'' Coats said of such a
requirement for parental leave, an idea promoted by Democrats and
some Republicans but strongly opposed by business. ``We've resisted
the temptation to pick up a politically charged issue and throw
something out there that we're not 100 percent comfortable with.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
