<1ST_LINE>u w PM-AilingThrifts     07-07 0214</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ailing Thrifts,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Thrift Regulators Double Texas Bailout Costs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government regulators more than doubled their
estimate today of how much it will cost to bail out Texas' ailing
savings and loans institutions, telling a House committee that it
now appears the bill will be $15.2 billion.
   Chairman M. Danny Wall of the Federal Home Loan Bank Board told
the House Banking Committee that to help pay for the bailouts, his
agency will raise an additional $12.3 billion, mostly by extending
the special assessment the thrifts now pay on their deposits.
   Panel chairman Fernand J. St Germain, D-R.I., asked Wall if he
envisioned needing taxpayers' help in footing the bill ``in the not
too distant future''. Wall responded, ``No, when you added `not too
distant future'.''
   The bank board had been saying that it expects the costs of
merging, selling or liquidating thrifts in Texas to be $7 billion.
   Wall also said he expected his agency to be able to raise $42.5
billion over the next decade for bailouts across the country, an
increase from earlier projections of $30.2 billion.
   Committee members complained that the regulators had been basing
their projections on rosey expectations.
   ``We need hard-nosed, tell-it-like-it-is analyses out of this
federal agency, not sugar-coated pablum,'' said St Germain.
</TEXT>
