<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 1359EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AlaskaStatehood     07-07 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Alaska Statehood,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Statehood Leader Has No Regrets on 30th Anniversary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Statehood didn't immunize Alaska from
hard times _ oil prices are down and there is no more boom in the
economy _ but a leader in the campaign for a 49th star on the flag
has no regrets.
   ``Statehood has done everything Alaskans said it would do for
them,'' Robert Atwood, chairman of the Alaska Statehood Committee,
said as the state marked one of its 30th birthdays.
   It was on July 7, 1958, that President Eisenhower signed the
Alaska statehood bill into law. Some consider the anniversary to be
June 30, the date in 1958 that Congress passed the bill to admit
the huge territory into the union. Still others cite Jan. 3, 1959,
when Eisenhower signed the proclamation admitting Alaska to the
United States.
   None of the dates is drawing much attention this year.
   The list of official Alaska holidays notes instead Seward's Day
in March and Alaska Day in October. Seward's Day marks the 1867
signing of the treaty by which the United States purchased Alaska
from the Russians. Alaska Day recognizes the formal transfer of the
territory and the raising of the flag at Sitka in 1867.
   The struggle for statehood spanned 10 years, said Atwood,
publisher of the Anchorage Times.
   ``We had our issues over statehood in Alaska: Would it be good
for Alaska and Alaskans,'' he said. ``But Congress wanted to know
would statehood be good for the nation. They didn't give a hoot
about what would be good for Alaska.''
   Politically, Atwood said, trying to gather votes among the
nation's lawmakers was ``like trying to line up 1,000 dominoes so
that when you knock one down, they all fall.''
   Representatives from some of the Southern states worried Alaska
would send Washington liberal congressmen who would bolster the
civil-rights movement, he said.
   ``Texas didn't want to lose the title of the biggest state,''
remembered Atwood, who moved to Alaska in 1935. ``They joked about
it, but it was a real concern to them.''
   He said opposition within Alaska came from the canned salmon
industry.
   ``They controlled the economics and the politics of the
territory,'' he said.
   With statehood accomplished, Alaska went through governmental
changes that Atwood believes helped lure investors north.
   Previously, he said, companies with money to stake were held
back by concerns about the amount of power exerted in Alaska by the
Secretary of the Interior. Before statehood, Atwood said, Alaska
was a colony run out of Seattle and Washington, D.C.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880707-0085 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 1402EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Shultz     07-07 0729</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz,0751</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Pledges U.S. Help on Refugee Problem</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz
told Southeast Asian leaders Thursday they do not stand alone in
dealing with the tide of refugees still fleeing Indochina 13 years
after the end of the war.
   ``The commitment of the United States to resolve the Indochinese
refugee problem is as strong today as it has been in the past,''
Shultz said. ``We have come a long way ... Now we solemnly recommit
ourselves to stay the course.''
   Shultz admitted a long-standing policy by Southeast Asians to
grant temporary asylum to the refugees was in jeopardy and proposed
a mix of strategies, including a Bangkok-based working group that
would ``craft new approaches.''
   Shultz spoke at the opening session of a three-day ``dialogue''
among the foreign ministers of the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations and close partners Japan, Australia, Canada, New Zealand,
the European Community and the United States.
   He arrived Wednesday at the start of a nine-country tour of Asia
amid tight security.
   Thai officials reinforced police and military security personnel
in the wake of the U.S. downing of an Iranian airliner in the
Persian Gulf on Sunday.
   Shultz told reporters traveling with him that the United States
was concerned and alert to the possibility of a response from Iran,
which he accused of supporting terrorism.
   Focusing on Cambodia, Shultz said the United States remained
``unalterably opposed'' to the Khmer Rouge returning to power in
that country. He urged strong support for resistance leader Prince
Norodom Sihanouk, with whom he confers Friday, and non-communist
groups fighting the Vietnamese in Cambodia.
   ``They represent the political alternative to the Vietnamese
occupation and the Khmer Rouge and are key to a Cambodian
settlement,'' Shultz said.
   He said continued pressure had to be exerted on Vietnam to
withdraw all its forces from Cambodia, but added: ``We look forward
to the time when Vietnam will rejoin the community of nations.''
   In a closed session, Shultz expressed ``cautious optimism''
about the results of talks this month in Jakarta among the warring
sides in Cambodia, State Department spokesman Charles Redman said.
Vietnam, Laos and ASEAN also are to take part in the talks
beginning July 25.
   ``We do not have an independent plan,'' the spokesman told
reporters. ``Our position is supportive of ASEAN.''
   ``The United States remains unalterably opposed to the Khmer
Rouge ever again taking control in Cambodia, and we believe it is
essential that any settlement have adequate safeguards to prevent
this,'' Shultz said.
   Foreign Minister Sosuke Uno of Japan called for an international
peacekeeping force in Cambodia and said his country would consider
funding and manning such a force.
   Vietnam's forces invaded Cambodia in late 1978, driving the
murderous Khmer Rouge from power and into the jungles where they
and two non-communist groups continue to battle the Vietnamese and
the pro-Hanoi government in Phnom Penh. Sihanouk leads the
three-party resistance.
   Shultz said Washington regards normalization of relations with
Vietnam in context of a solution in Cambodia. ``Vietnam must
realize that our commitment to a free and independent Cambodia is
unswerving,'' Shultz said.
   The secretary stressed that the issue of nearly 1,800 Americans
still listed as missing in action in Vietnam also continues ``to
divide our two peoples.''
   ``We believe it is critical for Vietnam to move on this issue
this year,'' he said.
   ``You do not stand alone,'' he said, referring to nations in
Asia providing first asylum to refugees from Vietnam, Laos and
Cambodia. Communist forces triumphed in those countries in 1975.
   Redman said Shultz's proposal for a refugee working group, which
would include ASEAN, the dialogue partners and the U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees, received favorable comments from some of
the delegates.
   Shultz also said the United States should discourage clandestine
flights from Vietnam, continue to resettle refugees and get Vietnam
to expand a U.N.-sponsored Orderly Departure Program.
   Facing a fresh surge of Vietnamese boat people, Thailand,
Malaysia and Hong Kong are adopting tougher measures. They claim
that most of the new arrivals are economic migrants rather than
people fleeing political persecution.
   In 1986 the United States accepted about 36,000 Indochinese
refugees who had sought temporary asylum in other parts of Asia.
This fiscal year, the number is about 29,500. Since 1975, more than
900,000 Indochinese refugees have settled in the United States.
</TEXT>
