<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CruisePreemie     07-07 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cruise Preemie,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parents Name Baby After Cruise Ship,Stop</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mother of a girl born
prematurely aboard a cruise ship in the Bahamas said Thursday
she'll take another cruise _ but she won't get pregnant again.
   ``This is the last one. This is enough,'' agreed husband Spencer
McCollum, as he and his wife told reporters they have named their
daughter Emera Cay to note the circumstances of her birth.
   The 2-pound, 11-ounce baby was born Wednesday, seven weeks
premature, in the infirmary of the Emerald Seas as the ship made
its stop at Little Stirrup Cay after leaving Nassau in the Bahamas.
Hence the name, Emera Cay.
   The baby was in serious but stable condition Thursday at Miami's
Childrens Hospital, said spokeswoman Ava Osle, who said it was too
early to predict how long the baby will be hospitalized.
   The mother, Wylene McCollum, said she wants to leave Broward
General Medical Center. Dr. Lheri Domond said Mrs. McCollum
probably will be released Friday.
   ``Everything is going great. I just want to hurry up and see how
she's doing,'' Mrs. McCollum said. ``I want to go home.''
   A cruise line spokesman said the McCollums will get another
cruise, free of charge, when they're ready.
   The Atlanta couple also has a 2-year-old daughter.
   The Emerald Seas, which makes regular runs from Miami to the
Bahamas, was anchored off Little Stirrup Cay on Wednesday morning
when Mrs. McCollum gave birth. The ship's crew radioed the Coast
Guard in Miami, and a helicopter equipped with an incubator
airlifted the family to two South Florida hospitals.
   ``The kid will be 6 years old before she realizes that storks
don't have rotary wings,'' said Coast Guard Chief Lou Parris.
   The McCollums, both 23, were taking a four-day cruise for their
anniversary, which is not until September. They took the cruise
early because of her pregnancy.
</TEXT>
