<DOCNO> AP880707-0090 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 1417EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Mars Bjt   07-07 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Mars, Bjt,0588</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Launch Unmanned Probe to Mars' Moon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union launched an unmanned probe
Thursday night on a six-month trip to Mars' moon, Phobos, for a
mission designed to pave the way for a manned voyage to the red
planet.
   The 180-foot-tall booster rocket spewed orange and blue flames
as it illuminated the nighttime sky at the Baikonur space center in
the Soviet Central Asian republic of Kazakhstan.
   The launch of the Proton rocket carrying the probe, Phobos I,
was carried live on Soviet television, which reported that the
spacecraft's flight was proceeding normally.
   More than a dozen nations are participating in the mission to
swoop close to the surface of Phobos and drop probes onto the
little, potato-shaped Martian moon that scientists say may hold
clues to how the universe was formed.
   Delegations from around the world gathered at Baikonur for the
launch of Phobos I, a joint East-West project to study the moon and
Mars itself.
   A companion probe, Phobos II, is scheduled for launch on July 12.
   If all goes well, the two spacecraft will enter the
gravitational pull of Mars in January 1989 and fall into orbit just
behind Phobos for a three-month remote study of the surface and
atmosphere of the planet. In April, the craft will drop out of
their orbit and swoop to within 30 yards of the moon's surface,
where they will release two small landers.
   The Soviet news agency Tass said Thursday that in one
experiment, a laser beam will be used to split a tiny piece of
Phobos' rocky surface and trap a specimen for close examination.
   One of the landers is expected to operate for about a year in
stationary position, sending back data. Another is designed to leap
around the little moon in 20-yard hops gathering soil samples and
analyzing them.
   This is the most sophisticated and ambitious of 18 Soviet and
U.S. unmanned missions to study Mars.
   Soviet space scientists have characterized the Phobos mission as
an important step toward a manned flight to Mars, which they hope
will be possible in the early 21st century.
   The Phobos probes will help map the surface of the planet ``in
order to choose a place for the future landing,'' said Vyacheslav
Balebanov of the Soviet Academy of Sciences' Space Research
Institute. ``Then, it is necessary to study the climate and soil
characteristics and find out whether oxygen should be taken from
Earth, or whether it can be gotten directly on the planet.''
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev has proposed that the United
States join in the prospective manned mission, but American
officials have been cool to the idea, saying it would be very
expensive and would require solutions to many difficult problems,
one of which is the problem of astronauts' physical deterioration
during long periods of weightlessness.
   Soviet space officials have put the cost of the Phobos mission
at $480 million.
   In addition to the Soviets, Austria, Bulgaria, Hungary, East
Germany, Ireland, Poland, Finland, France, West Germany,
Czechoslovakia, Switzerland, Sweden, the United States and the
European Space Agency are participating in the flight. The United
States, a late entry, will provide tracking data with its Deep
Space Network that can determine distances within yards and the
velocity of objects billions of miles from Earth.
   The Phobos craft also will carry a plaque commemorating the
moon's discovery by an American astronomer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
