<1ST_LINE>r p AM-BRF--HotelDispute     07-07 0148</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Hotel Dispute,160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Atlanta Labor Dispute Settled, Won't Disrupt Delegate Lodging</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A labor dispute that stood between about 1,000
Democratic National Convention delegates and their hotel rooms has
been settled, much to the relief of party officials scurrying for a
contingency plan.
   ``We're out of the pup-tent business,'' said Peter Kelly,
chairman of the California delegation, which had 700 rooms reserved
at the Atlanta Hilton & Towers, site of the dispute.
   The delegation, along with those from Louisiana, Tennessee and
Wyoming, had decided against crossing picket lines, which members
of the International Brotherhood of Firemen and Oilers had said
they would form if their contract dispute could not be resolved.
   Hilton General Manager Andre Shaefer said a one-year agreement
had been reached, but declined to give details.
   ``We came to an agreement, and that means no picketing,''
Shaefer said. ``It's something we didn't want.''
</TEXT>
