<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hostages     07-07 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hostages,0500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kidnappers Say Hostages' Fate Will Be Part of Revenge</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Airliner-Iran, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A radical Shiite Moslem group that holds
two American hostages said Thursday their fate will be part of
Iran's revenge for the shooting down of an Iranian airliner in
which 290 people were killed.
   ``Everybody knows that all the strong cards are still in our
hand, including the hostages issue, which will be part of a
comprehensive response that will make the killers and their
partners pay the price,'' said a statement from the Revolutionary
Justice Organization. It was not more specific.
   Missiles fired by the U.S. missile cruiser Vincennes destroyed
the airliner Sunday over the Persian Gulf.
   The typewritten statement in Arabic was delivered to a Western
news agency in Beirut with a photocopy of a page from hostage
Edward Austin Tracy's U.S. passport.
   Revolutionary Justice says it is holding Tracy and another
American, Joseph James Cicippio.
   ``We have monitored all the positions denouncing or supporting
the American crime,'' the statement said. ``We consider whoever has
denounced it a friend to the peoples of the area and whoever has
supported it a partner.''
   In threats directed at President Reagan, it said: ``We will
fight you. We will torture you with our hands. You will not know
where, when and how torture and death will face you.''
   On Oct. 21, 1986, the group calling itself the Revolutionary
Justice Organization claimed responsibility for kidnapping Tracy,
57, a writer from Rutland, Vt.
   Cicippio, 58, acting comptroller at the American University of
Beirut, was abducted Sept. 12, 1986. He is from Valley Forge, Pa.
   Eighteen foreigners, including nine Americans, are captives in
Lebanon, and most believed in the hands of Shiite extremists loyal
to Iran. Held longest is Terry A. Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent of The Associated Press, kidnapped March 16, 1985.
   The photocopy, apparently intended to authenticate Thursday's
statement, showed the passport page bearing Tracy's photograph,
name and date of birth.
   It said the shooting down of the Iran Air jetliner ``was not the
first time America killed children, women and other innocent
civilians and will not be the last one.''
   ``The Revolutionary Justice Organization stresses that the
presence of these (U.S.) fleets and their crimes will certainly
reflect on the safety of the American presence all over the
world.'' the statement said.
   Revolutionary Justice, Islamic Jihad and other Shiite groups
holding hostages are believed to be affiliated with the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God.
   A telephone caller who said he spoke for Islamic Jihad
threatened on Tuesday to kill one of the two American captives it
holds and dump the body in a west Beirut neighborhood. Police said
later the call was a hoax.
   Islamic Jihad holds Anderson, 40, and educator Thomas
Sutherland, 57, acting dean of agriculture at the American
University of Beirut. He was abducted June 9, 1985.
</TEXT>
