<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Korea     07-07 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Korea,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Welcomes South Korean Initiative</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States on Thursday welcomed a new
plan announced by South Korea to ease tensions with North Korea,
calling it a ``very constructive and forward-looking policy.''
   Deputy State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley expressed
hope that North Korea will respond positively to the six-point plan
announced by President Roh Tae-woo.
   She said the U.S. goals on the Korean peninsula include a
reduction of tensions between the two countries, discouraging North
Korean recourse to terrorism and a dialogue leading to peaceful
reunification of North and South Korea.
   ``We welcome the very constructive and forward-looking policy
which President Roh has announced,'' Mrs. Oakley said. She added
that that United States has no immediate plans to take steps of its
own.
   The United States has no diplomatic relations with North Korea
and prohibits U.S. diplomats from engaging in substantive contacts
with North Korean envoys.
   That restriction had been loosened in 1987 but was reinstated
last fall after North Korean agents were blamed for the bombing of
a South Korean passenger plane over Burma.
   North Korean requests to visit the United States are generally
turned down, but Mrs. Oakley said an exception was made recently
when a delegation of North Korean technical experts was allowed to
attend an international conference on dams in San Francisco.
</TEXT>
