<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ernest P. ``Know-What-I-Mean, Vern?''
Worrell is hooking up with George the Iguana and Existo the
Magician to produce a new Saturday morning kids' program, ``Hey
Vern, It's Ernest.''
   Actor Jim Varney, who has portrayed the Ernest character on
milk, car and pizza commercials as well as in a full-length movie,
is working with a Nashville cast and crew on the show for CBS.
   The first of 13 episodes is to hit the airwaves Sept. 17,
following ``Pee-Wee's Playhouse'' and ``Garfield,'' Varney said
Wednesday. ``It's sort of like the old `Bullwinkle' show, which a
lot of adults enjoyed.''
   Ernest will be just one of Varney's alter egos on the show.
He'll also play Sgt. Glory, Auntie Nelda and Dr. Otto, the evil
scientist.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Novelist Walker Percy has quit the
Louisiana State University Board of Supervisors after just one
meeting.
   ``That was a short term,'' said Allen Copping, president of the
LSU system. ``Maybe one board meeting was enough for him, and that
was a good one.''
   He said Percy, whose most recent novel is ``The Thanatos
Syndrome,'' wrote Gov. Buddy Roemer after the June 24 meeting that
he was quitting for health reasons. Roemer spokeswoman Sidney
Coffee said she couldn't comment because Percy didn't want his
reasons disclosed.
   ``It has nothing to do with the board itself,'' she sbeing filmed in
Yazoo City, about 45
miles north of Jackson.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With two weeks to go before Cardinal John
O'Connor's peace pilgrimage to Ireland, only about 500 people have
signed up _ about 1,000 less than organizers expected.
   O'Connor announced plans for the pilgrimage on St. Patrick's
Day, saying he hoped as many as 100,000 Americans would accompany
him to the Shrine of Our Lady of Knock to pray for ``peace with
justice'' in Northern Ireland.
   But limited accommodations in Knock, a small town where the
Virgin Mary is believed to have appeared in 1879, forced organizers
to limit the trip to about 1,500 people. Those who have said they
will go include Mayor Edward Koch, City Council President Peter
Vallone and former Gov. Hugh Carey.
   The pilgrimage, which begins July 21, includes three days in
Knock and two days in Dublin.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Mercedes McCambridge, whose son
killed his family before committing suicide last year, says in a
lawsuit that she should not be required to make restitution to a
company for money lost on investments by her son.
   Ms. McCambridge filed the complaint as a third-party plaintiff
in a lawsuit filed Tuesday by the Stephens Inc. investment banking
firm of Little Rock. The suit alleged that the Chicago investment
banking firm of Geldermann Inc. was negligent in its handling of
commodities futures orders made by Ms. McCambridge's son, John
Markle.
   Markle, of Little Rock, was fired in November from his post as
commodities trader for Stephens. Stephens says Markle placed orders
with Geldermann, then assigned profitable transactions to an
account in his mother's name while unprofitable ones went to
Stephens.
   Ms. McCambridge is seeking $1.1 million compensatory damages and
$5 million punitive damages from Stephens, Geldermann, and the
executor of her son's estate.
   Police said Markle shot his wife and two children while they
slept, then killed himself on Nov. 16.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
