<DOCNO> AP880707-0095 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 1438EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel Bjt   07-07 0703</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, Bjt,0728</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defiant Arabs Turn in Identity Cards To Protest Tax Raid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIT SAHOUR, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of Palestinians
turned in their army-issued identity cards Thursday to protest a
pre-dawn raid by Israeli tax collectors.
   The Palestinian action was an unprecedented gesture of defiance
by Arabs toward military authorities in the occupied lands.
   Non-payment of taxes has become one of the chief civil
disobedience tactics used by Palestinians in the uprising against
Israeli occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip that began Dec.
8.
   In Beit Sahour, near Bethlehem, Israeli tax collectors
accompanied by about 300 troops entered the homes of 50 residents
at 5 a.m., seized their identity cards, and said they wouldn't be
returned until the Palestinians paid their back taxes.
   Troops also impounded the cars of some Arabs, apparently for
nonpayment of vehicle licensing and other fees.
   The move prompted about 250 other Arab residents to hand in
their identity cards in protest.
   Palestinians are required to carry identity papers at all times
and face immediate arrest if caught without them. The cards also
must be presented when requesting permits to travel abroad or other
government services.
   An official of Israel's West Bank military government said there
had been no previous incidents of large numbers of Palestinians
returning identity cards in protest even though a number of
underground leaflets have called for such action.
   An army official said there was a large gathering outside city
hall which dispersed without military intervention. He declined
further comment.
   Dozens of Beit Sahour residents streamed into town hall to turn
over the orange-colored cards, which filled a large drawer.
   At one point, Palestinians broke into loud cheers and applause
when Abdullah Mousta, the mukhtar or leading town elder, handed
over his papers.
   In their latest leaflet, uprising leaders ordered Palestinians
not to pay taxes to ``escalate the uprising and bring us closer to
total civil disobedience.''
   On Thursday, Beit Sahour residents were told to report to a
girls' high school where departments were set up for collecting
back income taxes, value-added taxes and vehicle licensing fees.
   Few residents turned up to settle their bills. Some said they
could not afford to pay what they owed, and others said they
refused to pay out of defiance.
   ``The Israelis are asking the impossible,'' said a Palestinian
who would only give his first name, Abdullah. ``We can't afford it.
We live in very difficult conditions.''
   Narri Kheir, a carpenter, said the army ordered him to pay
$2,000 in taxes although he had not worked for three months.
   A woman, who refused to be identified, said many residents were
no longer afraid of Israeli punishments. ``We have nothing to lose
any more,'' she said.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, meanwhile, said the first
firebomb attack in Jewish west Jerusalem since the uprising began
showed that Arabs were intent on destroying Israel.
   There were no casualties in the Wednesday night attack on an
Israeli passenger bus in the central commercial district of Jewish
west Jerusalem.
   ``The uprising is not about the question of territory ... but
about our very existence,'' Shamir told Israel radio. ``This shows
the growing nerve of hostile elements who dare to do such a thing
in the center of the state of Israel.''
   Mayor Teddy Kollek described the firebombing as ``a terrible
danger for the present and the future.''
   Although stone-throwing and firebomb attacks have escalated
recently in Arab east Jerusalem, where 135,000 Arabs live, the
attack marked the first time violence has spread to west Jerusalem,
where about 340,000 Jews live.
   Also Wednesday, assailants threw a rock from the roof of the
largest commercial center in Tel Aviv, damaging the roof of a car.
Police spokeswoman Dalia Gilad said police blamed Arabs and rounded
up five residents of the occupied Gaza Strip for questioning. Four
were later released.
   The trial of Hanna Siniora, editor of the pro-Palestine
Liberation Organization daily, Al Fajr, began Thursday in a
Jerusalem District Court.
   Siniora was charged with violating censorship laws last year for
publishing an interview with PLO leader Yasser Arafat without first
submitting it to the military censor.
   Siniora has advocated an Arab civil disobedience campaign.
</TEXT>
