<HEAD>Former IRS Agent Jailed When Drug Found In Address Book</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Internal Revenue Service agent
who lost her job after being charged with cocaine possession was
sent to jail after a packet of the drug was discovered in a book
she had left in court, authorities said.
   Kymber Doran, who had been free on a $100,000 personal surety
bond, was jailed when the court ordered her bond revoked Wednesday.
   A U.S. marshal had found the address book and was thumbing
through it to find its owner when he found a small packet of white
powder wrapped in paper, federal prosecutors said.
   Federal Magistrate Lurana Snow then ordered detention for Ms.
Doran, who had left the courtroom without the book and then
returned.
   Ms. Snow asked Drug Enforcement Administration agents to test
the powder. It tested positive for cocaine, officials said.
   Ms. Doran, 26, worked in Fort Lauderdale IRS office when she was
arrested in May on a charge of conspriracy and possession with the
intent to distribute cocaine. She has pleaded innocencent and is
awaiting trial on that charge.
   Wednesday's hearing was to discuss a trial date.
