<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Macdonald is cq in first item.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tracy W. Macdonald is in a quandary _ does
he become the owner of a Caribbean island or take $50,000 cash?
   From all indications, the Pontiac resident has settled on ruling
his island roost.
   During a promotion cruise Wednesday for 225 people who entered a
contest through Coca-Cola Co. and the MTV cable television network,
Macdonald's name was drawn as the winner of a 25-acre island a mile
off Salinas, Puerto Rico.
   ``I want to be king of my own island,'' the 29-year-old video
store employee said.
   He can take the island or the money. While he didn't say for
sure what he'd do, he said he was thinking about developing the
island.
   ``We flew there by helicopter and it's just beautiful,'' said
Macdonald, who grew up in the U.S. Virgin Islands. ``It'd be great
for vacations.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SANTA ROSA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who calls himself ``the fastest
remote control in the West'' will spend two weeks doing what he
does best, which is very little.
   John Silveira, 24, a print-shop employee and aficionado of old
movies, was selected the Sonoma County Fair's official Couch Potato
on Wednesday night.
   Each day of the fair, which starts July 25, he will lounge in a
specially built booth, reclining on a couch, reading or watching TV
10 hours a day, eating whatever junk food he desires, and talking
with fairgoers.
   For this, he will be paid $1,000.
   ``The trick is to move around a lot'' on the couch he said in an
interview with the Santa Rosa Press Democrat. ``Sometimes you lie
on your back and watch the TV upside down. If you always watch from
the same position, you get bedsores.''
   Silveira of Santa Rosa out-loafed 12 other couch potato
competitors, including 64-year-old Thomas Bonesteel, who said he
literally lives on the couch in his tiny apartment.
   ``The only piece of furniture in the whole place is my couch,''
said Bonesteel, who claimed to watch TV ``about 15 hours a day, my
choice.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mother duck and ducklings caused a
traffic fowl-up on Interstate 5 before police took them into
custody for waddling on a freeway.
   Motorists reported the ducks walking up the southbound lanes
Wednesday morning, said Officer Howard Jordan.
   The mother and her brood weren't blocking traffic, but
rubbernecking drivers on both sides of the freeway slowed for a
look, causing backups, Jordan said.
   A highway crew used a truck to temporarily block traffic while
Jordan and two other officers rounded up the ducks and took them to
a veterinary hospital. The owner of the clinic said he planned to
release the ducks on a large pond on his property.
</TEXT>
