<DOCNO> AP880707-0105 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 1520EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-VeepChoices Bjt   07-07 0795</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Veep Choices, Bjt,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis' VP Choices: Nobody's Perfect</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As Michael Dukakis looks over his list of
potential running mates _ seven names by all indications _ no one
of them stands out as an unencumbered choice.
   The Massachusetts governor is expected to announce his choice
next week, before the opening of the Democratic National Convention
where he will be named the party's presidential nominee.
   Dukakis was on a Western campaign swing on Thursday, scheduled
to return to Boston on Sunday. Aides said he was taking Monday off,
but the expectation was he would use that time to go over the
material gathered by Paul Brountas, the close friend and lawyer who
has been heading the veep search.
   The following names are understood to be on the Dukakis list:
Jesse Jackson, Sens. John Glenn of Ohio, Lloyd Bentsen of Texas,
Bob Graham of Florida and Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee, and Reps.
Richard Gephardt of Missouri and Lee Hamilton of Indiana.
   Three other names were on the Dukakis list _ Sens. Sam Nunn of
Georgia and Bill Bradley of New Jersey and House Majority Leader
Tom Foley of Washington. All three said no thanks.
   It's always possible that the buttoned-down Dukakis could
surprise everyone and choose someone whose name has made no lists.
But the known universe is the above-named seven. Each has been
asked for detailed personal and financial information and each has
met privately with the governor.
   While strong cases can be made for each, it often is the
negatives that play a key role in determining the choice. In other
words, it often is as much a process of elimination as of selection.
   Here's a look at the downside of the seven:
   _ Jackson. Despite a campaign in which he was widely praised for
moving into the mainstream of the Democratic Party and addressing
issues of primary concern to white as well as non-white voters,
every national survey has said Jackson would hurt the Democratic
ticket far more than he would help it.
   Dukakis is a highly disciplined individual and would expect his
running mate to be equally controlled, an expectation that would be
impossible with the volatile Jackson.
   _ Glenn. The former astronaut and Marine pilot is a genuine
national hero who would give the ticket an image of strength on
defense. Polls indicate Glenn helps the ticket in nearly every
section of the country. But Glenn has always done better in the
polls than at the ballot box. He ran a disastrous campaign for
president in 1984 and still owes more than $2 million. Another rap
against him was best expressed by Jimmy Carter in 1976. After
meeting Glenn, Carter reportedly told aides, ``He's the most boring
man I've ever met.''
   _ Bentsen. No Democrat has been elected president this century
without carrying Bentsen's home state of Texas, which has the third
largest number of electoral votes _ 29. But Texas also is George
Bush's home state and there is no guarantee Bentsen would carry the
state for the Democratic ticket. In addition, Bentsen is up for
re-election. The old Lyndon B. Johnson law remains in effect _
legislation passed in 1960 to permit Johnson to run for re-election
to the Senate while he also was running for vice president. But
times have changed and an effort to go for a double could cost
Bentsen his Senate seat.
   _ Graham. Graham would probably give the Democratic ticket
Florida's 21 electoral votes. But he's little known outside his
home state and is only in his second year in the Senate. If Dukakis
is looking for Washington experience to balance the ticket, Graham
seems an unlikely choice.
   _ Gore. ``Damaged goods'' is the phrase some Dukakis advisers
use to describe the Tennessee senator, a reference to his failed
presidential campaign. A major argument Gore used during his
campaign earlier this year was that Dukakis represented the
Mondale-McGovern wing of the party. George McGovern and Walter
Mondale share the distinction of having lost 49 states as
Democratic presidential nominees. It was a comparison that didn't
sit well with Dukakis.
   _ Gephardt. Another failed challenger for the presidential
nomination, Gephardt ran well in Iowa and creditably in New
Hampshire, but then bombed out. His Japan-bashing rhetoric on trade
was sharply different from the Dukakis approach. He also was seen
as too willing to play special interest politics.
   _ Hamilton. ``Well respected'' is the term often used to
describe this senior member of the House Foreign Affairs Committee.
``Boring'' is another. Virtually unknown outside his district,
Hamilton couldn't even guarantee Dukakis Indiana's 12 electoral
votes.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Donald M. Rothberg is the chief political writer
of The Associated Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
