<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PorchWoman     07-07 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Porch Woman,0314</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Relatives Arrive to Care For Elderly Woman Who Lived on Porch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILTON, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 88-year-old woman who sat on her porch
for a month, waiting to die, has been taken by her stepchildren for
a bath and a checkup.
   Annie Jeffrey, who cannot walk, was spending Thursday at a
neighbor's home.
   ``Older people are going to be defiant but from what I've seen
here, she's not fine,'' said a stepdaughter, Roxie Harris of San
Francisco. ``She did have some objections but we decided to go on
in and take her away from the house.''
   Mrs. Harris said she and two other stepchildren have tried for
years to get Mrs. Jeffrey to live with them. ``We've been very
concerned about her, but she wouldn't let us do anything, wouldn't
let us take her back. We were here last year to clean up the house
or either to buy a mobile home to put on the lot, but she was
determined that we wouldn't do that.''
   Then, Mrs. Jeffrey could walk and seemed able to care for
herself, Mrs. Harris said. ``What I've seen here is a totally
different individual.''
   The stepchildren, all of whom live in other states, were
contacted by neighbors concerned about Mrs. Jeffrey's physical
condition, rundown house and cluttered yard. While Mrs. Jeffrey sat
on the rotted porch, neighbors took her food each day and tried to
persuade her to leave.
   She now has seen a doctor and taken a bath, but no decision has
been made on where she will go when her stepchildren leave.
   ``I feel so much better. I can sleep now,'' said the Rev. A.L.
Jones of Montevallo, who tried to get help for her. He said that
since she did not want to leave her home, he could do little
besides checking on her condition.
</TEXT>
