<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Drought-LawnShower     07-07 0185</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Lawn Shower,0190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shower A Day Keeps Drought At Bay</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Drought Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A shower a day helps keep the drought at
bay, and a little soap in hand doesn't hurt.
   Frank Reeves has rigged up a portable shower on his front lawn.
Several mornings a week, he trots outside in his swimsuit, connects
the garden hose and lathers up with biodegradable soap.
   ``I feel sorry for my lawn,'' said Reeves, 41, a corporate
lawyer. ``I think my lawn needs the water more than the city sewer
system does.''
   Nashville has no restrictions on outside water use, but Reeves
is doing his bit for conservation with his shower.
   ``I've been using it for a shower and lawn-waterer
intermittently for about three weeks now,'' he said.
   Reeves moves the shower to a different spot each day but the
dousings aren't enough to water his entire lawn. He limits the
watering to specific flowers and trees.
   ``Any other water the lawn gets is from whatever spray or
overflow it happens to get from what little plant watering we do,''
he said.
</TEXT>
