<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis-Prison     07-07 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Prison,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Offers $5 Million For Prison Site; Owners Want $9.6 Million</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Dukakis administration on Thursday offered $5
million for land designated for a prison, but the owners demanded
nearly twice as much money and vowed a court fight if the state
acquires the property by eminent domain.
   ``This bid is simply too low for us to seriously consider,''
co-owner Daniel Striar said after a brief meeting with state
officials. ``We feel confident that the property has a market value
of over $9 million.''
   The controversy over the planned medium-security prison on 782
acres in rural New Braintree has become a political embarrassment
for all-but-certain Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis.
   The FBI is conducting a preliminary inquiry into allegations by
prison opponents that Striar and co-owner Gary Jacobson bought the
land after receiving a tip about the state's interest. Dukakis and
the owners have dismissed the charges.
   The Massachusetts governor also has continued to back the
proposal for the 500-bed prison.
   ``If negotiations are not successful, we will move to take the
property by eminent domain,'' Dukakis said.
   Striar and Jacobson stood by the $9.6 million price they asked
for when they first offered the land to the state in 1986, less
than a year after they bought it for $3 million. On the property is
a building that once served as a religious academy, 20 homes and
more than 700 acres of farmland.
   A preliminary state appraisal estimated the land's value at $8.7
million.
   Opponents of the prison, led by New Braintree selectwoman
Dorothea Thomas-Vitrac, cited those figures to support claims that
the state sought out the developers as middlemen in the land deal
and would reward them with a whopping profit.
   Three subsequent, more detailed appraisals that were
commissioned by the state, placed the value of the land at about $5
million. Two appraisals put its worth at exactly $5 million; the
third at $4.98 million.
   The state's offering price was based on those appraisals, which
took into account an environmental impact study that said the state
would have to build a sewage treatment plant on the land if it
located a prison there.
   If negotiations for the property do not resume and the state
seeks to claim the land through eminent domain, the owners can
contest the state's offering price in court. Michael Goldman, a
spokesman for Jacobson and Striar, said the owners would take legal
action.
</TEXT>
