<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Reagan-Bush     07-07 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Bush,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan, Bush, Seek Coordination on White House, Campaign
Activities</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Politics Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan and Vice President George
Bush, seeking to limit public disagreements, directed their chiefs
of staff Thursday to coordinate campaign policy pronouncements and
strategy.
   ``I think everyone agrees that the main issue is, `No
surprises,''' presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said in
describing a luncheon that Reagan, Bush and aides had in the White
house residence.
   ``Keeping them informed of our policy moves and vice versa would
be a key element,'' he said. ``We didn't talk about specific
issues.''
   Fitzwater said Reagan's policy decisions would not be driven by
consideration of how they would affect Bush's prospects.
   ``The president makes his decisions on the merits, on what he
thinks is best for the country,'' he said. ``On the other hand,
it's also important to know what the vice president's positions
are, how the campaign is framing certain actions and so forth.''
   At the luncheon, he said, Reagan reiterated that he expects Bush
to ``present his own approach to the problems'' of the 1990s. And
he said Reagan acknowledged ``their previously reached
understanding that the vice president will want to take positions
during the campaign that may differ from the president and
administration policy.''
   But the spokesman also said that beginning Monday, a
coordinating team headed by White House chief of staff Kenneth
Duberstein and Bush chief of staff Craig Fuller will meet at least
once weekly.
   Fuller has been sitting in on White House staff meetings. But
the new committee, Fitzwater said, would be aimed specifically at
making sure neither Reagan nor Bush is blind-sided by the other, to
the extent possible in a campaign in which Bush will be on the road
much of the time.
   Fitzwater would not say whether formation of the coordinating
group resulted from differences that have arisen between Reagan and
Bush on such issues as the Civil Rights Restoration Act and U.S.
strategy for ousting Panamanian Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   Taking part in Thursday's meeting besides Reagan, Bush,
Duberstein and Fuller were Stuart Spencer, a longtime Reagan
political adviser; former Sen. Paul Laxalt, a Reagan confidant; Lee
Atwater, Bush's campaign manager; pollster Robert Teeter; White
House political adviser Frank Donatelli, Fitzwater and Sheila Tate,
the Bush campaign press secretary.
   Fitzwater said that Reagan outlined to Bush the themes he would
like to strike during campaign-related appearances, including
patriotism, family values, military strength, less government,
private initiative and lower taxes.
   ``The president feels he can be especially helpful with
conservative Republicans, Democrats and other key groups which are
not registered Republican but which have voted for the Reagan-Bush
ticket in '80 and '84,'' he said.
   Reagan would like to spend at least two days a week campaigning
for Bush this fall, after Congress' recess around Oct. 5, Fitzwater
said.
   He said Reagan may take part in some campaign activities for
Bush on the West Coast during the president's summer vacation in
August.
   Bush said at a news conference in Boston that joint Reagan-Bush
appearances were not discussed at the meeting, ``but I would think
there would be some.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880707-0114 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 1629EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Drought-Governors     07-07 0746</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Governors,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ag Secretary Says Need for Drought Relief Bill Is Urgent</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Drought Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng met with
six farm-state governors Thursday and emerged saying the need for
legislative action to provide drought relief has now become urgent.
   ``There's a need to do something, it would probably take
legislation to do that and there's a need to do it with some
urgency,'' Lyng told a news conference following the session with
governors and key lawmakers.
   Lyng's call for swift action was in marked contrast to past
remarks that Congress should hold off on fashioning a drought
relief package until it is certain of the extent of the damage
wrought by sizzling temperatures and a shortage of rainfall in the
Farm Belt.
   Since he made those remarks several weeks ago, however, the
drought has become more ominous. Spring wheat, oats and barley
already are hard hit in the Grain Belt and authorities forecast
drastic reductions in corn yields unless there is substantial rain
in the Midwest within a week.
   ``It's a critical time when the corn is tasseling and we're in
the pollinating stage,'' said Iowa Gov. Terry Branstad said after
the meeting. ``Every day that goes by we see a substantial
reduction in yields.''
   Participants in the meeting at offices of the National
Governors' Association said they reached broad agreement on almost
all fronts. They said farmers need more assurance that Congress
will act this year and that therefore bill drafting should begin
quickly.
   ``The decision to act I think is uniform among the people who
were present,'' said North Dakota Gov. George Sinner, chairman of
the association's committee on agriculture and rural development.
``There also was a uniform decision that Congress probably should
address this.''
   Bill-drafting sessions could start as early as next week in both
the House and Senate Agriculture committees, said the chairmen of
those panels, Rep. E. ``Kika'' de la Garza, D-Texas, and Sen.
Patrick J. Leahy, D-Vt.
   Also on hand were Govs. George Mickelson of South Dakota, Terry
Branstad of Iowa, Rudy Perpich of Minnesota, John Ashcroft of
Missouri and James Martin of North Carolina. Seven other states
were represented at the session by their lieutenant governors.
   Lyng said there were good prospects that President Reagan would
sign relief legislation if it is a measure ``that is reasonable and
compassionate and will help farmers.''
   Officials said a consensus was forming around a few key
proposals that could well be included in relief legislation. They
said the measure most likely would allow farmers to keep all of the
so-called deficiency payments that they have received in advance.
   Deficiency payments are income-support subsidies. They represent
the difference between the market price of the crop and a target
price set by Congress and adjusted by the secretary of agriculture.
   As the drought has intensified, crop prices have been rising in
anticipation of scarcity later. Thus the gap between market prices
and target prices has shrunk, leaving farmers with smaller payments
at the same time that their crops have been wiped out. Forty
percent of the deficiency payments, however, already were parceled
out in advance to producers.
   ``I think it would be very difficult to collect advance
deficiency payments from farmers who have no income,'' Lyng told
reporters.
   The officials also said that producers of ``non-program'' crops
should also receive relief under the legislation. Soybeans
constitute the largest of these crops, whose producers do not
receive deficiency payments. Various other fruits and vegetables
also are non-program crops.
   The officials were less clear on exactly how much the measure
would cost.
   De la Garza and others emphasized that the cost of the drought
bill would not be able to push the cost of farm subsidies over
their budgeted $17 billion limit. Lawmakers are expecting to save a
considerable sum as a result of the smaller size of deficiency
payments to many farmers.
   This amount in turn could be recycled and paid out in the form
of drought relief, but that still would not take in aid to growers
of non-program crops.
   ``That was discussed in there,'' said Rep. Charles Stenholm,
D-Texas. He said it was unsure where the money would come from.
   Governors made clear, however, that some form of relief was
needed.
   ``Farmers in Missouri would face a a real economic disaster from
which they would not recover if we failed to get relief,'' said
Ashcroft. ``We will get relief.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880707-0115 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 1714EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Homeless 500   07-07 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Homeless, 500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Call For $15 Billion Housing Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Standing in front of a run-down motel where
the government pays for the lodging of homeless families, three
Democratic lawmakers on Thursday called for a $15 billion-a-year
program to create new low-income housing.
   ``We have a responsibility,'' Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., told
reporters and homeless activists at the Capital City Inn, a
Washington motel where the government provides room and board for
the homeless at an estimated cost of $3,000 a month per family.
   Under Frank's bill, about $75 billion would be spent over five
years for construction of new housing, renovation of existing
buildings, upgrading of public housing and the acquisition of
additional units.
   Frank, joined by Reps. Kenneth J. Gray, D-Ill, and Floyd Flake,
D-N.Y., said the legislation is not aimed at this year, but for
1989 and the new administration. Frank said he has not discussed
the proposal with Massachusetts Gov. Michael S. Dukakis, the
Democrat's expected presidential nominee.
   The lawmakers criticized the Reagan administration's cuts in
housing programs and the increasing government reliance on
vouchers, designed to be used by the poor to go towards paying for
rents in privately owned apartments. They said the vouchers do not
work in cities such as Boston where there are few available
low-cost housing units.
   The legislative program would be self-financing through a
doubling of the cigarette tax, limiting deductions for business
meals and entertainment expenses and other tax adjustments, Frank
said.
   ``We cannot afford not to build more affordable housing,'' said
Flake. ``Homeless are human beings and they have rights too.''
   The legislation was embraced by homeless activists.
   ``This bill can eliminate this place,'' said Mitch Snyder,
pointing to the motel where he said families with four and five
children live in a single room. Windows in the rooms do not open,
forcing residents to leave doors open at night and making them more
vulnerable to crime, Snyder said.
   Organizers from the Community for Creative Non-Violence said
parents or older children must stay awake through the night to
protect infants from rats.
   Officials at the motel, apparently upset by the publicity,
instructed security guards to prevent Snyder and the congressmen
from touring the complex with reporters and TV camera crews in tow.
   ``Tell him to have me arrested,'' Frank snapped at the guard.
The tour continued without incident.
   The group did not go inside any rooms, but walked through a
darkened corridor littered with food and other trash to the back
where Snyder described living conditions.
   Motel manager Fadru Haji declined comment. ``Let them say what
they want to say,'' he said. ``It's a one-sided story.''
   Meanwhile, homeless organizers announced plans for
demonstrations in more than 60 U.S. cities and towns next Thursday
to protest the plight of the homeless.
   Activists plan to occupy abandoned government-owned buildings as
an act of civil disobedience to focus attention on structures that
go unused while some poor have no place to live.
   The Community for Creative Non-Violence said activists also plan
24-hour vigils, rallies and marches.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
