<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Wille     07-07 0203</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Wille,0209</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Frank Wille, Banker, Dies At 57</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENWICH, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frank Wille, a former chairman of the
Federal Deposit Insurance Corp., has died of a heart attack at his
home. He was 57.
   At the time of his death Wednesday, Wille was chairman and chief
executive officer of The Greater New York Savings Bank, a position
he held for seven years.
   Wille also was on the board of directors of the National Council
of Savings Institutions and the Savings Banks Association of New
York State.
   Before joining the bank, Wille was a partner in the law firm of
Cadwalader, Wickersham & Taft, specializing in banking law. While
with the firm, he was chairman of the Banking Law Committee of the
Association of the Bar of the City of New York.
   He was chairman of the FDIC from 1970-76, and also served from
1964-70 as superintendent of banks of the State of New York and
chairman of the New York State Banking Board.
   He is survived by his mother, Alma Schutt Wille; his wife,
Barbara Bowen Wille; and two daughters, Serena and Alison Wille,
all of Greenwich; and a sister, Vivian B. Wheeler of Magnolia, Mass.
   A funeral was scheduled Monday.
