<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 1647EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush-Strategy 1stLd-Writethru a0615 07-07 0753</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Strategy, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0615,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush, Breaking Tradition, Plans to Campaign While Democrats Meet</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with White House meeting, subbing 2 grafs for grafs
4-5 pvs, Playing down ... White House.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush, hoping to steal
thunder from Michael Dukakis, is likely to break with tradition and
go on the road stumping for votes and media attention during the
Democratic National Convention.
   The plan, Bush said, is to ``get a little bit of ink'' while the
spotlight is on Dukakis and his nomination as the Democrats'
presidential candidate.
   Traditionally, presidential candidates keep a low profile during
the nominating conventions of their rivals. President Reagan, still
playing by those rules although he is not running this year, will
be at his mountaintop ranch in California when the Democrats meet
in Atlanta July 18-21.
   On another campaign matter, Bush and Reagan, seeking to limit
public disagreements, directed their chiefs of staff Thursday to
coordinate campaign policy pronouncements.
   ``I think everyone agrees that the main issue is, `No
surprises,''' presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said after
Reagan, Bush and aides met over lunch at the White House.
   Bush said recently he was debating whether to travel during the
Democratic convention. ``I think probably some but _ you know, I
don't know, I don't know what's the right thing to do.''
   On the one hand, Bush said, he'd get news coverage by being on
the road.
   On the other hand, he said, ``you don't want to look like you're
trying to frantically elbow your way into the news cycle.''
   Tentatively, Bush's planners are looking at events on Monday and
Tuesday and Friday and Saturday of Democratic convention week _ the
opening two days of the convention and the two days after it ends.
   Republicans already are planning to send a team of surrogates to
Atlanta to make sure the media hears their point of view.
   Sheila Tate, the vice president's press secretary, said Bush's
schedulers were looking ``mainly at fund-raisers, nuts and bolts
work that's got to get done, and it's a good time to do it.''
   She said that Wednesday and Thursday ``are the big, big days
(for the Democrats) and you keep them open.'' Wednesday night at
the convention is reserved for the presidential nomination and
presidential roll call, while Thursday night is set aside for the
vice presidential nomination, roll call and acceptance speeches.
   At this point, most polls show the Dukakis-Bush race fairly
close. Some surveys show Dukakis ahead by about four points, while
others indicate it is even.
   With all the attention on the Democratic convention, Dukakis is
expected to move ahead of Bush and come away from Atlanta with a
hefty lead over the vice president, perhaps as much as 10 to 15
points, according to Richard Wirthlin, the Reagan's pollster.
   ``The Republicans need some kind of major event, giving George
Bush the focus, the play, the visibility'' after Atlanta, Wirthlin
said.
   He said an obvious thing for Bush to do would be to name his
vice presidential nominee right after the Democratic convention,
robbing Dukakis of the opportunity to bask alone in the limelight.
Bush has said he has not begun to focus on his running mate yet.
   Bush, talking with reporters on Air Force II Wednesday night as
he returned from Dallas, said he would not be idle after he claims
the Republican nomination at the party's convention in New Orleans
Aug. 15-18. He said he is thinking about having meetings in Houston
on campaign strategy and with surrogates.
   He acknowledged that the general election phase of the campaign
will begin ahead of the traditional Labor Day opening and talked
about the demands that will pose.
   ``The physical thing _ I don't want to get too tired. I'd like
to get some time (off) before this last rush to judgment. But I
know physically I can do this.'' He said he was still jogging,
``getting tired but I still feel up to it.
   ``So physically, I'm not too worried about it. I don't want to
get tired and make a lot of mistakes,'' Bush added. ``And if you do
(get tired), as I've found out, you can make mistakes.''
   Referring to Dukakis, who is 54, the 64-year-old vice president
said, ``He will not outwork me. Might do other things more, better,
but he's not going to outwork me. He will not be in better shape
than I am to do the physical part of this thing.''
</TEXT>
