<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 1738EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Unrest     07-07 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Unrest,0526</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Death of Demonstrator Reported in Ethnic Turmoil</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first death of a demonstrator in a monthslong
ethnic dispute was reported Thursday in the southern republic of
Armenia, whose residents continued a strike that has devastated the
area's economy.
   The government newspaper Izvestia said a resident of the
Armenian capital of Yerevan, Kh. Zakharyan, was seriously wounded
on a highway Tuesday and died later in a hospital. It said a
criminal investiation had begun.
   Izvestia reported that a ``major part'' of Armenia's industry,
construction and transportation remained idle Thursday.
   The Armenian press agency said Zakharyan was hit by a plastic
bullet fired by Soviet forces shortly after thousands of
demonstrators mobbed Yerevan's international airport on Tuesday to
demand that aviation workers join the strike.
   Government spokesmen in Moscow denied on Wednesday that anyone
had died in the latest round of protests by Armenians seeking
annexation of the nearby region of Nagorno-Karabakh, now part of
the neighboring republic of Azerbaijan.
   The report Thursday was the first of Soviet forces using guns
against demonstrators since the peaceful protests in Yerevan began
in February. It was also the first indication that troops
patrolling the area are armed with rounds designed to be non-lethal.
   An editor at Armenia's official news agency said troops were
called to Zvartnots Airport to break up the demonstration, which
disrupted flights. The soldiers were withdrawn Thursday and flights
resumed, said the editor, speaking on condition of anomymity.
   A Soviet television newscast Thursday night showed crowds of
people who had been waiting for days at the airport for flights out
of Yerevan.
   ``What I saw is practically impossible to describe in words,'' a
witness of Tuesday's airport demonstration said in a broadcast
interview. ``In my opinion, innocent passengers suffered.''
   The TV report showed soldiers wearing helmets and carrying guns
patrolling roads leading to the airport. It was not clear when the
pictures were taken.
   The labor newspaper Trud said Thursday that the airport
disturbance forced cancellation of 60 flights Monday and Tuesday
and disrupted the travel of 14,000 passengers.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Vadim Perfilyev told a news
conference Wednesday that troops routed about 2,000 people from the
immediate airport area. He said 36 people ``had to seek medical
assistance'' after the clash late Tuesday.
   S. Petrosyan, a member of Armenia's Politburo, went on
television Wednesday evening to call on Armenians to resume work
and ``be reasonable,'' Trud said. It quoted the Ministry of
Internal Affairs as saying the situation in Yerevan remains serious.
   Ethnic Armenians make up the majority in Nagorno-Karabakh. They
have long been demanding that the mountainous region be transfered
to Armenia.
   Armenia supports the demand, but Azerbaijan rejects it and the
issue has gone to officials in Moscow.
   In February, rioting in the Azerbaijani city of Sumgait left
dead 32 people _ 26 Armenians and six Azerbaijanis.
   Newspapers reported Tuesday that a general strike had begun in
Yerevan, apparently over dissatisfaction with a national Communist
Party conference in Moscow that failed to resolve the
Nagorno-Karabakh dispute.
</TEXT>
