<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 2111EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Teachers-NEA     07-07 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teachers-NEA,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teachers Union Adopts Sympathy Resolution Over Iran Jet</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Teachers-Notebook Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National Education Association delegates
concluded their annual meeting Thursday by adopting a watered-down
resolution extending condolences to the families of the 290 victims
of the downed Iranian jet.
   After a long debate, the 8,227 delegates voted to delete
language that would have implicitly criticized the U.S. action in
the Persian Gulf.
   The final wording approved by the teacher delegates extended
``our sincere condolences to the families of victims. The
Representative Assembly urges all parties to seek an immediate
solution to the conflict.''
   The 1.9 million-member union has been a frequent critic of
Reagan administration foreign policies.
   In other actions, delegates approved a resolution that would
restrict home schooling and force anyone teaching a child at home
to meet state requirements.
   They also urged public schools to teach children about the
influence of religious heritage in the nation and the world.
   The union also passed a measure urging athletic organizations,
sports media outlets and others ``to join in efforts to change the
term, `man-to-man' defense'' to ``one-to-one'' defense in reference
to women's and girls' basketball.
   Finally, the teacher union called on its members to refrain from
participating in mass released balloon launches, especially those
made of latex, because they have ``a deleterious impact on our
environment.''
   A national balloon launch sponsored each spring by a science
teachers' organization has come under criticism from
environmentalists, who say porpoises and other marine life have
been harmed by ingesting the ballooms. The science teachers are
looking for safer balloons.
</TEXT>
