<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Landers     07-07 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Landers,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ann Landers Breaks Own Rule to Fulfill Vietnam Vet's Dream</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLIFF EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Advice columnist Ann Landers says she broke her
rule against helping readers contact each other to help a Vietnam
veteran get in touch with the mother of a buddy killed in the war.
   After trying unsuccessfully to locate the man's family, Ms.
Landers decided to publish a letter from veteran Gil Noble, who
wrote that he wanted Kevin H. Dugan's parents to know ``how much
their son was admired and respected by the men he served with.''
   She said she telephoned several Dugans in Kevin's hometown of
Blue Point, N.Y., but no one knew him.
   Finally, Ms. Landers said she decided to break her rule and
publish Noble's name with his letter Tuesday, in hopes that a
reader of her nationally syndicated column would know Kevin's
family.
   It turned out well, but there's a risk, she noted.
   ``You never really know who these people are. Sometimes these
people who write the most charming and warm letters can be the
kookiest,'' Ms. Landers said Thursday, explaining her rule of not
putting people in touch with each other. ``But I felt the letter
from Gil Noble was so sincere. I felt, well, here's an opportunity
to make a whole family happy.''
   Kevin's mother, Anne Dugan Brown, still lives in Blue Point,
N.Y. But she remarried after her son's death in 1968 and said she
might never have heard from Noble without Ms. Landers' help.
   A neighbor called early Tuesday to tell her about the column,
she said, and the phone then rang all day.
   Noble, a 44-year-old business teacher in Vista, Calif., also
talked to Ms. Brown on Tuesday after Kevin's brother passed on her
telephone number.
   ``We were all a little teary-eyed at first,'' Ms. Brown said,
``but I felt it was a wonderful tribute to (Kevin's) memory.''
</TEXT>
