<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Panama     07-07 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Panama,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Regrets Panamanian Boycott of Canal Meeting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Panamanian decision to boycott a scheduled
meeting of the board that oversees operations of the Panama Canal
is ``regrettable and irresponsible,'' the State Department said
Thursday.
   The decision was also denounced by William R. Gianelli, board
chairman of the Panama Canal Commission. He accused Panama of a
``total disregard for the efficient and safe operation of the
Panama Canal.''
   The commission's next meeting is set for next week in Savannah,
Ga., but Panamanian Foreign Minister Jorge Ritter said Tuesday that
Panamanian representatives will not attend that or any future
meeting.
   That policy, Ritter said, will remain in place until ``the
United States normalizes relations with Panama'' and recognizes
nominees appointed by the government that replaced the one headed
by President Eric Arturo Delvalle last February.
   The Reagan administration has continued to recognize Delvalle as
the legitimate authority in Panama. It also has called on Panama's
de facto ruler, Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, to resign and to leave
the country. Noriega is under federal indictment on drug-smuggling
charges.
   The Panama Canal treaty established the canal commission,
mandating that it consist of five U.S. and four Panamanian members.
   Gianelli said Panama's boycott of the commission meeting
``impacts on training Panamanians for higher positions with the
canal commission and will undoubtedly slow the process of moving
those outstanding Panamanian employees into more responsible and
senior positions.''
</TEXT>
