<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Plans Bus Trip To Convention</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson announced plans Thursday to lead a
three-day ``Jackson Action Rainbow Express'' bus trip from Chicago
to the Democratic National Convention in Atlanta.
   Jackson said his presidential campaign also will sponsor
workshops for people outside the convention hall. He said the
emphasis on non-delegates is intended to strengthen the party, not
steal thunder from the expected Democratic presidential nominee,
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis.
   Jackson was in Atlanta Thursday to review his convention plans
and to join local civil rights leaders in work on his political
action committee, the Keep Hope Alive PAC.
   ``We will be raising money to put the focus on areas where there
is need to finance candidates running for various offices to keep
building our progressive coalition of farmers and workers and men
and women,'' he said at a news conference.
   Jackson said he is not organizing a large-scale pilgrimage of
his supporters to Atlanta for the July 18-21 convention, but said,
``thousands of people always come.''
   He said the bus ride, probably starting July 14 in Chicago, will
allow him to thank his supporters and encourage voter registration
for the general election.
   ``We just decided to come by bus rather than by Airbus. We don't
want a ship to mistake us,'' he said. Jackson earlier had said that
Sunday's downing of an Iranian Airbus passenger plane by a U.S.
warship showed American foreign policy should be based more on
diplomacy than sophisticated weapons.
   Jackson would not comment on whether his enthusiasm for the
general election might diminish if he were not asked to be the vice
presidential nominee, but he suggested he will be influenced by the
treatment his candidacy and platform proposals receive from the
convention and Dukakis.
   ``The conclusion of those steps will in some measure determine
what our fall activities will be,'' he said.
</TEXT>
