<1ST_LINE>r p AM-DemocraticPlatform     07-07 0254</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Democratic Platform,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Platform To Be Formally Issued Next Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic Platform Committee will issue
its streamlined party platform early next week, a party official
said Thursday.
   Although the party's platform writers approved a roughly
3,500-word draft platform in Denver June 25, they have not yet
completed the task of polishing the amendments approved at that
meeting.
   The Michael Dukakis campaign is still negotiating with Jesse
Jackson's forces over the civil rights leader's plan to pursue as
many as 13 minority plants at the party's convention in Atlanta
July 19.
   The Jackson campaign was rebuffed at the Denver meeting on such
issues as Jackson's call for higher taxes on the wealthy, a
Pentagon freeze, a U.S. promise of no-first-use of nuclear weapons,
and self-determination for the Palestinians.
   Mike Barnes, a former Maryland congressman handling the platform
for the Dukakis campaign, said, ``We are continuing to work with
the committee members and the other campaign trying to resolve
outstanding issues.''
   He said ``purely mechanical'' reasons had delayed issuing the
amended majority report. ``People were hard to reach during the
holiday weekend,'' Barnes explained.
   A platform committee official, who asked not to be identified,
said the entire report, including the Jackson minority planks, may
be released Monday.
   The convention starts July 18 in Atlanta, with the delegates
scheduled to take up the platform the next day.
   Jackson controlled more than a quarter of the 186-member
platform committee, enough to ensure that he can carry any issue he
wishes to the floor.
</TEXT>
