<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 2126EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Airliner-Glance     07-07 0594</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airliner-Glance,0632</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Airliner Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, is a summary of developments Thursday in the
aftermath of last Sunday's destruction of an Iranian jetliner by
the USS Vincennes:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>PENTAGON BRIEFING</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   A Pentagon spokesman said it was extremely unlikely that a
second Iranian airplane was near Iran Air Flight 655 when it was
shot down. It has been suggested that a second plane, emitting a
military identification signal, might have prompted the Vincennes
captain to fire on the civilian airliner.
   The Pentagon backed off from its earlier assertion that the
Iranian airliner was flying outside the commercial air corridor.
   Pentagon spokesman Daniel Howard also said that Iran should
share responsibility for the downing of the plane because it took
off from a joint military and civilian airfield during an exchange
of fire between the Vincennes and Iranian gunboats and was headed
straight at the Vincennes.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>IRAN FUNERALS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   In Tehran, tens of thousands of Iranians shouting ``Death to
America!'' buried victims of the attack.
   President Ali Khamenei, Parliament Speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani
and Ayatollah Hussein Ali Montazeri, the designated successor of
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, led the procession with 76 coffins
draped with Iranian flags.
   The mass funeral started with a fiery speech from Khamenei, who
mocked American statements on the incident and called for revenge.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>IRAN-AIRPORT</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The manager of the airport in Bandar Abbas, where Flight 655
originated, said the Navy failed to use the proper frequency when
it warned the Iran Air flight away from the Vincennes.
   Hossein Peroussi, who said he was in the control tower Sunday,
denied Pentagon claims the Vincennes sent warnings to the plane on
both ultra-high frequency and very-high frequency radio channels.
He said the Navy uses only UHF channels and the Airbus received
only VHF signals.
   Peroussi also said transponders on the plane emitted signals
``only in a civilian mode, not a military mode.'' The Pentagon said
the Vincennes received both types of signals from the plane.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>HOSTAGES-REVENGE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   In Beirut, Lebanon, a radical Shiite Moslem group holding two
American hostages said their fate will be part of Iran's revenge
for the 290 killed.
   The typewritten statement in Arabic from the Revolutionary
Justice Organization was delivered with a photocopy of a page from
hostage Edward Austin Tracy's U.S. passport.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>COMPENSATION</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``Humane and moral'' considerations will figure heavily in the
decision on compensation to the families of victims of the Iranian
airliner tragedy, President Reagan's chief spokesman said.
   Spokesman Marlin Fitzwater emphasized that the compensation
matter is under staff review and has not yet even gone to senior
advisers or the president.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>CONGRESSIONAL COMMENTARY</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Senate Democratic leader Robert Byrd said U.S. ships in the
Persian Gulf are ``in an untenable position'' and President
Reagan's policy in the region needs to be reassessed.
   House Speaker Jim Wright called the incident ``a very
straightforward error of misidentification'' but said the Iranian
government ``must assume some serious responsibility for this kind
of an error'' because of the attacks by its gunboats on the
Vincennes just before the A-300 Airbus was shot down.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SECURITY ALERTS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   CIA Director William Webster said the United States was prepared
for Iranian reprisals. ``Our government has procedures in place to
protect our citizens and our officials who would be likely targets.
And they are being utilized,'' he said.
   America's international airlines say they have taken additional
precautions against terrorism since the incident. Bob Kierce, TWA's
director of international security, said the airline has taken
steps to ensure that security procedures ``are being exercised to
the fullest.''
</TEXT>
