<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 2102EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Dubcek     07-07 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dubcek,0397</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Czech Leader Calls on Current Leaders to Follow Soviet
Reforms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND PRINZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alexander Dubcek, whose liberal
Czechoslovak ``Prague spring'' was ended by a Soviet invasion in
August 1968, urged his country's current leaders Thursday to adopt
new Kremlin-style reforms.
   In a television interview said to be the first with a Western
network since his ouster as Communist Party chief, Dubcek called
the invasion ``a heavy moral burden on our society.''
   Dubcek, 66, lost his party post in April 1969 and was expelled
from the party in June 1970.
   Many economic and social reforms supported by Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev are similar to those Dubcek introduced 20
years ago.
   He now lives as a pensioner in virtual seclusion. Austrian
television interviewed him as he worked in his garden at
Bratislava, the capital of Slovakia about 40 miles east of Vienna,
dressed in an undershirt and shorts.
   ``I welcome every positive step which is made for the
application of Soviet restructuring under our conditions,'' the
former party chief said. ``Some people say we cannot use all that,
but in the last 20 years the same people have copied everying (from
the Soviet Union).''
   When the late Soviet leader Leonid I. Brezhnev was in power,
``we had to march the way Brezhnev ordered,'' Dubcek said.
   ``Now the same people (Czech leaders) are very selective when it
comes to deciding what suits Czechoslovakia and what not,'' he
said. ``There is a certain inconsistency in evaluating the
experience. I believe that what happens in the Soviet Union now is
well suited for our conditions.''
   Dubcek deplored the fact that Kremlin reform ``unfortunately
comes after 20 years.'' In those years, he said, ``the existing
backwardness has deepened, and that testifies to the fact that the
invasion was not right.''
   Asked for comment on the recent Communist Party conference in
Moscow, Dubcek said: ``I was always firmly convinced that ...
Gorbachev's leadership will prevail. The conference has confirmed
that and I am happy about it.''
   Dubcek chided Western officials, who he said believe it is a
good thing ``if socialism ares badly.''
   On the contrary, he said, ``it is better for Western democracies
if the Soviet leadership finally and radically distances itself
from Stalinist militarism and departs from Brezhnev's dogmatism.''
</TEXT>
