<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Hastings 2ndLd-Writethru a0752-a0757 07-07 0719</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hastings, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0752-a0757,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Panel Recommends Impeachment of Judge Hastings</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Combines Urgent series; SUBS grafs 4-6 pvs, `Even Terence ...
in Miami,' with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Hastings reax, background</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House Judiciary subcommittee recommended
unanimously Thursday that the House impeach U.S. District Judge
Alcee L. Hastings for committing ``high crimes and misdemeanors.''
   The House criminal justice subcommittee voted 7-0 to send the
resolution of 17 articles of impeachment to the House Judiciary
Committee for further action. The full committee is expected to act
next Thursday.
   The resolution charges three main impeachable offenses: that
Hastings conspired with a Washington attorney to receive a bribe in
exchange for modifying the sentences of two convicted racketeers,
that he lied during his trial and that he compromised an FBI
wiretap by leaking information from it to a target.
   ``It ain't over. It's far from over,'' Hastings said at the U.S.
District Courthouse in Miami where he had been participating in a
trial.
   Hastings, Florida's first black federal judge and a fiery orator
popular on the lecture circuit, was unusually terse. He refused to
appear on local television newscasts.
   Saying he is ``legally, morally and spiritually correct,''
Hastings called the proceedings politically motivated and said the
panel decision shows they ``do not respect the jury system.''
   Hastings said he would continue to hear cases because there is
no reason why he would have to step down.
   Terence J. Anderson, Hastings' lawyer, said he believes the
resolution will go to the House floor for a vote as soon as
possible.
   If the full House impeaches Hastings, the Senate would conduct a
trial to determine whether he should be removed from office.
   ``I was pessimistic, but I was surprised by the unanimity,''
said Anderson.
   ``I take it in good faith that they believe it was an
impeachable offense,'' Anderson said. ``It's now time to prepare
for a trial in the Senate.''
   Hastings has insisted he is innocent of any wrongdoing.
   The seven members voting for the resolution were Chairman John
Conyers, D-Mich.; Don Edwards, D-Calif.; Mike Synar, D-Okla.; Rick
Boucher, D-Va.; John Bryant, D-Texas; George W. Gekas, R-Pa.; and
Hamilton Fish Jr., R-N.Y. Patrick L. Swindall, R-Ga., did not
attend the session.
   Conyers, who like Hastings is black, said the decision was the
hardest he has had to make during his years in Congress.
   Reciting his civil rights record, including opposition to
Southern judges who discriminate against blacks, Conyers said, ``We
did not fight that civil rights struggle to replace one
discrimination with another. We cannot set up a double standard. We
must demand that everyone live up to high standards.
   ``We are not here to discuss guilt or innocence, but whether
there have been high crimes and misdemeanors and pass them onto the
full House. We have done that,'' Conyers said.
   Gekas said the resolution contains offenses ``that were
substantiated fully in the hearings.''
   Fish said the hearings showed that Hastings ``sought to sell his
office for private gain and then lied about it under oath.'' He
also said the leaking of the wiretap information ``cannot be
tolerated.''
   ``The evidence in this matter is overwhelming,'' said Synar.
``There is no doubt that Judge Hastings committed these act for
which he is charged.''
   In February 1983, Hastings was acquitted of charges he conspired
with Washington lawyer William Borders to receive a bribe in
exchange for modifying the sentences of two convicted racketeers.
Borders was convicted in a separate trial, was sent to prison and
has been released.
   A month after Hastings' 1983 acquittal, U.S. District Judges W.
Terrell Hodges of Florida and Anthony A. Alaimo of Georgia filed a
complaint under the 1980 discipline law asking the 11th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals, which includes Florida, to investigate
Hastings.
   After a lengthy inquiry, made longer by Hastings' challenge to
the law's constitutionality, a five-member panel of the 11th
Circuit recommended that the House begin the impeachment inquiry.
   The main charges against Hastings before the House criminal
justice subcommittee were that Hastings conspired with Borders to
take a bribe, that he had fabricated his defense to secure the
acquittal at his criminal trial and that he had compromised three
investigations by leaking the fact that the FBI hada wiretap in the
cases.
</TEXT>
