<DOCNO> AP880707-0133 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 2143EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Bartok     07-07 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bartok,0494</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Composer's Remains Laid to Final Rest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mortal remains of Hungarian-born
composer Bela Bartok were laid to final rest Thursday in the family
tomb on a Budapest hillside, 43 years after he died of leukemia in
New York.
   At least 5,000 Hungarians thronged the small Farkasret Cemetery
for the reburial, including Foreign Minister Peter Varkonyi and
pianist Annie Fischer.
   Bartok, one of the leading composers of the 20th century, was
born in 1881 in Transylvania. He left Hungary in 1940 in disgust
over its close ties with Nazi Germany and emigrated to the United
States, where he died five years later.
   ``This is a welcome home and a last farewell rolled into one
solemn ceremony,'' Jozsef Ujfalussy, former director of the Franz
Liszt Academy of Music, told the mourners. ``His music created a
new world that extended mankind's artistic horizons and tends to
universality.''
   ``He set a great human example for man's search for freedom and
humanity, and his remains now return to a nation in quest of a
newly found self-awareness,'' said Ujfalussy, author of several
monographs on Bartok.
   As part of a Unitarian burial ceremony, Bishop Joszef Ferencz
delivered a funeral oration extolling Bartok's human qualities and
moral standing.
   A monument of Swedish black granite, the work of scupltor Miklos
Borsos, marked the burial place. Borsos said it symbolizes ``an
apotheosis of music, the soul as a taking-off bird.''
   Bartok was reburied next to his two wives, his mother and an
aunt, and near his greatest friend and collaborator, Zoltan Kodaly.
   The remains were exhumed at New York's Ferncliff cemetery June
21. A brass plaque that marked Bartok's grave there was buried with
him at Farkasret.
   The ceremony was broadcast live by this Communist-ruled nation's
state radio and television.
   Peter Bartok, 64, who lives in Homosassa, Fla., and Bela Bartok
Jr., 78, accompanied their father's remains from New York on the
liner Queen Elizabeth II and then through France, West Germany and
Austria. The elder son lives in Budapest and is president of
Hungary's Unitarian Church.
   A religious choir sang the hymn ``We Have Placed Our Faith In
The Lord'' at the funeral service Thursday, then Ferencz, spiritual
leader of Hungary's 10,000 Unitarians, praised Bartok for adopting
the faith in 1916.
   ``This faith is humane tolerance itself, very much an embodiment
of what he stood for as a musician and a man,'' he said.
   Vice President Rezsoe Trautmann spoke after the Unitarian
service. He criticized some of the ``dogmatic'' events of the early
1950s, when Bartok's music was oficially frowned upon as
``formalist'' and effectively disappeared from concert programs.
   ``The return of his remains now is a great solace for the nation
as a whole,'' Trautmann said.
   At least 10,000 Hungarians and hundreds of foreign visitors
Wednesday paid their last respects to Bartok's remains at the
Academy of Sciences building.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880707-0134 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 1855EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-Balloons     07-07 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Balloons,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>International Competitors Float Over Desert in Israel's First
Balloon Race</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 40 balloonists from 15 countries
floated over the Negev Desert Thursday in Israel's first
international balloon race, with U.S. participants saying the
weather was perfect for the three-day adventure.
   Balloonists, including 20 from the United States, came to Israel
for the three-day International Hot Air Balloon Goodwill Fiesta,
organized as part of a festival in the Negev Desert highlighting
Israel's 40th anniversary celebrations.
   Ron Bush, 48, of Lubbock, Texas, said the unpredictable desert
winds forced him to make an unscheduled stop in a Bedouin village.
   ``We found that the winds were taking us quite a way from the
main road into this village,'' he said. ``We were curious, so we
made a low-level flight, about six feet off the ground, right
through the village.
   ``When we landed at the edge of the village, the boys and the
men came out to greet us,'' Bush said. ``They were very excited.
These people have never seen such a thing,'' he said.
   The children shouted ``Ahlan Wahsahlan,'' Arabic for welcome,
when the balloon touched down on Wednesday, the first part of the
race, the daily Jerusalem Post said.
   Some of the American competitors said quickly shifting desert
winds provided conditions that were just right for ballooning.
   ``It's great for balloonists,'' said Bush. ``You can pick a
current that can take you this way or that way. At home, the winds
usually blow in the same direction.''
   Paul Smith, 32, a lawyer from Albuquerque, N.M., agreed. ``The
wind speed is less than five knots on the ground for a nice easy
takeoff, and a little faster when you get up,'' Smith said.
   Bill Arras of Redmond, Ore., took the lead Wednesday. Thursday's
results were not immediately available.
   Smith said that when he landed at the end of the race Wednesday,
he came down next to some camels, ``but they just walked away from
us.''
   Participants are ranked according to how close they come to a
target, but speed is not essential, Smith said in a telephone
interview.
   He said the 70-foot-tall balloons can reach an altitude of
50,000 feet, although in the current race most floated at about
2,000 feet.
   Balloonists can only adjust the altitude of their crafts. They
navigate horizontally by latching on to wind currents taking them
in the right direction.
   The take-off field near Tel Arad, about 35 miles south of
Jerusalem, was heavily guarded by Israeli troops.
   One soldier noted the duty was ``a nice change from the West
Bank,'' referring to previous tours of duty in Israel's turbulent
occupied territories.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880707-0135 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 2202EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CriticalMaterials     07-07 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Critical Materials,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hodel Admits He Can't Do His (Part-time) Job</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interior Secretary Donald P. Hodel told
Congress on Thursday that a White House agency he heads isn't doing
the job and ought to die a natural death.
   The agency is the three-member National Critical Materials
Council, of which Hodel is chairman. The council was established in
the Executive Office of the President by Congress in 1984 to report
within a year on inventories and prospects for certain important
materials.
   Among other things, the council was supposed to coordinate
materials research by government agencies.
   That couldn't be done, Hodel said in testifying before the House
Science subcommittee on transportation, aviation and materials. ``I
have gradually and reluctantly come to the conclusion that this is
not a workable model,'' he said, and advised the subcommittee that
the legislation establishing the council be allowed to lapse
without renewal in 1990.
   ``It is extremely difficult for a three-person council ... to
move in and take a look at the very heart of mission-related
departmental programs and tell the department managers how they
ought to restructure or structure their research programs. There is
considerable resistance to doing that,'' said Hodel.
   Robert Dale Wilson, until a month ago executive director of the
council, blamed the Office of Management and Budget for delaying
the council's first report, a report Hodel said was now at the
printer.
   ``OMB directed me to delete or substantially rewrite all of
these (four) factual chapters, because, and I quote, `Giving these
facts to Congress would be like throwing raw meat to dogs,'''
Wilson said in written testimony.
   He did not indicate the specific facts in question, but said the
chapters dealt with ``the administration's notoriously flawed
proposal to sell 96 percent of the national defense stockpile, a
discussion of our recently increased dependence on the Soviet bloc
for metals, the importance of South African minerals and the
inequitable and noncompetitive impact of U.S. involvement in
funding international financial institutions ... which directly
subsidize competitors of the U.S. mining industry.''
   Wilson said the American mining industry should be helped by the
government, the council should be retained with a larger budget and
OMB's powers should be reduced: ``I have seen it override decisions
made by cabinet secretaries who opposed it. ... OMB does not want
(the council) to survive or to issue its reports in any fashion
that might be helpful to the public interest. Quite frankly, I do
not know who is served by their actions.''
   Answering questions from the subcommittee chairman, Rep. Dave
McGurdy, D-Okla., Hodel said a single administrator ``would be
stronger'' than a multimember body.
   But the council's job, he said, might better be handled by the
president's science adviser, because that adviser has experience
roaming through different departments, access to the president and,
just as important, access to the Office of Management and Budget.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
