<HEAD>With AM-Airliner Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS last graf to show Wright was bombardier, not pilot</NOTE>
<HEAD>Wright Wary of Compensation Proposals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, said
Thursday he does not necessarily endorse proposals to pay
compensation to the families of Iranians killed in the U.S.
destruction of a commercial jetliner over the Persian Gulf.
   Wright, whose district office in Fort Worth has been flooded
with angry calls over the issue, said he had been misquoted Tuesday
when questioned during a trip to London about whether the United
States should offer compensation.
   ``At no time did I say anything that would lend itself to the
interpretation that I was endorsing the idea,'' Wright told
reporters in his first news conference since returning from the
weekend trip.
   Rather, Wright said, any decision on such payments should come
from President Reagan. If the president decides to offer
compensation, Congress would likely support it, he said.
   In a national ABC News-Washington Post poll following the
incident, 61 percent of those surveyed said they did not favor
payment of compensation.
   In London on Tuesday, Wright was asked whether the United States
should offer monetary compensation for the 290 lives lost.
   He responded that it was difficult to equate money with lost
lives, but added: ``Yes, if that would assuage the grief of the
other aggrieved party, surely we could do that ... Congress would
support that if it were requested.''
   Wright also called the incident ``a very straightforward error
of misidentification.'' He told of a time during his service as a
bombardier in World War II when what he had thought were U.S. P-38
fighters began to fire on his aircraft. ``It's a human error,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
