<DOCNO> AP880707-0139 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 1904EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-OilRig-Questions     07-07 0503</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oil Rig-Questions,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Safety Questions Over North Sea Oil Rig</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BEN DOBBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABERDEEN, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roy Carey, a survivor of the world's
worst offshore oil platform disaster, said Thursday: ``We had all
that water around us and no way to get it to us. We had sprinklers
but they weren't strong enough.''
   Carey's remark as he lay badly burned in a hospital bed in
Aberdeen Royal Infirmary pointed up a bitter irony of offshore
oil-drilling, one of the world's most dangerous occupations.
   The presumed death toll from the explosion and fire Wednesday
night on the Piper Alpha platform in the North Sea exceeded 160.
   Urgent questions about safety in the offshore oil and gas
industry are being raised by the disaster, which brings to more
than 300 the number of people who have died in the British sector
of the North Sea since gas was first pumped ashore in 1967.
   Drilling accidents killed 76 and a helicopter crash killed 45.
Last year, six workers were killed and 59 seriously hurt among the
28,000 British workers.
   Three workers from Piper Alpha died after being thrown into the
sea when a gangway collapsed in 1982. In 1984, a non-fatal
explosion and fire forced the evacuation of 174 men.
   The platform, which has been producing oil since December 1976,
passed its latest annual safety inspection by the Energy Department
less than two weeks ago.
   Smoking and drinking are forbidden on oil platforms and a rescue
vessel stands by each rig at all times.
   John Brading, a London-based executive of Occidental Petroleum,
which operates the platform, said workmen had been installing a
vertical pipe linked to a seabed pipeline that runs to a new oil
field.
   The platform draws mixed oil and gas from under the seabed,
separates them and sends them ashore through separate pipelines.
   When a reporter asked if sparks from an oxyacetylene burner
could have ignited gas supplies passing through the platform,
Brading replied: ``It is much too early to draw any conclusions.''
   A company statement said the fire's cause appeared to be a gas
leak. Derek Ellington, one of the survivors, said he heard a
shrieking sound just before the explosion and believed it was gas
escaping from the separation system.
   In Parliament, lawmaker John Prescott of the opposition Labor
Party claimed inspection and maintenance of rigs had been reduced
in recent years, insufficient money was spent on training, and
government health and safety legislation did not apply fully to the
North Sea oil and gas industry.
   Energy Secretary Cecil Parkinson replied that serious North Sea
accidents had declined from 101 in 1986 to 59 last year. ``But that
is too high a figure and we wish to keep the pressure on to ensure
that improvement is maintained.''
   Labor unions have complained in the past about the quality and
avilability of survival gear and too few rescue helicopters. They
see a conflict of interest in making the Energy Department
responsible for oil production as well as safety.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
