<DOCNO> AP880707-0140 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 1906EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-OilRig-Survivors 1stLd-Writethru a0601 07-07 0817</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oil Rig-Survivors, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0601,0836</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rig Survivor: `It Was Fry And Die, Or Jump And Try'</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 7th graf pvs, `John Maxwell ...' with 7 grafs to add
quotes from other survivors; PICKS up 8th pvs bgng, `We Were ...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos LON3,4,12,20,21</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABERDEEN, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Men jumped from the blazing oil
platform or slithered down searing pipes as the heat popped windows
like bubbles, but most had no chance and comrades could only watch
helplessly from a nearby vessel.
   ``It was a case of fry and die or jump and try,'' said technican
Roy Carey, 45, who leaped into the cold North Sea to escape the
flames that engulfed the giant Piper Alpha rig after an explosion
Wednesday night.
   His face was burned and his arms were in slings. ``I was
smothered with smoke. I could hardly see and couldn't breathe, so
it was over the side or die there,'' he said from his hospital bed
in Aberdeen.
   Carey said one of the rig's survival boats floated past him and
three other men.
   They grabbed at it and a man aboard held out his hands, ``but I
couldn't get a foothold. The waves were hitting me in my chest. I
didn't want to drag him off so I just stayed in the water.''
Another boat picked him up half an hour later.
   ``We had all that water around us and no way to get it to us,''
to fight the fire, Carey said. ``We had sprinklers but they weren't
strong enough.''
   James McDonald, a 50-year-old rigger, told the Aberdeen Evening
Express he waited for about 45 minutes in the crew's quarters, then
he and three others decided to run for it through doors blocked by
flames.
   ``I wasn't going to sit down and get burned to death,'' McDonald
said. ``You either stayed where you were and burned to death or you
tried to get out.''
   He said they fought past men on packed stairways to the lower
levels of the platform, and ``I just forced my way through the
flames,'' and slid down a hose and jumped. ``The water was red
hot,'' McDonald said.
   Tony Sinnett, 34, was on the nearby support ship Tharos because
of a shortage of beds on the Piper Alpha.
   ``There was nothing that anybody could do,'' he said. ``It was
totally hopeless. It was like the platform had been hit by an
atomic bomb. There was massive mushrooms and flames shooting into
the air. I just thanked God I wasn't on board.''
   John Maxwell, another rig worker, also watched from the Tharos
as some of the more than 200 workers tried to get off the platform.
   ``We were in our survival suits ready to go to the rescue when
we saw the drill derrick giving way, falling toward the pipe deck
and possibly on the accommodation (crew's quarters) _ I don't
know,'' he said.
   ``If there were men inside then, they couldn't have survived.
They couldn't have survived all that heat.
   ``The heat was blowing out the windows. ... Panes of glass were
all cracking off and the ferocity of the heat would suck all the
oxygen out and the men inside would have smothered. It was
terrible.''
   Bill Elder, 48, a burly Scot who also had been on the Tharos,
said he watched men slide down pipes and hoses on the side of the
blazing platform.
   ``Some were swimming from the ship,'' he said. ``I felt
helpless, sick. There was panic all around. We saw 10 guys waving
from the deck. There was nothing you could do.''
   He waited at a hotel in a dirty undershirt and blue sweat suit,
cap stuffed in his pocket, to tell his story to investigators.
Elder arrived in Aberdeen by helicopter, with other survivors and
witnesses, more than 12 hours after the disaster.
   Rig worker Dave Lambert said the deck collapsed as he tried to
find a way through the flames. ``The cabin slid forward and a hole
appeared, so we made for it and jumped,'' he said. ``We fell in the
sea. It must have been 60 or 70 feet.''
   ``It was stay and get toasted or jump and chance it in the
water,'' said Lambert, 38. He was in the water several hours before
a rescue boat reached him.
   Bill Lobben, 27, his hand burned, one wrist in a cast, said he
was watching a movie when the explosion shook the platform.
   ``We didn't see any flames so I went down and got warm gear and
a survival suit and then went on the pipe deck,'' he said.
   ``There was a lot of flames and smoke there. There were more
explosions and the rig just dropped suddenly to one side. I was
terrified. I shielded myself and jumped into the water.''
   Lobben clung to a piece of debris and swam to the Tharos.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
