<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iran-Iraq     07-07 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Iraq,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq and Iran Trade Air Raids</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq said its warplanes bombed oil
targets in southwest Iran on Thursday, while Iran announced that
its air force raided military positions along its southeastern war
front.
   A war communique carried by the official Iraqi News Agency said
Iraqi bombers destroyed oil installations at Imam Hassan oilfield
and Ghorah in an attempt to keep Iran from using its petroleum
resources for ``aggressive purposes.''
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency said Iranian
fighter-bombers hit Iraqi military positions east of Basra in
southwestern Iraq.
   Both agencies were monitored in Nicosia.
   IRNA gave no specific casualty toll but said Iran's air raids
``inflicted substantial losses and casualties upon the enemy.''
   The Iraqi agency said all Iraqi air force jets returned safely
after carrying out 91 combat missions in a campaign to throttle
Iran's economic lifeline.
   No independent confirmation of the raids was available, nor did
the Tehran and Baghdad governments immediately comment on each
other's claims.
   Both Iran and Iraq reported border skirmishes in various sectors
of their 730-mile) front in the nearly 8-year-old war.
   The Iraqis have driven the Iranians out of their southern
bridgeheads on the Faw peninsula, the Salamcheh sector in the south
and the oil-rich Majnoon islands north of Basra in consecutive
assaults in the past three months.
   The last Iranian foothold left on Iraqi soil is the northern
Kurdish mountains, where the Iraqis recently claimed to have
recaptured more than a dozen peaks in heavy fighting.
   From Manama, Bahrain, came reports by shipping executives that
radio monitors picked up a distress signal in the Persian Gulf on
Thursday from a vessel that identified itself as a Romanian
freighter and gave a location close to Iran's Farsi Island.
   The executives said, however, that six hours later, they still
had not determined that it was authentic and thought it might be
another hoax.
   Distress signals purportedly sent by two other vessels Wednesday
were not confirmed.
   The executives, who spoke on condition of not being identified,
said the waterway might be suffering from a wave of hoaxes by
irresponsible radio operators, exploiting the tense situation
following Sunday's downing of an Iranian airliner by a U.S.
warship, killing all 290 aboard.
</TEXT>
