<1ST_LINE>u i AM-MalaysianLabor     07-07 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Malaysian Labor,0228</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Malaysian Trade Official's Citizenship In Jeopardy, Panel Told</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Malaysian trade union official is threatened
with loss of his citizenship for discussing with American labor
leaders the issue of ending U.S. trade concessions for Malaysia, a
Congressional hearing was told Thursday.
   Eric Schwartz, program director of Asia Watch, a private U.S.
human rights monitoring group, said there are demands in Malaysia
to strip Vethamuthu David, opposition member of the Malaysian
Parliament and trade union official of his citizenship.
   David is under fire, he said, for discussing with America's
largest Labor Federation, the AFL-CIO, its petition to cancel trade
concessions given Malaysia under the U.S. system of preferences for
developing countries.
   Schwartz quoted AFL-CIO officials as telling him talks with
David did not influence their decision to file the petition.
   David was detained on his return to Malaysia from attending the
AFL-CIO convention as a guest last October and only recently
released. He was among more than 100 people detained without trial
last autumn under the Malaysian Internal Security Law.
   AFL-CIO spokesman Rex Hardesty said the union wanted Malaysia
removed from the concessions group because, among other reasons, of
its violations of the rights of labor leaders to associate.
``Malaysia's violation of the right of free association is not
confined to the illegal detention of David,'' he said.
</TEXT>
