<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 1946EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SalemBombings     07-07 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salem Bombings,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Feds Offer $5,000 Reward For Bombing Information</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal investigators offered a $5,000 reward
Thursday for information leading to an arrest in the placing of 13
homemade bombs under bridges and behind buildings in this community.
   The Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms offered the reward
because of the ``inherent danger to the public safety caused by the
explosive devices,'' said spokesman Joe Thurman.
   The bombs were found Tuesday in this small southern Indiana
community about 30 miles north of Louisville, Ky. Some of the
devices detonated, causing small fires, but no one was injured.
   Thurman said investigators continued to canvass the business
district and neighborhoods, searching for clues that might lead to
a suspect.
   ``We keep hoping each lead we run down is the one, but so far we
don't have any suspects,'' he said.
   Thurman declined to say whether investigators had been able to
track down the source of the dynamite used to make the devices,
which were found in paper grocery sacks.
   ``We're not going to talk about the device components. We'd just
as soon keep quiet about that,'' Thurman said. ``It's normal
procedure. The people we're looking for don't need us to tell them
what we're looking at.''
   Thurman said there were about 35 outside investigators working
on the case, representing the ATF, the FBI, the Indiana State
Police and the U.S. Army.
   ``It's just a big investigation, and it's taking some time to
run down the leads,'' Thurman said.
   Life for the 6,000 Salem residents had returned to normal by
Thursday.
   ``There's no areas blocked off, or anything like that,'' Thurman
said. ``As far as I can see, things are back to normal _ other than
you have a town full of strangers here running around asking
questions.''
   He said residents had been urged to report any suspicious
packages.
   ``We hope there aren't any more out there, but people should be
aware that there could be another one out there. We hope we got
them all,'' Thurman said.
</TEXT>
