<1ST_LINE>u w AM-BankBill     07-07 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bank Bill,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bill Would Permit Bank Holding Companies To Underwrite Many
Securities</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: St Germain, no period, is cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the House Banking Committee on
Thursday proposed legislation that would permit bank holding
companies to underwrite many securities.
   The long-awaited bill from Rep. Fernand J. St Germain, D-R.I.,
also would require banks to cash Social Security and other
government checks and abolish an agency set up to sell property
from insolvent savings institutions.
   It would reverse, in large part, restrictions on the mixing of
investment and commercial banking that have been in place since the
1933 passage of the Glass-Steagall Act.
   Securities subsidiaries of bank holding companies would be able
to underwrite and deal in corporate bonds, commercial paper,
municipal revenue bonds and securities backed by mortgages and
other kinds of loans.
   Banks would be precluded from underwriting in two major
securities areas: corporate stocks and mutual funds. However, the
subsidiaries would be able to sell mutual funds underwritten by
others.
   The legislation provides for various ``fire walls'' to prevent
losses in the securities affiliate from affecting the safety and
soundness of bank deposits.
   Other provisions require securities subsidiaries to be regulated
by the Securities and Exchange Commission. Also, to prevent any
confusion by consumers with insured deposits in a bank, the
securities subsidiary could not share a name, logo, advertising or
location with an affiliated bank.
   This is St Germain's second try at fashioning a bill that would
attract enough votes to pass his committee. In March, a week before
the Senate passed broad legislation including bank underwriting of
mutual funds and corporate stock, St Germain offered a much more
restrictive bill.
   The latest effort is more permissive. In a statement, St Germain
called it a ``consensus document'' and predicted it would get broad
support in his committee and on the House floor. Aides said a
committee vote likely will be held by the end of July.
   However, a spokeswoman for the banking industry's largest trade
group, the American Bankers Association, said bankers, who support
the Senate bill, are disappointed with the proposal.
   ``The price of paying for new consumer protections far outweighs
any benefits banks would get from entering new areas,'' ABA
spokeswoman Mary-Liz Meany said.
   In return for getting new powers, banks are being asked to cash
government checks presented by non-customers, a measure aimed at
helping Social Security and welfare recipients who can't afford to
maintain a bank account. They also will be required to offer
low-fee ``lifeline'' checking accounts for depositors with less
than $1,000.
   Also, the bill gives a break to big competitors of banks _
so-called non-bank banks owned by Sears and other commercial
companies _ which make loans or accept deposits but not both. A law
enacted last summer restricted a non-bank bank's growth to 7
percent a year. However, St Germain's legislation would lift the
limit for two years.
   And, the bill curbs expansion of banks' insurance and real
estate powers.
   An unrelated provision abolishes the Federal Asset Disposition
Association, which has been accused of wasting money and doing a
poor job of disposing of loans and real estate from closed savings
institutions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
