<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ohio Valley and Great Lakes Region Baking in the Heat</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Record-breaking heat continued to scorch states in the upper
Ohio Valley and the Great Lakes Thursday, while thunderstorms
flooded parts of western Kansas, the Oklahoma Panhandle and the
northern Texas Panhandle.
   As temperatures climbed into the upper 90s and low 100s, at
least two dozen cities broke temperature records for the date.
   In Elkins, W.Va., Thursday was the ninth day that a temperature
record has been broken since June 1.
   Many of the records broken Thursday had stood more than a
century; for example, Erie, Pa., broke a record that existed 114
years.
   Record highs for Thursday included Akron, Ohio, 99; Albany,
N.Y., 97; Binghamton, N.Y., 91; Charleston, W.Va., 99; Cleveland,
97; Detroit, 100; Duluth, Minn., 95; Elkins, W.Va., 93; Erie, Pa.,
94; Flint, Mich., 98; Fort Wayne, Ind., 102; Harrisburg, Pa., 100;
Huntington, W.Va., 99; Mansfield, Ohio, 97; Marquette, Mich., 95;
Muskegon, Mich., 93; Pittsburgh, Pa., 101; Rochester, N.Y., 97;
Sault Ste. Marie, Mich, 96; South Bend, Ind., 97; Toledo, Ohio,
101; Williamsport, Pa., 100; Youngstown, Ohio, 98; Washington,
D.C., 101.
   In parts of the Oklahoma Panhandle, some 2 inches of rain fell
Thursday morning, and widespread flooding was reported east of
Guymon, Okla., with Highway 3 under water.
   Flooding also was reported in Texas, where Highway 136 was under
water between Borger and Stinnett. Three inches of rain was
measured near Oberlin, Kan.
   Strong thunderstorms were developing across eastern Colorado and
southeast Wyoming, and a severe thunderstorm watch was effect for
those regions.
   While record highs were being set in many places, a few U.S.
cities also saw record low temperatures for the date, including
Macon, Ga., with 58 degrees and Wilmington, N.C., with 59.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 105
degrees at Needles, Calif., to 57 degrees at Crescent City, Calif.,
and Fort Ord, Calif. The low temperature for the nation Thursday
morning was 29 at West Yellowstone, Mont.
   The national forecast Friday called for hot weather to prevail
again throughout much of the nation. Showers and thunderstorms
should be scattered from the central and southern Plains into the
central Rocky Mountain region, throughout the Gulf Coast region
into the Florida Panhandle, and over central New England.
   Temperatures were forecast to be in the 90s throughout much of
the eastern third of the country, with some temperatures
approaching 100 in the Great Lakes region and the upper Ohio
Valley. Temperatures in the 80s were expected in the Pacific
Northwest, the Rocky Mountain region and Great Plains. Highs should
reach the 90s in eastern Montana and Nevada, with 100s in the
desert Southwest and 70s along the northern California coast.
</TEXT>
