<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 2010EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-McKay-Meese     07-07 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-McKay-Meese,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>McKay Forwards Report on Meese to Justice Department</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Meese Successor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Independent counsel James McKay said Thursday
he has referred his 830-page report on Attorney General Edwin Meese
III to the Justice Department, a step which could result in an
ethics review of Meese.
   McKay sent the report, the result of a 14-month criminal
investigation of the attorney general, to Solicitor General Charles
Fried in Fried's capacity as acting attorney general.
   Fried ultimately will have the authority to turn it over to the
Office of Professional Responsibility, which investigates
accusations of improper conduct within the Justice Department.
   For now, however, the special three-member federal appeals court
which appointed McKay has issued an order which directs that those
holding copies of the report not discuss it with anyone.
   Asked whether an ethics review was imminent, Justice Department
spokesman Patrick Korten said only that the report ``is being
handled in the ordinary course.''
   Acting on an order by the appeals court panel, McKay also sent
the report to Meese's lawyers _ Nathan Lewin and James Rocap _ who
refused to take reporters' telephone calls. A secretary in their
office, citing the court order, said the attorneys weren't
permitted to discuss the report with anyone.
   McKay said April 1 that if he decided that no criminal
prosecution of Meese was warranted, he would refer all the matters
he had investigated to ``the appropriate administrative
authorities.''
   When Meese announced his plans Tuesday to leave the government
in late July or early August, his aides said there wouldn't be an
Office of Professional Responsibility probe because of the attorney
general's impending departure. On Wednesday, however, after other
Justice Department sources disputed that assessment, Korten
acknowledged that an ethics review by OPR was possible.
   OPR has the power to recommend sanctions ranging from reprimand
to dismissal, but it also in the past has conducted reviews of
employees who were leaving the department.
   The Justice Department's deputy attorney general, Harold
Christensen, and Associate Attorney General Francis Keating,
outrank Fried, but are filling their jobs on an acting basis.
Therefore, the report was referred to Fried.
   McKay said anyone who believes he or she is named in the report
and wishes to respond should notify the independent counsel's
office, which will provide the portion of the report relating to
that person.
   McKay's office launched a criminal investigation of Meese on May
11, 1987, and ended it Tuesday by submitting the report to the
court.
   The independent counsel has been examining the involvement of
Meese, at the request of his longtime friend E. Robert Wallach,
with scandal-plagued Wedtech Corp. in 1981 and 1982, when Meese was
White House counselor. McKay also has been looking into Meese's
involvement, again at Wallach's behest, on behalf of a $1 billion
proposed Iraqi oil pipeline project in 1985.
   McKay reviewed the attorney general's meetings with and decision
on behalf of executives of the regional Bell telephone companies at
a time when he held $14,000 in telephone stock.
   The independent counsel also looked into the fact that members
of a Washington real estate family, through a foundation, arranged
to pay a $40,000-a-year salary for Meese's wife while leasing
office space to the Justice Department.
   Wallach was involved with Meese in both the phone stock and Mrs.
Meese's job.
</TEXT>
