<1ST_LINE>u a AM-TridentLaunch     07-07 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trident Launch,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trident Missile Fails Test Launch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy had to destroy a Trident 2
missile in flight Thursday night, the second failure in 13 test
launchings of the new submarine-based missile, authorities said.
   The 44-foot, $23.7-million missile, carrying a dummy warhead
package, blazed away from a land launch pad at 6:38 p.m. EDT after
a flawless countdown and darted quickly into heavy clouds. But the
Navy later issued a statement reporting a problem developed during
first-stage flight.
   The range safety officer sent a radio signal 60 seconds after
liftoff to blow apart the missile so that pieces would fall
harmlessly into the Atlantic Ocean and not threaten land, the Navy
said.
   The statement said the cause of the malfunction could not be
determined immediately.
   The three-stage Trident 2 was to have hurled its warhead package
to an Atlantic Ocean target several thousand miles to the
southeast. The weapon has a range of nearly 6,000 miles but its
intended range Thursday night was not disclosed.
   The test was the 13th of 20 land pad launches planned here, to
be followed by at least five submarine launch tests. The weapon is
scheduled to become operational late next year.
   The test program began in January 1987 and reeled off nine
straight successes before logging a failure last January. It had
recorded two more successes before Thursday night's malfunction.
   Each Trident 2 is designed to hurl up to 10 nuclear warheads to
different targets. There are to be 24 of the weapons aboard each of
nine planned Trident submarines.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
