<DOCNO> AP880707-0151 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 2258EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ForeignAid     07-07 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Foreigssociated Press Writer=</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate on Thursday adopted a $14.3 billion
fiscal 1989 foreign aid bill that would revive U.S. contributions
to the World Bank, which makes development loans to Third World
countries. The vote was 75-15.
   The measure has been remarkably without controversy this year,
in part because of last year's agreement between Congress and
President Reagan that smoothed the way for this year's money bills.
   If signed into law, the bill would be the first free-standing
foreign aid money bill to be completed since 1981. Since then, aid
money has been rolled into large omnibus spending measures each
year.
   The Senate version would provide $71 million as the U.S.
contribution to a recapitalization of the World Bank under a new
five-year commitment to boost lending authority.
   The Senate rejected an attept by Sen. J. Gordon Humphrey,
R-N.H., to withhold the aid unless the bank changed its practices
to make loans no more favorable than those available from other
sources to U.S. borrowers.
   But the Senate did adopt an amendment offered by Sen. Phil
Gramm, R-Texas, to withhold $1.2 billion in U.S. contributions to
all multilateral development banks if needed to meet next year's
deficit-reduction target.
   The House version of the bill, which was approved May 25, does
not include the World Bank contribution, and would need additional
authorizing legislation before the money could flow.
   The legislation is the primary vehicle for U.S. economic and
military aid to friendly foreign countries. As usual, the largest
chunk of aid goes to Israel, which would get $1.2 billion in
economic and $1.8 billion in military assistance. Egypt is the
second-largest recipient, with $815 million in economic and $1.3
billion in military aid.
   Other major aid allocations include the Philippines, which would
get $125 million in military aid, $124 million in economic aid and
$40 million for development; $500 million to an African development
fund, $101 million to an international drug control program. Turkey
would receive $500 million in military aid and Greece $350 million.
   In Central America, El Salvador would receive $185 million in
economic support, Guatemala $80 million, Costa Rica $90 million,
and Honduras $85 million.
   The bill also would continue a ban on aid to Panama, where
strongman Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega continues to defy U.S.
efforts to remove him from power, including elimination of Panama's
lucrative U.S. sugar sales quota.
   The bill also includes a cut in aid to Pakistan, which would
receive $210 million in economic and $220 million in military aid.
The total is $10 million less than the House earmarked and $60
million less than the administration requested.
   Pakistan has received favorable treatment in recent years
because of its status as a conduit for U.S. aid to the anti-Soviet
rebels in neighboring Afghanistan. As the Soviet Union withdraws
its troops, some in Congress are beginning to call for a
re-examination of U.S. aid.
   In addition, the bill makes available $50 million to aid Afghan
refugees and $362 million for other refugee programs, $157 million
for the Peace Corps, $40 million for an international program to
combat AIDS and $1 million for the Solidarity trade union in Poland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
