<HEAD>Iran Denies Desire for Direct Contact with the U.S.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A spokesman for Iran's Foreign Ministry
on Thursday denied statements by U.S. Secretary of State George P.
Shultz that Iran recently tried to open direct talks with
Washington, it was reported.
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency agency, monitored in
Nicosia, said the Foreign Ministry dismissed claims by Shultz that
Iranian officials had sent messages through third parties
indicating a desire to open diplomatic discussions with the United
States.
   The unidentifed Foreign Ministry spokesman described Shultz's
claim as ``futile efforts'' to divert world public attention from
Sunday's downing of an Iranian passenger airliner by a U.S. missile
cruiser in the Persian Gulf. All 290 people aboard the jetliner
were killed.
   The New York Times published a report Wednesday quoting Shultz
as saying, ``we've had a number of probes ... from Iran through
various third parties saying that they'd like to talk with us, and
we've responded to those.''
   The newspaper said Shultz declined to identify the Iranian
officials involved and that he would not speculate on what effect
the airliner attack might have on the previous proposal.
   The Iranian spokesman said Shultz's report also aimed at cooling
down the fury of the Iranian people over the U.S. ``crime and
legitimizing its illegal military presence in the gulf.''
