<2ND_LINE>AM-NIreland-Bomb, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0811,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb in Swimming Pool Building Kills 2, Wounds 4</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughtout to UPDATE with police saying more than one
gunman involved; CORRECTS age of man killed; details. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb placed by a gang of
gunmen exploded against the inside wall of a public swimming pool
building Thursday, killing two people and wounding four, police
said.
   The Royal Ulster Constabulary said the bomb apparently was meant
to bring the wall down on a security patrol that was passing by in
the Falls Road, a predominantly Roman Catholic area of west
Belfast, but the timing was wrong.
   The explosion missed the patrol and all the casualties were
civilians, including a 4-year-old girl who was slightly injured.
   A police spokesman said a group of armed men came into the
building and ordered swimmers to leave. They held the pool staff at
gunpoint while they placed the explosive device. Police said the
gunmen escaped and the bomb exploded a while later.
   Those killed in the explosion were a 60-year-old woman and a
24-year-old man, police said.
   Asked if anybody telephoned to warn police about the bomb in the
interval between the gunmen's escape and the explosion, a police
spokesman said: ``You'll have to draw your own conclusion about
that.''
   The Falls Road is a guerrilla stronghold and the implication of
the spokesman's comment was that no warning was telephoned either
because those involved feared guerrilla reprisals or because they
sympathized with the guerrillas' cause.
   There was no immediate claim of responsibility, but police said
it bore the hallmarks of an attack by the outlawed Irish Republican
Army. The mainly Catholic IRA targets security forces in its
guerrilla war to end British rule in predominantly Protestant
Northern Ireland and unite it with the overwhelmingly Catholic
Republic of Ireland under socialist rule.
</TEXT>
