<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 2123EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SovietVisit     07-07 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Visit,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Marshal Tours Camp Lejeune</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with details of Marine
demonstration, Soviet marshal's reaction, Crowe quotes, Soviet
delegation's tentative schedule. Picks up 5th graf pvs, ``One of
...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first Soviet official ever to
visit Camp Lejeune watched U.S. Marines train Thursday and gave the
``thumbs up'' sign as a Harrier jet completed a vertical takeoff
and roared over the reviewing stand.
   ``I do believe he was impressed,'' said U.S. Navy Adm. William
J. Crowe Jr., chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, who
accompanied the Soviet Marshal Sergei Fedorovich Akhromeyev.
   Crowe related that Akhromeyev, who is on a tour of military
installations, tapped him on the shoulder and gave him the sign as
the two watched the demonstration at the base.
   Akhromeyev, chief of the general staff of the Soviet Union,
watched a task force exercise involving Marine infantry units,
tanks, helicopters and in-flight refueling, as well as the Harrier
attack jets, which lift into the air from a standstill.
   ``He (Akhromeyev) wanted to talk to them (the Marines),'' Crowe
said. ``He is very pleasant and easy to be with. It's an historic
occasion and I'm proud to host him.''
   Gen. Alfred M. Gray, commandant of the Marine Corps, said after
the demonstration that he suggested a joint training operation with
the Soviets to Akhromeyev, chief of the general staff of the Soviet
Union.
   ``He just laughed,'' Gray said.
   The Soviet delegation, which includes ranking officers from most
of the Soviet armed forces, arrived at New River air station
Thursday morning on a U.S. Air Force jet from Washington. The
group, which arrived in the United States Tuesday, is scheduled to
stay in the country at least through Monday.
   ``One of the goals for this visit is to enhance the credibility
of deterrence by giving him a feel for the quality of our military.
Seeing is believing, and believing is important in this business,''
said Army Lt. Col. Arnold Williams, a Pentagon spokesman.
   Crowe and the Soviets are scheduled to visit the Navy's newest
aircraft carrier, the Theodore Roosevelt, in the Virginia Capes
region. They also will observe Army main battle tanks at Fort Hood,
Texas; and see a new B-1B bomber in South Dakota.
   The field marshal and his party, which includes ranking officers
from most of the Soviet armed forces, will attend a rodeo and
barbecue on a cattle ranch in Oklahoma and see the Alamo in San
Antonio, Texas, on Saturday. Other stops include colonial
Williamsburg, Va., and New York City.
</TEXT>
