<1ST_LINE>u a AM-RoofCollapses-Scene     07-07 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Roof Collapses-Scene,0392</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Workers Struggle to Locate Survivors</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos BRO1,2,3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As growling front-end loaders bit
giant chunks of debris from what had been his department store,
owner Bernard Levine voiced amazement at being alive.
   ``I was lucky. God was with me. Not a scratch,'' he said.
   At least seven people died and 60 were injured when the roof of
Levine's three-story Amigo Store collapsed during a driving
rainstorm.
   Three hundred rescue workers, using everything from dump trucks
to wheelbarrows, carefully dug into the debris hoping to find
survivors.
   ``I need an ax,'' one worker high on the pile of debris shouted
in English, then Spanish.
   Hundreds of onlookers, held back by police sawhorses, strained
to get closer to the site.
   As Police Sgt. Dean Poos prepared to brief reporters, a woman
approached and asked in heavily accented English, ``Children?''
   ``No children,'' the policeman replied somberly.
   U.S. Border Patrol and Customs agents brought in dogs which
usually hunt drugs to search for people possibly trapped.
   The rubble _ crushed cinderblocks, broken brick and glass,
twisted steel _ was speckled with remnants of merchandise Levine
had been selling moments before disaster struck.
   T-shirts, caps, hats, a little girl's dress were strewn in with
the piles broken concrete.
   Several dozen rescue workers formed a human chain up the nearly
three-story mound to hand debris down, piece by piece. Officials
ordered them to move carefully, fearing that sudden shifts might
cause a further collapse. Portable lights were hauled in so work
could continue through the night.
   The light brown building was 19 years old and located on one of
Brownsville's main downtown streets, about a block from the
international bridge across the Rio Grande from Matamoros, Mexico.
   Police Officer Javier Saenz, who was near the store when the
roof caved in, was among those who struggled to find survivors.
   ``When we got to the front of the business, we saw two persons
that already looked dead. They were just between the cement, the
concrete or whatever,'' Saenz said.
   The policemen said he and other officers managed to rescue five
people from a breach in the wall of the adjacent store. ``We took
them out through the wall at Woolworth's,'' he said.
</TEXT>
