<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 4thLd-Writethru a0819 07-07 0911</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0819,860</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says Bush A Newcomer To Affirmative Action; Flip-Flopper
On Taxes</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 10th graf pvs with 1 graf, bgng: ``Some people, to
UDPATE with more Dukakis comment to Hispanic group</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis on Thursday questioned
Republican George Bush's ``rather late'' commitment to affirmative
action and accused the vice president of breaking his pledge not to
support new taxes.
   Dukakis, before heading West for three days of presidential
campaigning, also called again on President Reagan and Bush to
support trade legislation that includes a plant-closing
notification provision.
   He refused to say whether he would select a running mate next
week, but with Democratic National Convention less than two weeks
away, conceded he would have to make up his mind ``in the not so
distant future.''
   Bush, the presumed Republican nominee, promised Wednesday that
he would appoint a Hispanic to his Cabinet if elected president.
   ``It strikes me that this is a rather late commitment,'' said
Dukakis, who made a similar pledge a year ago. ``I don't know where
he has been for the past eight years.''
   Like Bush, Dukakis refused to extend an absolute commitment to
women and other minority groups but invited examination of his
state appointments and said his record on affirmative action stood
in ``dramatic contrast'' to the Reagan-Bush administration.
   ``I expect to have women, black citizens, Hispanic citizens,''
Dukakis said.
   Dukakis flew to Dallas, where he spoke to the annual convention
League of United Latin American Citizens, or LULAC. A day earlier,
Bush spoke to the same group and made his pledge to appoint a
Hispanic American to his cabinet.
   The Massachusetts governor continued to jab at Bush.
   ``Some people think it's enough to wake up after eight years and
then promise opportunity for one Hispanic. I want to stand with you
and create opportunity for 20 million Hispanic citizens across the
country,'' he said.
   ``I've campaigned fom one end of this country to another, and I
know that we Americans are ready for a change,'' Dukakis added.
``We're tired of waiting for opportunity to trickle down from a few
privileged neighborhoods into our cities and into the small
communities of rural America.''
   Dukakis made some of his remarks in Spanish.
   Earlier, in Boston, Dukakis said Bush had broken his pledge to
oppose any new taxes by supporting a provision of the trade bill
that calls for $1 billion in taxes for job training programs and
catastrophic health care legislation that included $6 billion in
taxes on elderly people who opt for the comprehensive care.
   ``So much for iron-clad no tax commitments,'' said Dukakis, who
himself had to renege on a no-tax pledge in his first term as
governor.
   Bush, who was in Dukakis' hometown for the day, hit back.
   ``I'm against raising taxes, and I think recent events here in
this state that I don't plan to go into demonstrate we have a
different view on taxes,'' he said. That was a clear reference to
Dukakis' recent signing of a cigarette tax and the governor's
support for another tax-hike measure.
   The Bush campaign also quarreled with Dukakis' assertion.
   ``The vice president's campaign pledge not to raise tax is
iron-clad and it's not going to change,'' added Mark Goodin, a Bush
spokesman. He said neither of the proposals Dukakis mentioned
involved tax increases.
   ``He is dead wrong on both counts and he is trying to blow smoke
into the room,'' Goodin said.
   Reagan earlier this year vetoed major trade legislation because
it contained a provision requiring employers to give 60 days'
notice before closing plants. The measure has won overwhelming
Senate approval for a second time and is awaiting action in the
House.
   ``The president opposes it, the vice president opposes it, I
don't know why,'' Dukakis said.
   Dukakis said American workers deserved such notice and said the
issue represented ``the fundamental difference in what a Democratic
administration would mean to this country.''
   Dukakis has been dogged at home by a fiscal 1988 deficit and a
struggle to balance the budget for fiscal 1989, which began last
week.
   Legislation to erase the defict and close the books on fiscal
1988 is working its way through he Legislature, although portions
of the administration's plan remain controversial, and a compromise
on the new budget was reached Wednesday.
   Dukakis said he expected final passage of both by the end of
next week.
   ``If there is one thing we are committed to doing in this state
it is to making sure we have a strong fiscal foundation,'' Dukakis
said.
   Some local Dukakis critics have contended that the governor has
been late dealing with budget problems because he is preoccupied
with his search for a running mate, a process which included
interviews with eight contenders in the past two weeks.
   Georgia Sen. Sam Nunn removed himself from consideration.
Dukakis said that none of the remaining seven have been ruled out.
They are Sens. John Glenn of Ohio, Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee,
Lloyd Bentsen of Texas and Bob Graham of Florida, Reps. Richard
Gephardt of Missouri and Lee Hamilton of Indiana and Jesse Jackson.
   Paul Brountas, Dukakis' campaign chairman and closest adviser,
has been in Washington this week researching the vice presidential
contenders and is expected to remain there through Friday. Dukakis
is due back in Boston late Saturday.
   Dukakis aides expect Dukakis and Brountas to meet during the
weekend and predict an announcement next week.
</TEXT>
