<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DestroyerSlaying 1stLd-Writethru a0683 07-07 0713</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Destroyer Slaying, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0683,0728</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trial Begins for Navy Man Charged With Murder in Shipboard Robbery</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 5 grafs after 7th graf, ``There are ...'' to UPDATE
with later testimony; Picks up 8th graf pvs bgng `The prosecutor
...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By IKE FLORES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MAYPORT NAVAL STATION, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Navy petty officer charged
with murdering a disbursement officer during the robbery of a
$94,000 payroll had plenty of money and was wrongly accused, his
lawyer said Thursday in opening arguments.
   Petty Officer 1st Class Ruben Colon, 34, had saved more than
$100,000 and was preparing to leave the service after 15 years, the
attorney, Lt. Matthew Michels, told a court-martial panel.
   However, prosecutors told the five-officer panel that Colon was
tailed by Navy investigators to the bank where $87,000 in cash and
2,575 U.S. Treasury checks were found in a safe deposit box rented
in Colon's name.
   Colon, of Vega Baja, Puerto Rico, faces the death penalty if he
is convicted of the murder charge. The Navy has not executed anyone
since an 1849 mutiny.
   Lt. j.g. Ratish Prasad, disbursing officer of the destroyer John
Hancock, was bound, strangled and shot with a .38-caliber handgun
March 15 in a robbery of the warship's payroll. The weapon has
never been found.
   Michels argued there was nothing to link his client to the
slaying or to the items found in the safe deposit box.
   ``There are no fingerprints on the money or checks or the (safe
deposit) box,'' said Michels, calling the government's case purely
circumstantial.
   Evidence submitted to the court shows that Colon's driver's
license was used as proof of Florida residence to purchase a
.38-caliber revolver three days before the robbery-murder.
   But store clerk Cheryl Crismas of Southside Guns, who testified
said she sold the weapon March 12, said she listed the purchaser as
Ruben ``Cohen'' and she couldn't identify the defendant in court.
   Dr. Bonifacio Floro, deputy chief medical examiner for the City
of Jacksonville, conducted an autopsy on the victim's body and
concluded that the primary cause of death was a gunshot fired at
point-blank range into Prasad's left temple. He said the victim was
``probably kneeling when he was shot in the head.''
   Larry D. Smith of the Florida Department of Law Enforcement
Crime Lab testified the ropes that bound Prasad's feet and neck
were similar to rope found in Colon's apartment. But Smith said he
could find no fiber evidence from the victim's clothing or the
crime scene to match that of the defendant's.
   Investigators had ``two primary suspects that should still be
suspects,'' Michels said.
   The prosecutor, Lt. Daniel Glary, told the jury that Colon
bought a .38-caliber revolver three days before the robbery-murder.
He also said witnesses will testify that Colon lied about his
movements during and after the slaying.
   ``Much of the government's case is circumstantial ... but the
case against this defendant is devastating,'' Glary said.
   Colon, who was Marine Corps military police officer before his
Navy service, is a qualified weapons expert and was an electronic
warfare technician for the Navy.
   He is also charged with the victim's kidnapping, which carries a
life sentence; robbery, with a 15-year sentence; and receiving
stolen property, with a three-year sentence.
   It takes a vote of at least four of the five jurors to convict
on any of the charges. But the death penalty cannot be considered
unless the murder conviction is unanimous.
   The prosecution said it would introduce a bank witness who will
testify that Colon rented the box in which the cash and checks were
found by agents of the Naval Investigative Service. The agents were
tipped off by bank officials who became suspicious about renting
out their largest box to a sailor.
   Shortly after the robbery-slaying, Colon took leave and told
friends upon his return that he was going to leave the Navy so he
could provide a better living for his family.
   Michels told jurors that Colon had fathered a child seven years
ago while stationed in the Philippines and that the mother had
recently joined him here.
   Colon was arrested April 12, almost a month after the crime.
   The judge, Cmdr. John A. Studer, said he expected the military
trial to last about two weeks.
</TEXT>
