<1ST_LINE>u a AM-JuiceTampering 1stLd-Writethru a0730 07-07 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Juice Tampering, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0730,0582</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poison Threats Prompt Heightened Market Security, No Arrests</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs figure in 2nd graf and subs final graf with 2 grafs to
UPDATE with year-end FDA figures on tampering complaints.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said Thursday they had few clues to
who punctured orange juice cartons with hypodermic needles at three
suburban markets this week and left notes warning of poison.
   A national expert on product tampering warned that widespread
news coverage of the cases could prompt ``copycat'' crimes and
noted there were more than 700 reports of product tampering across
the country last year.
   No one drank from any of the juice cartons, discovered Monday,
Tuesday and Wednesday at three supermarkets within a few miles in
the San Fernando Valley suburbs. Police tests were incomplete, but
one grocery store test cleared the first carton of cyanide
contamination.
   Investigators have yet to find anyone who saw any of the
tampering and are hampered in fingerprint checks because of the
number of people who handle cartons in stores, said police Lt. Fred
Nixon.
   ``We're treating it as very high priority despite the fact that
we don't know for certain that there is contamination present. In
either case it's still a crime,'' Nixon said.
   Police advised consumers, particularly near the affected stores,
25 miles northwest of downtown, to check cartons before buying.
   The three supermarket chains involved, Vons, Hughes and Alpha
Beta, all stepped up security in stores in the area, company
spokesmen said. Involved were two national orange juice brands,
Coca Cola Co.'s Minute Maid and Procter & Gamble's Citrus Hill.
   In each case, a two-quart carton of orange juice was removed
from the refrigerator case and punctured with the needle from a
hypodermic syringe. The cartons, with the needles still attached,
were found by customers or employees on shelves elsewhere in the
markets, each with a note attached suggesting poison had been
injected.
   California law makes threats of tampering with food or drugs a
misdemeanor and actually contaminating a product a felony. The FBI
is evaluating the case to see if federal felony tampering statutes
apply, said spokesman Fred Reagan.
   Investigators withheld some details of the tampering to make it
easier to identify possible imitators.
   Research suggests that one nationally publicized case of product
tampering leads to 30 ``copycat'' crimes across the country, said
Park Elliott Dietz, a psychiatrist at the University of Virginia in
Charlottesville who studies such cases and has consulted for the
FBI.
   ``The major determinant of how many cases there will be in the
next three months is how widely this is publicized,'' Dietz said in
a telephone interview. ``The consensus of how to handle this is to
make sure the public is informed about potential risk _ in that
geographic area.''
   According to statistics from the Food and Drug Administration,
threatened and actual product tampering increased ninefold in 1986,
to 1,698 reported cases, after the death of a New York woman who
took a poisoned Tylenol pain capsule.
   In 1987, the FDA received 774 consumer complaints of tampering
with food, drugs and other regulated products, and confirmed 84
cases of tampering with packages or their contents.
   Cases of threats combined with some form of tampering, as in the
California incidents, are much more rare, said Richard Swanson,
director of emergency operations for the FDA. He wasn't able to
provide statistics on such cases.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
