<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WritersStrike 2ndLd-Writethru a0809 07-07 0765</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Writers Strike, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0809,0779</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Writers Strike Move Fails to Produce Results; Fox Forces Vacations</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 6th graf `The significance' with
estimate of number of writers returning to work. Picks up 7th graf
`Walton said...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST HOLLYWOOD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking movie and TV
scriptwriters announced Thursday they overwhelmingly approved an
interim contract that will put writers back to work for at least 13
production companies, including the makers of the ``Rambo'' movies.
   Members of the Writers Guild of America, who cast ballots
Wednesday night in New York and Los Angeles, approved the interim
pact by an 8-1 margin, union President George Kirgo said Thursday.
   ``This will help bring this town back to work,'' Kirgo said,
referring to the 18-week strike that has stalled production in
Hollywood and forced postponement of the start of the fall
television season.
   The interim contracts with independent producers are a union
effort to split the ranks of the industry's bargaining group, the
Alliance of Motion Picture and Television Producers.
   Thirteen companies have already signed the new deal, including
Carolco Pictures, makers of the ``Rambo'' movies, and actress
Shelly Duvall's Platypus Productions Inc., union officials said.
   ``The significance of this vote for the industry is that there
is one remaining obstacle to getting this town back to work, and
it's not the Writers Guild of America,'' said Brian Walton,
executive director of the union's western division.
   Walton predicted that the new interim agreement, in conjunction
with a previously approved independent contract, would mean 300 to
500 writers would resume work in coming weeks.
   Walton said the producers' alliance is pressing independent
companies to spurn the interim pact.
   The union earlier approved a different independent contract, and
as of Thursday 124 mostly small production companies had signed
that pact.
   ABC and CBS officials said earlier Thursday they wouldn't use
any programming made by independent producers. NBC and Fox
Broadcasting Co. officials had said they would not enter into new
deals with independent production companies that signed contracts
with the WGA during the strike.
   ``We strongly believe that the economic issues remaining in this
labor dispute with the WGA are directly related to the long-term
viability of the television industry,'' ABC Entertainment President
Brandon Stoddard said through a spokeswoman.
   ``We feel that independent production companies, tempted to sign
the interim agreements, would be prolonging the strike and
contributing to further industry uncertainty without gaining any
real advantage,'' she said.
   ``CBS completely supports the industry position in its dealings
with the Writers Guild. We do not believe it is in the best
interests of any producer to sign the interim agreement the WGA is
offering. In support of that position, we will not enter into any
new agreements for product produced under the interim WGA
agreement,'' the network said in a statement issued Thursday.
   ``The economic issues in this labor dispute bear importantly on
the continued health of our entire industry. It is clearly in
everyone's best interest to end this strike as soon as possible. We
believe that acceptance of the WGA interim agreement will prolong
this strike to the disadvantage of all,'' the statement said.
   ``NBC's greatest hope is that this lengthy strike comes to a
swift settlement, and the writers go back to work. We don't feel we
are in a position to give economic or business advice on a series
of complex issues,'' NBC said in a statement released in New York.
   NBC earlier had confirmed separate agreements to continue
production of ``The Cosby Show,'' ``A Different World,'' ``ALF,''
``Highway to Heaven'' and ``Amen.''
   Guild leaders believed a model interim contract could be used to
lure a studio, network or additional small production companies to
break ranks with the alliance. More than 100 independent production
companies have already signed interim contracts with the WGA,
allowing some writers to go back to work.
   Among those who have been able to resume writing is cartoonist
Garry Trudeau, writer of the ``Tanner '88'' series on cable
television's Home Box Office.
   The strike started March 7 after the two sides could not agree
on payments for television reruns and foreign television
syndication.
   Meanwhile, 20th Century Fox studios said it was imposing forced
vacations on several hundred employees beginning July 11. The WGA
strike has placed the start of the fall television season in
jeopardy and has resulted in sweeping layoffs among California's
230,000 entertainment industry employees.
   The alliance has stated publicly that its last contract offer,
rejected by the WGA on June 22 by a 3-1 margin, was final.
</TEXT>
