<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0793 07-07 0828</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0793,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Praises Dukakis' Ethnic Background in Speech to
Greek-Americans</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 2nd graf pvs to UPDATE with speech delivered, INSERTS
grafs 4-5 with more Bush comment</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush, campaigning on Michael
Dukakis' home turf, hailed the ethnic background of his Democratic
rival before an audience of Greek-Americans Thursday and disavowed
any responsibility for an attack against Dukakis on religious
grounds.
   ``I know how proud you are of Michael Dukakis,'' Bush said in a
speech to a conference of laity and clergy of the Greek Orthodox
Church.
   ``What a tribute it is to Greek-Americans, to our political
system, and to this great country of ours that we find it totally
natural that the son of an immigrant is one of two men still
contending to be president of the United States,'' said Bush,
certain to be the Republican nominee.
   Bush got a warm reception from the audience of several thousand
of Dukakis' fellow Greek Americans. His address was delayed more
than 45 minutes _ until after 10 p.m. _ by other speakers and the
singing of Greek songs. He joked to the audience that it was wise
to have Dukakis and himself appear on different days.
   ``Too much charisma can be dangerous to your health,'' he said
to laughter.
   At a news conference earlier, Bush turned aside questions about
Dukakis' role as Massachusetts governior in handling the state's
budget and overseeing its economy.
   ``I don't want to get into these details,'' said Bush, who on
other occasions has relished attacking Dukakis. ``I prefer to be
positive and tell you what to do to lead this country ...''
   The vice president was asked his view of a widely distributed
letter written by James Jatras, a staff member of the Senate
Republican Policy Committee and a Greek Orthodox Church layman, who
called Dukakis ``a renegade, an outcast'' for his positions and for
his marriage to a Jew.
   ``I'm not going to get into that,'' said Bush. ``That did not
emanate from me and I had never heard of it before.''
   Archbishop Iakovos, the primate of the Greek Orthodox Church in
the Americas, has said the attack was ``extremely unjustified'' and
that Dukakis was a steadfast son of the church.
   In his speech, Bush identified with the values of the
Greek-American community. ``Family, faith, education, hard work _
those are the keys and no one knows it better than you,'' he said.
   ``It's the same message you preach in your homes, the same way I
was raised, the same way Barbara (Bush's wife) and I raised our
family.''
   While praising Dukakis' heritage and saying he did not want to
criticize him, Bush went on to do exactly that, saying the two
candidates had ``a different view on taxes.''
   The Massachusetts governor recently signed a cigarette tax.
   Bush also said he would try to make clear ``who has the most
experience, who (is) best to sit down with (Soviet leader Mikhail
S.) Gorbachev.''
   The vice president added that the Reagan administration ``has
achieved the only arms control agreement in the nuclear age to
eliminate an entire category of weapons when some were sitting up
here saying `Freeze, freeze' _ lock in Soviet superiority with a
thousand warheads and zero for the United States.''
   On another matter dear to Greek-Americans, Bush expressed hope
for a resolution of Greek-Turkish differences over Cyprus.
   He said the administration encourages dialogue. ``We pray for
reconciliation and we seek for Cyprus a constitutional democracy
based on majority rule, the rule of law and the protection of
minority rights,'' he said.
   At his news conference, Bush said his strategy, with the help of
surrogates, will be to put Dukakis' record on public display. He
said one recent poll found that two-thirds of the people surveyed
thought Dukakis was more conservative than Bush.
   ``There's something wrong with that,'' Bush said. ``The issues
are not in focus ... I honestly believe that the country doesn't
yet fully appreciate where the governor stands ... on a lot of key
issues.''
   Bush faulted himself for not making clear ``what makes me tick
inside.''
   He said, ``I've not felt too comfortable talking about the
private side of the Bush family and all of that _ what it means to
me, the loss of a child, whatever it might be.''
   ``I now have concluded that I have to make clear what makes me
tick inside,'' he said, referring to a speech Wednesday before a
Hispanic audience in which he talked at some detail about his life.
   Bush said, ``I was trying to say, look, I understand this is
what motivates me, here's the inner side.''
   He jokingly said he ``wasn't trying to draw a contrast that
we've got 12 grandchildren and he's (Dukakis) working for one.''
   However, the vice president's wife quickly corrected him on the
number of grandchildren and Bush said, ``Make that 10.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
