<1ST_LINE>u w AM-MeeseSuccessor 3rdLd-Writethru a0828 07-07 0853</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Meese Successor, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0828,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Administration Widens Search For Meese Successor</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 13th graf pvs bgng, `Also, former,' to
UPDATE with Laxalt saying he's not interested in succeeding Meese
as attorney general</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration on Thursday combed
through a ``pretty long'' list of candidates for attorney general
in hopes a successor to Edwin Meese III can be nominated before
Congress recesses late next week for the Democratic National
Convention.
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the White House is
moving ``as rapidly as possible,'' but ``it's not the end of the
world'' if the search goes beyond the convention recess. The
Democrats meet in Atlanta July 18.
   With another recess scheduled for the Republican convention in
mid-August, it appears that only the least controversial of
prospects could be confirmed before September. Meese, long an
object of campaign debate, has said he will leave office in late
July or early August, now that he has been ``vindicated'' by an
independent counsel's decision not to seek an indictment against
him.
   Some successor prospects would have to undergo a vigorous FBI
background check. But others already have been investigated for
other top-level positions, and their reviews would only need to be
updated, according to FBI spokesman Bill Carter.
   The ideal time for an early confirmation vote would appear to be
in the first two weeks of August, before the GOP convention break.
The Senate doesn't plan to return until the second week of
September.
   The Judiciary Committee, which would conduct the confirmation
hearing, already has a heavy schedule the last week in July,
including confirmation sessions for those nominated as top Justice
Department deputies.
   ``They've got time to get somebody in, but it depends who it's
going to be,'' said Sen. Patrick J. Leahy, D-Vt., who has presided
at the committee's judicial confirmation hearings.
   ``If they go with competence rather than ideology, they can get
somebody in easily. With the right person it can be done in August.
Everybody would bend over backwards to work it out. But nobody's
going to rubber stamp a candidate,'' he said.
   Added Sen. Orrin G. Hatch, R-Utah: ``I think the administration
is going to have to make up its mind next week.''
   Fitzwater said, ``There really isn't anything new except to say
that we are proceeding with the collection of names and processing
of individual candidates, and we would like to have a nominee
before the Congress recesses'' for the Democratic convention the
week of July 18.
   Fitzwater said the White House list is still ``pretty long. I've
seen a number of news reports with a lot of names in them, and you
take the longest one, and we're at least that long.''
   Among those mentioned as possible successors to Meese: former
Republican Sen. Paul Laxalt of Nevada; former House Republican
Leader John Rhodes of Arizona; the former Democratic attorney
general under Jimmy Carter, Griffin B. Bell; Reagan's first
attorney general, William French Smith; former Transportation
Secretary Elizabeth Dole; former White House Chief of Staff Howard
H. Baker; Washington attorney Judith Richards Hope, a nominee for a
federal appellate judgeship and the daughter-in-law of comedian Bob
Hope; and acting Deputy Attorney General Harold Christensen.
   Also, former American Bar Association President Eugene Thomas;
Lois Haight Herrington, chairman of the president's Conference for
a Drug-Free America; Carla Hills, former Republican secretary of
housing and urban development; William D. Ruckelshaus, former
administrator of the Environmental Protection Agency; former
Pennsylvania Gov. Richard Thornburgh; Howard T. Markey, chief judge
of the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit in Washington,
and U.S. Attorney Rudolph Giuliani of New York.
   A statement issued Thursday by Laxalt's law office said he was
not interested in the position and is committed to remain with the
office he opened less than a year ago.
   ``In addition, no one has approached the senator about accepting
the job,'' the statement said, adding that reports Laxalt could be
a successor to Meese ``amount to nothing more than speculation and
rumor.''
   Hatch said Christensen, from the senator's hometown of Salt Lake
City, would be the most logical choice, because he already has
received a background check for his nomination as deputy attorney
general. Christensen's confirmation hearing is set for July 28.
   The senator, who has spoken to the White House, said Christensen
and Laxalt are among those under consideration. ``They know I'd
support Laxalt,'' Hatch said. He declined to name anyone else under
consideration.
   Meanwhile, Meese said Wednesday he would have handled his role
in connection with scandal-plagued Wedtech Corp. differently if he
had known at the time ``that this was a gang of crooks.''
   ``Obviously, ... if you had total knowledge of what was going to
be revealed later ... then there might be things you do
differently,'' Meese said in an interview with reporters.
   ``For example, in the Wedtech matter, which was handled like I
would any other ... If I had known or anybody had known ... that
this was a gang of crooks, there would have been quite different
handling of the situation, obviously.''
</TEXT>
