<DATELINE>ABERDEEN, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Men jumped from the blazing oil
platform or slithered down searing pipes as the heat popped windows
like bubbles, but most had no chance and comrades could only watch
helplessly from a nearby vessel.
   ``It was a case of fry and die or jump and try,'' said technican
Roy Carey, 45, who leaped into the cold North Sea to escape the
flames that engulfed the giant Piper Alpha rig after an explosion
Wednesday night.
   His face was burned and his arms were in slings. ``I was
smothered with smoke. I could hardly see and couldn't breathe, so
it was over the side or die there,'' he said from his hospital bed
in Aberdeen.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TEHRAN, Iran (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pall-bearers Thursday paraded 76 flag-draped
wooden coffins through Tehran's streets, where thousands of
mourners shouted their anger at the United States for shooting down
an Iranian jetliner and killing all 290 people aboard.
   ``No compromise! No surrender! Fight with America!'' shouted
waves of marchers, who carried wreaths, anti-American posters and
golden-framed photographs of the victims.
   The mass funeral started with a fiery speech from Iran's
president, Ali Khamenei, who mocked American statements on the
incident and calling for revenge.
   ``The case is not closed in the opinion of those who are seeking
retribution,'' he said, referring to a remark by President Reagan
that no more could be said about U.S. responsibility after one of
its missile cruisers shot down the Iran Air jetliner over the
Persian Gulf on Sunday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. commanders in the Persian Gulf were on
the lookout over the July 4th weekend for Iran's F-14 fighters,
advanced aircraft recently stationed at the mouth of the Gulf of
Hormuz, but seldom _ if ever _ flown in combat by the Iranians.
   The administration has said the commander of the USS Vincennes,
Capt. Will C. Rogers III, thought he was under attack by an Iranian
F-14 when he fired two SM-2 anti-aircraft missiles and destroyed
Iran Air flight 655, an A-300 Airbus with 290 civilians aboard.
   But the F-14 is primarily designed for combat against other
aircraft. And Pentagon sources, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said that Iran hardly ever flies any of its few
operational F-14s, and has never risked one in a shooting situation.
   ``Iran has never used an F-14 in combat,'' said one U.S.
military source with gulf experience. ``They have sent them up to
escort tankers, and put them up when Iraqi fighters were around,
but they always veered off and stayed out of danger.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union launched an unmanned probe
Thursday night on a six-month trip to Mars' moon, Phobos, for a
mission designed to pave the way for a manned voyage to the red
planet.
   The launch of the 180-foot-tall Proton rocket carrying the
probe, Phobos I, was carried live on Soviet television, which
reported that the spacecraft's flight was proceeding normally.
   More than a dozen nations are participating in the mission to
swoop close to the surface of Phobos and drop probes onto the
little, potato-shaped Martian moon that scientists say may hold
clues to how the universe was formed.
   A companion probe, Phobos II, is scheduled for launch on July 12.
   If all goes well, the two spacecraft will enter the
gravitational pull of Mars in January 1989 and fall into orbit just
behind Phobos for a three-month remote study of the surface and
atmosphere of the planet. In April, the craft will drop out of
their orbit and swoop to within 30 yards of the moon's surface,
where they will release two small landers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unusual formations on the surface of Mars _
including a mile-long rock shaped like a human face _ may have been
carved by a lost civilization or could be just ``a trick of
nature,'' four scientists said Thursday.
   In either case, they said, the mysterious outcroppings demand
further scrutiny by spacecraft.
   The scientists, including a former astronaut, said that a
photograph taken of the Martian surface in 1976 by NASA's Viking
spacecraft clearly shows a face that could have been carved out of
a Martian mountain a half million years ago.
   And the sphinx-like image that stares outward from the planet
may be part of a complex, as evidenced by other unusual formations
nearby, which was built by a civilization that has since
disappeared, the scientists said.
   Or, they admit, it could all be ``a trick of light and shadow.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Children under 5 are more likely to be run over
and killed in parking lots or by their parents backing down the
driveway than they are in traffic, a study shows.
   ``Older children are injured and die from darting out into
traffic,'' said Dr. Robert J. Brison, the study's principal author.
``Younger children seem not to have that pattern of injury. They
seem to be injured most commonly in a home driveway or in a store
parking lot.''
   Such tragic deaths are especially likely to occur in families
that drive a light truck or van, said Brison of Queen's University
in Kingston, Ontario.
   Brison, who practices emergency medicine at Kingston General
Hospital, said in a telephone interview Thursday that parents of
young children ``need to be aware of this pattern of injury, so
that they can put the children in a safe area, such as a playpen,
or pick them up'' before backing out of the driveway.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most of the nation's top goals for babies and
pregnant women _ including a hoped-for reduction in the infant
mortality rate _ will not be met by the 1990 target date, federal
health officials said Thursday.
   ``It's certainly sobering and concerning,'' said Dr. Ann Koontz,
a specialist with the Health Resources and Services Administration
in Rockville, Md. ``This indicates that we have some significant
problems relating to maternal and infant health.''
   The government in 1979 published its 1990 health objectives for
the nation, including 13 top-priority goals relating to pregnancy
and infant health. Only three of those 13 goals are likely to be
met, the national Centers for Disease Control said Thursday in its
weekly report.
   The CDC, using National Center for Health Statistics data,
projects that the nation's infant mortality rate _ infants dying
before age 1 _ will be 9.1 per 1,000 live births. That's a drop
from the 10.6 rate in 1985, but still short of the 9.0 rate in the
1990 objectives.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House, grappling with one of its most
sensitive political issues, sidestepped a decision Thursday on
whether to let the Pentagon shut down unneeded military bases.
   The chamber was considering a pair of plans setting up complex
mechanisms and procedures for closing some of the 3,800 military
installations around the nation. Pentagon officials estimate that
between $2 billion and $5 billion annually could be saved by
shutting unneeded bases.
   But after a preliminary test vote, the chamber dropped the bill,
in part because the debate had run longer than scheduled. House
members generally do not work past Thursday afternoons, permitting
members from Western states to return home for election-year
campaigning.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush, hoping to steal
thunder from Michael Dukakis, is likely to break with tradition and
go on the road stumping for votes and media attention during the
Democratic National Convention.
   The plan, Bush said, is to ``get a little bit of ink'' while the
spotlight is on Dukakis and his nomination as the Democrats'
presidential candidate.
   Traditionally, presidential candidates keep a low profile during
the nominating conventions of their rivals. President Reagan, still
playing by those rules although he is not running this year, will
be at his mountaintop ranch in California when the Democrats meet
in Atlanta July 18-21.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MENLO PARK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Southern California faces a 60 percent
chance and the San Francisco Bay a 50 percent chance within three
decades of being rocked by a major earthquake that could kill
thousands of people, the U.S. government said Thursday.
   ``Unless we aggressively pursue earthquake reduction measures,
there is the potential for many people to die, perhaps more people
than ever died in a single day from any disaster in the United
States,'' said Richard Andrews, deputy director of California's
Office of Emergency Services.
   The report by the U.S. Geological Survey and a working group of
its National Earthquake Prediction Evaluation Council deals only
with the San Andreas, Hayward, San Jacinto and Imperial faults.
   So, with other major faults such as the Newport-Inglewood Fault
in Los Angeles excluded from the report, the likelihood of large
earthquakes ``may significantly exceed the probabilities we
present,'' said geophysicist James Dieterich of the Geological
Survey and other authors of the report.
</TEXT>
