<1ST_LINE>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv08   07-07 0603</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 08,0620</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 08</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Friday July 8</NOTE>
<HEAD>Everyone Believes in Quality</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The war over, their industries wasted and their
recovery prospects dim, the Japanese attached themselves to a
concept that, as much as anything else, helped them rise up from
the ashes.
   The concept was industrial quality, which presupposes that you
offer a customer the very best you can produce because that, and
nothing less, is what the customer expects.
   In concept or practice it wasn't new. Americans had learned the
trick years before, and its authorities on the subject were quite
willing to share their ideas. A flock of them trekked to Japan; the
Japanese listened and improved.
   Now, one of the great authorities on the subject, Armand
Feigenbaum, former manager of General Electric's worldwide
manufacturing operations, has finished offering a revolutionary
idea to the Soviets.
   The notion: The customer is always right. And what the customer
wants, needs, demands is quality.
   On reading that advice, most people consider it too obvious for
comment. But the fact of the matter is that it isn't at all.
   Time after time companies have fallen on bad times because they
forget it. Repeatedly, companies have resurrected themselves on
rediscovering it. And not just companies but entire nations, as
witness the Japanese.
   The notion was all but lost in the labyrinthic Soviet production
system, which for decades has emphasized production goals over
customer needs, and thereby affirmed one of Feigenbaum's basic
no-nos, to wit:
   ``The wrong way is for the manufacturer of a product or the
provider of a service to satisfy his own perceived internal needs
at the expense of the customer's requirements.''
   The message was delivered last month to an audience at the 32nd
annual conference of the European Organization for Quality Control,
made up mostly of Russians bent on improving Soviet production and
export prowess.
   Will the Russians take heed as the Japanese did? And as much to
the point: Will Americans remain competitive by practicing quality
control; or will they forget, as they did for 20 years or so prior
to the 1980s.
   Feigenbaum, author of ``Total Quality Control,'' a bible on the
subject, is now president of General Systems Co., a Pittsfield,
Mass., company that installs quality control systems throughout the
world.
   These are some of the points he made to the Russians, and which
he suggests might draw the attention of American producers of
products and services:
   _Quality is everybody's job but it will become nobody's job
unless management provides operating systems that support the work
of individuals and promote teamwork among individuals and
departments.
   _Quality and cost are partners, not adversaries. The essence of
both higher quality and lower costs is fully effective use of
resources. Anything less produces waste, which means higher costs.
   _Automation is no substitute for quality. Unless installed as an
integrated part of an overall quality system, automation merely
produces the same bad products faster.
   _Quality is not just a technical function or department. It is
an operating system that extends throughout the organization and
provides the social stability and economic efficiency essential to
quality.
   _Quality improvement doesn't come through sloganeering, bumper
stickers, occasional quality fireworks called campaigns, or the
dusting off of a few traditional quality-control techniques.
   Customers perceive quality and they relate it to price. Quality
shows through, he says, and when it isn't there it doesn't take
long for the customer to know it ... in Japan, the United States or
the Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Fri July 8</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
