<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 1357EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a AM-PhonyDoctor Adv11   07-07 1063</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Phony Doctor, Adv 11,1095</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv11</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, July 11, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Man Thought to Be Doctor Now Behind Bars</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOAN GOESSL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One-time friends say the man they knew
as Dr. Michael J. Kelley told them he came here for a quieter life
of medical practice and part-time teaching at the University of New
Mexico medical school.
   Kelley seemed to have a physician's demeanor and plenty of
medical knowledge. He wore a white lab coat embroidered with his
name and told stories about his teaching job.
   But it turns out that nobody at the university had ever heard of
him and that the New Mexico Medical Examiner's Board had no record
of a Michael J. Kelley being licensed to practice medicine in the
state.
   And now his former friends _ remembering inconsistencies in his
story that they once glossed over _ say they are embarrassed and
angry they wee taken in by a man they describe as confident,
extroverted, entertaining and smart.
   They're troubled by his criminal past and the story of his
relationship with a teen-age boy who died.
   And they're relieved that one acquaintance ``outconned the
con,'' as an investigator put it, and helped bring about his arrest.
   A Bernalillo County grand jury returned a 34-count indictment in
April charging him with multiple counts of practicing medicine
without a license in Albuquerque in 1986 and 1987.
   ``He was so successful at convincing very well-educated people
that he's something he's not,'' said Bill Copeland, the district
attorney's investigator who handled the case. ``Part of his motive
was he loved the high lifestyle. He enjoyed status, enjoyed the
high roller-type lifestyle.''
   Kelley, whose real name is Gerald Thomas Lampkins, was arrested
in Tempe, Ariz., in February and is being held in the Bernalillo
County Detention Center in lieu of $250,000 cash bond, awaiting
trial.
   Lampkins, whose birthdates listed on arrest records put him at
51, 54 or 56, surfaced in Albuquerque early in 1986, allegedly
passing himself off as a wealthy endocrinologist and surgeon whose
heart problems forced him to leave a busy and prosperous practice
in New York.
   The part of the story about heart problems may be true; Copeland
says Kelley issued medication to himself as Lampkins for treatment
of a heart condition.
   Kelley allegedly prescribed Ibuprofen, a muscle relaxant, to one
woman who complained to him of lower back pain. To another friend
he allegedly prescribed an antibiotic after she experienced a
negative reaction from a flu shot. He is not accused of performing
examinations or surgery, but of issuing prescriptions.
   His lawyer, public defender Richard Knowles, declined to allow
his client to be interviewed, saying, ``I just don't like the idea
of going to trial with newspaper clippings.''
   Authorities say Lampkins' criminal record dates back to the
early 1950s and that his convictions range from kidnapping to
making false statements. He's served time at the federal
penitentiary at Leavenworth, Kan., for violating the Selective
Service Act and for other offenses in state and county prisons in
Missouri and California.
   Then there's the story of his relationship with 18-year-old
Ronnie Teunis.
   Kelley and Teunis, who lived together in the former's opulent
Oakland, Calif., apartment, took out a $100,000 life insurance
policy on each other in November 1982. Teunis died in a motorcycle
accident two weeks later. The district attorney's office in Oakland
has closed the case, according to investigator Nicole Lee.
   But it's not closed as far as Allstate Life Insurance Co. is
concerned.
   Kelley collected $203,365 from Allstate, a sum that included
interest and payment on a double indemnity clause. The insuror now
is trying to recover the money plus $600,000 in punitive damages,
contending that Kelley, or Lampkins, misrepresented himself as
Teunis' stepfather.
   A newspaper's legal notice of the insurance company's suit added
to Albuquerque friends' vague uneasiness about Kelley.
   ``Things would happen to sow a seed inside you, but then nothing
would happen for a while,'' said a woman whose family regularly
invited Kelley to dinner and parties.
   A small, balding man described by friends as slightly effeminate
and given to talking dramatically with his hands, he was good
company, highly intelligent, schooled in the arts and
well-traveled. He drove a Mercedes-Benz and carried a business card
saying he was a Ph.D. as well as a medical doctor.
   The woman and her husband, who spoke on condition they not be
identified, said Kelley avoided doctors whom they tried to
introduce him socially and sometimes gave inconsistent accounts of
his marital status _ divorced in one version, widowed in another.
   He wept while telling about the motorcycle accident that killed
Ronnie, they said. But he said it happened in New York, not
California, and that the boy was an underprivileged youth his
family had taken in.
   Every time Kelley piqued the couple's suspicions, the wife said,
he'd offer a gift or a compliment _ ``something nice to overcome
the feelings I had.''
   But the legal notice was too much. The couple discussed their
suspicions with a friend who passed them on to Cheryl Boll, a
Placitas, N.M., kennel owner who had befriended Kelley through
their mutual interest in dogs.
   ``I think several people began snapping to this person who was
not who he said he was. But she pegged him as a phony and a
manipulator. Eventually she out-conned the con guy,'' Copeland, the
prosecutor's investigator, said of Mrs. Boll.
   ``I talked to him almost every day,'' she said. ``Basically I
played a role as his dearest and best friend. Call me Judas. That's
a good name.''
   Her motivation, she said, was to stop a phony doctor. She
eventually told what she knew to the district attorney's office.
   An arrest warrant accusing Gerald Thomas Lampkins of practicing
medicine without a license _ and listing more than six aliases _
was filed last Feb. 12.
   Lampkins, who had fled Albuquerque after being served with the
Allstate summons three months earlier, was then living in Tempe,
Ariz.
   Lt. Stephen Graehling and other Tempe officers knocked on his
door.
   ``We stood around for a few minutes,'' Graehling says. ``He came
out the back door, which empties onto a golf course, and tried to
run out back. But I had two deputies out back who arrested him. He
didn't run very far.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, July 11</NOTE>
