<1ST_LINE>a a AM-Drought-Report Adv11   07-07 0968</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Report, Adv 11,0994</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv11</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday AMs, July 11, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Widely Followed Weekly Report Is One Of Least Scientific Surveys</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN P. ROSENFELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They often are based on
seat-of-the-pants judgments rather than scientific measurements,
but the government's weekly crop reports are among the most eagerly
awaited figures for commodity traders, farmers and other drought
watchers.
   Another round of reports will be released Monday afternoon and
analysts will be looking to see how the nation's corn fields are
standing up to dry conditions during a pollination period that is
crucial to the survival of the crop. For soybeans, that
make-it-or-break-it point is still weeks away.
   In Iowa, like other farm states, the reports are assembled from
hundreds of questionnaires returned by farmer volunteers,
government employees and bank officers who make farm loans. There
are few yardsticks for the responses that, among other things, rate
crops from excellent to very poor. Participants say they rely on
their own judgment.
   ``It's probably one of the least scientific surveys we do.
However, it's the most popular release we have,'' says Duane Skow,
state statistician for Iowa for the Agricultural Statistics Service
of the U.S. Department of Agriculture. ``It's a subjective report.
It's not based on measurements.''
   To farmers, the figures help in making decisions on when to buy
hay, corn or soybean meal to feed livestock or whether to sell
livestock and break up herds because of concern adequate feed will
be too costly in winter. Farmers also may use the reports to base
decisions on buying or selling crop surpluses or contracting for
future sales or purchases.
   Public policymakers are watching the figures as they consider
drought-relief programs. This year, for example, reports are being
distributed for the first time to members of the Iowa Legislature
and are being circulated to members of state drought task forces.
   Commodity firms, traders and market watchers view the figures as
an important benchmark for grain and livestock markets _ providing
regular progress reports on the condition of crops months before
the harvest, as well as assessments on the availability of grains
and grasses used as livestock feeds.
   ``These numbers are closely followed by grain trade analysts,''
says Robert Wisner, an extension economist and grain market
specialist at Iowa State University.
   ``They are used for a general indication of whether the crop is
improving or deteriorating in condition,'' Wisner said.
``Obviously, they are not precise enough to forecast exact yields
per acre, but these are good indicators.''
   Last week's report for Iowa, for example, indicated a slight
improvement in the soybean crop from the previous week, when
triple-digit temperatures blistered fields.
   In the June 27 report, none of the Iowa soybean crop was rated
excellent and 16 percent was graded poor. But on July 5, four
percent was given an excellent rating and 12 percent was poor.
   In general, a normal crop is considered good, better than that
is excellent and below normal is either fair, poor or very poor.
   The people who fill out the weekly questionnaires say it is
easier to distinguish between the excellent and poor crops than to
make distinctions between crops that are good or fair.
   ``Excellent and failure are real easy to identify,'' said
Richard Thuma, extension service director and agriculturalist in
Henry County in southeast Iowa, who has been participating in such
surveys for 36 years.
   But sometimes, a conversation with a farmer will determine how
some parts of the survey are answered.
   Is subsoil moisture inadequate?
   Thuma said it is when ``a farmer tells me he dug a fence post
three feet deep and didn't find water.''
   In Iowa, 427 questionnaires go out each Wednesday, asking for
ratings of crops, an assessment of the moisture content of the soil
and subsoil, progress on hay harvests and general comments on
livestock, weather effects, fertilizer supplies, soil erosion or
related topics. As the growing season progresses, questions are
added each week to track the progress of corn and soybean crops.
   Last week's survey marked the start of questions on corn
pollination, a critical period that will determine if kernel-filled
ears will develop.
   Tassels already have formed on some stalks and must drop pollen
on silks that are beginning to form on the ears. The silks must be
moist and sticky enough to catch the pollen,``otherwise you have a
cob without corn,'' Skow said.
   Survey participants are asked to complete the forms on Friday or
on Saturday morning, and replies received Monday morning in Des
Moines are tabulated and combined with data provided by the
National Weather Service and the state climatologist.
   Last week's Iowa report was based on 222 questionnaires returned
in time for use.
   Skow's office strives to avoid sensationalizing the reports _ as
he put it, ``to limit the adjectives.''
   A typical passage last week said: ``The rain and cooler
temperatures helped sustain the condition of Iowa's corn crop this
past week, particularly in the northern and western parts of the
state. Overall the corn was in fair-to-good condition.''
   This year in Iowa, because legislators restored cut funds
supporting such projects, the weekly reports not only give
statewide summaries, but also have restored a section that provides
figures on soil moisture and crop progress for nine areas of the
state.
   The people who compile and contribute to the report say that
even if ideal conditions return, the corn crop has suffered.
   ``I'm not one to overdramatize this situation, but I'm also a
realist,'' said Roger Brummett, a farmer and an agriculturalist at
the extension service in Taylor County who responds to the
questionnaires in his southwest Iowa community. ``We're looking at
a potential 40 percent to 60 percent (corn crop) loss right now in
this county.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday AMs July 11 and Thereafter</NOTE>
