<DOCNO> AP880707-0173 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 1322EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s p BC-Convention-Omni Adv10   07-07 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Convention-Omni, Adv10,0488</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv10</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, July 10, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Convention '88</HEAD>
<HEAD>From Rock to Rodeos to Democrats, The Omni Has Seen It All</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The rusty-looking building the Democrats will
crowd into next week has been home over the years to revivals,
rodeos and rock concerts; tennis, tractor-pulls and title fights;
Springsteen, Sinatra and soccer. And basketball, especially
basketball.
   The Omni arena, which opened in 1972 with a professional hockey
game, was built at a cost of about $17 million on a platform over
land owned by a group of developers who also put together the
adjacent Omni International business-office-hotel complex.
   Since then, the building housing the businesses has been sold to
Ted Turner. He changed the name to CNN Center after his Cable News
Network, which moved into space originally occupied by an indoor
amusement park.
   A Turner-owned company manages the arena, but it remains owned
by a joint city-county authority.
   The arena was constructed mainly to provide a home for the
Atlanta Hawks, a professional basketball team, said former Mayor
Sam Massell. He spearheaded the negotiations with then-Hawks owner
Tom Cousins, who was also the lead developer in the larger complex.
Turner now is majority owner of the Hawks.
   There was ``a thirst for professional sports,'' Massell said,
and a hope that the arena would serve as a catalyst for development
on a neglected side of downtown Atlanta.
   Massell admitted that hasn't happened as rapidly as some
predicted.
   The building's exterior was intentionally designed to rust, to
cut down on maintenance costs.
   Its roofline of 25 pyramid-shaped pods has been compared to an
upside-down egg crate, the configuration designed to provide
external support and to avoid columns inside.
   Indoors, the arena floor runs diagonally, to give more room for
16,237 seats for basketball and to provide space in the corners for
private clubs.
   That space is going to be at a premium for the Democrats since
construction of the podium and of skyboxes for network television
will reduce the seating to about 11,000, forcing off the convention
floor many of the non-delegates accustomed to priority seating in
the past.
   Little controversy has surrounded the building, aside from
periodic griping about concession prices, beer drinking and drug
use at rock concerts.
   As for the unusual name, Massell recalled that as one of the few
controversies 16 years ago.
   He said the name ``came from the dictionary,'' which defines the
Latin-derived prefix ``omni'' as ``all, universal ... without
restriction.'' It's been quite appropriate considering the ice
shows, circuses and conventions staged there year in and year out.
   Massell said the name ``omni'' was unusual when the complex was
built, but the Omni International Hotel was the beginning of what's
become a chain of upscale hotels.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, July 10</NOTE>
</DOC>
