<1ST_LINE>s p BC-Atlanta'sPoor Adv10   07-07 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Atlanta's Poor, Adv10,0505</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv10</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, July 10, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Convention '88</HEAD>
<HEAD>Amid the Bustle and Polish, The Poor Are Overlooked</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Atlanta is dressing up for the Democrats with the
hope that the 35,000 visitors to the party's national convention
will take home a rosy impression of the city.
   But the newly-planted flowers along Peachtree Street and the
scrubbed down convention center will be unable to hide the rickety
shanties of Cabbagetown and the thousands of homeless.
   This prosperous heart of the new South has a core city that
ranks as the second-poorest in the nation, and activists estimate
that 7,000 to 10,000 people are homeless. Leaders say they plan to
make their plight known during the convention in July.
   Anita Beatty, co-director of the Atlanta Task Force for the
Homeless, said there are no plans for large marches or
demonstrations during the convention because the impact would be
lost.
   Instead, with representatives of national homeless groups, task
force members will occupy some of the 1,300 empty public housing
units in Atlanta for an undetermined time starting July 14, four
days before the opening gavel.
   ``Who among the Democrats will take action to solve the problem
if the problem is not visible?'' Mrs. Beatty said. ``It's nice to
have 58 facilities to house the homeless, but it is kind of like
letting steam out of the kettle.''
   The coalition plans a ``sanctuary space,'' either in a church or
large tent, where homeless can go and not fear arrest in clean-up
drives. The city also decided some months ago to keep open a
shelter for about 150 men that would have closed at the end of
March and to add three more shelters, each housing about 30 people.
   Statistically, Atlanta is an island of prosperity in the South,
but the numbers for the ``Atlanta area'' say little about the city
proper, which has only about 20 percent of the metropolitan area's
2.2 million residents.
   Suburban Atlanta is composed of large, shaded lots, nice brick
homes, golf courses, shopping malls and white faces. Urban Atlanta
is overwhelmingly black with about 27 percent of the residents
living below the poverty line, second only to Newark, N.J.,
according to U.S. Census figures.
   Fulton County, which includes the city of Atlanta, has an
unemployment rate of 6.2 percent. The average for the four
surrounding metropolitan area counties is 4.3 percent.
   Some of Atlanta's homeless live under a viaduct that runs past
the convention site, within the projected security zone around the
convention area. City officials say the indigents must vacate the
shantytown for security reasons.
   ``I don't see why they're tryin' to hide us. It ain't like we
done nothing wrong. We just ain't got nowhere else to stay,'' said
Charles Prater, 37, one of the group.
   Mrs. Beatty fears that ``some Draconian things are going to be
done.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, July 10</NOTE>
