<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   GAF Corp., two subsidiaries and the
corporation's vice chairman have been indicted for numerous
securities law violations in an alleged scheme to manipulate the
price of Union Carbide Corp. common stock.
   U.S. Attorney Rudolph Giuliani said Wednesday the charges were
the latest to result from information gathered from Ivan Boesky and
others caught up in the snowballing Wall Street insider trading
scandal.
   GAF, a Wayne, N.J.-based chemical and building products
conglomerate, confirmed last month that it was being investigated
for possible securities law violations but denied that it or its
executives were guilty of any wrongdoing.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New York Stock Exchange plans to drop its
``collar'' restriction on certain computerized trading and to
consider a rule enabling individual investors to place orders more
quickly, sources familiar with Big Board's plans says.
   Abandoning the collar would end one of the most highly
publicized and controversial confidence-boosting revisions
undertaken by the nation's largest stock market in the aftermath of
the October crash.
   The sources said Wednesday there was widespread thinking that
the collar no longer was needed.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of the Suzuki Samurai plunged 70.6 percent
in June from a year earlier, the automaker says in its first sales
report since Consumers Union alleged that the jeep-like vehicle
tips over too easily.
   American Suzuki Motor Corp. said Wednesday it sold 2,199
Samurais in June, down from 7,479 in June 1987.
   June's sales were the lowest since December 1985, the month
after the vehicle's U.S. introduction. Sales had been running at
more than 6,000 a month from March through May.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. and General Motors Corp. say their
car sales rose in late June, and the Big Three automakers all
finished the first half of 1988 ahead of the same period last year.
   Many foreign automakers also reported sales upturns Wednesday,
following a slow start during the year. Honda and Toyota reported
sales increases on both domestic and foreign-made cars.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state judge has struck down a provision of
Irving Bank Corp.'s anti-takeover ``poison pill'' designed to repel
Bank of New York Co. in its longstanding effort to acquire the
rival bank.
   Supreme Court Justice Herman Cahn ruled Wednesday that Bank of
New York was unfairly discriminated against and would suffer
``irreparable harm'' from the defense.
   The defense would have allowed all Irving shareholders _ except
a hostile suitor _ to buy $400 worth of Irving shares for $200 if
any suitor bought more than 20 percent of Irving stock without the
support of Irving's management.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pennsylvania officials have recommended civil
penalties and asked authorities to see if criminal charges are
warranted against Ashland Oil Inc. in connection with the Jan. 2
fuel tank collapse that polluted two major rivers in three states.
   Gov. Robert Casey, following the recommendations of a task force
report, told the Department of Environmental Resources on Wednesday
to begin seeking maximum civil penalties. He asked the state
attorney general to consider filing criminal charges.
</TEXT>
