<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0590</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's grain reserves are large enough
to prevent major shortages for the rest of the year and keep
consumer food prices in check despite the drought, an Agriculture
Department official says.
   However, there could be a squeeze in the supply of soybeans and
oats, according to Ewen M. Wilson, assistant secretary of
agriculture for economics.
   Wilson said Wednesday that 65 percent of the winter wheat crop,
which amounts to three-quarters of all U.S. wheat production,
already has been harvested. Almost two-thirds of the spring wheat
crop is rated in poor condition because of the drought, he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan was the only industrial power to best
the United States in reducing manufacturing labor costs in absolute
terms last year, according to a government report.
   Measured in devalued U.S. dollars, labor costs in Japan soared
13.5 percent compared with a 1.5 percent decline in the United
States, the Labor Department reported Wednesday.
   U.S. manufacturers held hourly wage and benefit increases last
year to just 1.3 percent, compared with boosts of 1.4 percent in
Japan, 4.5 percent in Candada, 3.4 percent in France, 4 percent in
West Germany and 8.2 percent in Great Britain.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   World oil prices rose amid reports that
three OPEC members might request an emergency meeting of the cartel
to consider ways of cutting production and propping up prices.
   But analysts remained steadfast in their predictions that the
fractured cartel could do little to forestall continued price
erosion through the summer.
   Prices have dropped sharply over the past month in response to
surplus supplies and a perception among traders that OPEC is
crumbling. The next regular OPEC meeting is set for Nov. 21.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate voted Wednesday by a veto-proof
72-23 margin to make companies provide workers and local officials
60 days advance notice of plant closings and large layoffs.
   Nineteen Republicans, many of them up for re-election this year,
joined Democrats in support of the mandatory notices, which
President Reagan cited as his primary reason for vetoing in May a
massive overhaul of the nation's trade laws.
   The bill requires employers to provide the advance notices for
any shutdown of an operation involving at least one-third of
plant's workforce and any layoff applying to 50 or more workers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines and its unions have signed an
agreement designed to defuse years of bitter battling and improve
safety procedures at the often-criticized carrier.
   The pact comes a month after federal investigators warned that
safety could be threatened.
   The deal, reached late Tuesday night, spells out procedures for
the company and its 32,500 workers to discuss complaints and
disagreements, but does little to directly address the airline's
ongoing negotiations with its mechanics and pilots, who are working
under expired contracts.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices surged while grain futures finished mixed
Wednesday amid uncertainty over the potential for further drought
damage.
   Stock prices fell on a late wave of selling. The Dow Jones
average of 30 industrials, up 27.03 on Tuesday, finished down 28.45
to 2,130.16.
   The dollar eased slightly in lackluster trading marked by
central bank intervention. Gold prices were little changed.
   Bond prices fell. The yield on the Treasury's closely watched
30-year bond soared to 8.98 percent from 8.87 percent late Tuesday.
</TEXT>
