<1ST_LINE>r f PM-EconomyRdp     07-07 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Fall; Automakers Report Sales Jump</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A selling wave has reversed an advance in the stock market, but
U.S. automakers reported their late June sales strengthened from a
year earlier.
   On Wall Street, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell
28.45 points Wednesday to finish at 2,130.16. The loss wiped out a
27.03-point advance on Tuesday that had carried the Dow average and
other widely-followed market indicators to new highs for this year.
   Analysts attributed the drop partly to selling by professionals
engaged in computer-program trading strategies involving
stock-index futures and ``baskets'' of individual stocks.
   The stock market also suffered from renewed inflation worries,
analysts said. Prices of some key farm commodities such as soybeans
jumped late in the session on a forecast of more hot, dry weather
in the Midwest. Oil prices also rose.
   The latest bout of inflation jitters, combined with the weaker
dollar, also dragged down bond prices. The Treasury's closely
watched 30-year bond dropped by $12.50 per $1,000 in face value,
while its yield soared to 8.98 percent from 8.87 percent late
Tuesday.
   In their auto sales reports, Ford Motor Co., General Motors
Corp. and Chrysler Corp. each said their car sales climbed in the
last 10 days of June, and the Big Three automakers all finished the
first half of 1988 ahead of the same period last year.
   Many foreign automakers also reported upturns after a slow start
on the year. Honda and Toyota reported sales increases on both
their domestic and foreign-made cars.
   In other economic developments Wednesday:
   _The Labor Department reported that only Japan among the world's
industrial powers bested the United States in reducing
manufacturing labor costs in absolute terms last year. But measured
in devalued dollars, labor costs in Japan soared 13.5 percent
compared with a 1.5 percent decline in the United States, which had
lower hourly increases in wages and benefits than any of its nine
largest industrial competitors.
   _Fears of higher interest rates and rising inflation weakened
consumer buying plans in June as confidence in the U.S. economy
slipped from an 18-year high in May, according to a survey by the
Conference Board.
</TEXT>
