<DOCNO> AP880707-0179 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 0120EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     07-07 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Rise on Technical Factors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures traders generally have disregarded a
report that three OPEC members were calling for an emergency
meeting of the cartel, but prices still rose on technical factors.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the contract for August
delivery of West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 27 cents
higher at $15.36 per barrel Wednesay after picking up 15 cents on
Tuesday.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, unleaded gasoline
closed up 0.84 cent to 50.56 cents a gallon and home heating oil
advanced 1.02 cents to 42.61 cents a gallon.
   Most traders gave little weight to a Kuwait News Agency report
that three members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries might request an emergency meeting of the cartel, said
Madison Galbraith, senior energy specialist for Merrill Lynch
Energy Futures.
   The Kuwaiti news agency, citing high-level senior industry
sources, said officials from Venezuela, Algeria and Ecuador wanted
OPEC to consider ways of cutting production and propping up prices.
   Some traders were concerned about the report and the possibility
of higher prices, but Wednesday's gains were the result of ``just
another short-covering rally,'' Galbraith said.
   In a short trade, an investor sells borrowed contracts in hope
of replacing them later with contracts bought at lower prices. In
such cases, a price rise can cause a flurry of buying as traders
try to cover their positions.
   Galbraith called the advance a correction of an oversold market,
and said the underlying market fundamentals remained bearish.
   At its meeting last month, OPEC oil ministers failed to settle
their internal problems and simply left the existing system of
production quotas and prices unchanged.
   But that system was, and still is, in disarray. Most OPEC
members are producing above their individual quotas or discounting
their prices.
   Some estimates put OPEC production at 3.5 million barrels above
the group's self-imposed overall ceiling of 15.06 million barrels a
day.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880707-0180 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 0126EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-NYSEChanges Bjt   07-07 0633</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NYSE Changes, Bjt,0652</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NYSE Pondering Individual `Express Lane,' Abandoning Collar
Restraint</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Lead prospects uncertain.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New York Stock Exchange, trying to appease
big brokers and small investors, is abandoning a post-crash limit
on computerized program trading while considering a plan to give
individuals speedier access to the market.
   Directors of the nation's biggest securities market were
discussing the changes at their regularly scheduled meeting today,
said sources familiar with the Big Board's plans who spoke on
condition they not be identified.
   Scrapping the so-called ``collar'' restraint on high-volume
computerized program trades would end one of the most controversial
confidence-boosting revisions undertaken by NYSE in the aftermath
of the October crash.
   The sources said there was widespread thinking, especially among
large brokerages which utilize program trading, that the collar no
longer was needed because the market has been relatively stable in
recent weeks.
   The other measure, which the sources likened to a rush-hour
``express lane'' for individual investors, is designed to counter a
perception that the NYSE ignores small trading orders in favor of
the larger and more profitable transactions from big brokers and
their institutional clients.
   NYSE spokeswoman Sharon Gamsin said she could not comment on
matters before the board. But she said the collar limitation,
implemented in February, never was meant to be permanent.
   Trading professionals gave mixed reactions to the collar news.
Some called the limit useless, but others said it played a valuable
role in calming the wild price swings that frightened away
investors during and after the crash.
   Under the collar, the NYSE banned use of its order system for a
popular form of computerized program trading called index arbitrage
on days when the Dow Jones industrial average rose or fell at least
50 points from the previous close.
   ``If they take the rule off, I think there will be more
volatility,'' said David Johnson, president and chief executive of
Johnson, Lane, Space, Smith & Co., a brokerage in Savannah, Ga.
``That means there will be less inclination for the individual to
participate in this market.''
   Robert Kirby, head of Capital Guardian Trust Co. in Los Angeles
and an outspoken critic of index arbitrage, said he thought the
collar had helped curb computer-armed speculators from rampantly
trading stocks to capture short-term profits regardless of
underlying values.
   ``Investors are being flushed out of the system by a bunch of
Star Wars guys,'' Kirby said. ``Markets are going to go where they
go, but I'd like to see them driven by investors, not computers.''
   The individual-investor proposal before the NYSE board also got
a mixed reaction, with some calling it a confidence builder and
others discounting it as a symbolic gesture.
   Under this proposal, individuals placing orders of less than
1,000 shares would have a special computerized ``express lane'' to
the NYSE floor on days when the Dow average swung more than 25
points from the previous close.
   During the crash, many small investors complained they could not
get their sell orders to the NYSE floor quickly because of the
congestion caused by large institutional orders. This meant
individuals were forced to sell at much lower prices, while larger
investors were able to sell first.
   ``I think the individual should have equal access,'' said John
Bachmann, chairman of the Securities Industry Association and
managing partner of Edward D. Jones & Co., a St. Louis-based
brokerage. ``Anybody who thinks the individual had equal access
last time (during the crash) were wrong.''
   But John Markese, vice president of the American Association for
Individual Investors in Chicago, said he was not sure such a
proposal would help small stockholders.
   ``It's holding out a hand,'' he said. ``It's going in the right
direction, but it may prove to be a token gesture.''
</TEXT>
