<DOCNO> AP880707-0183 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 0141EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-EasternAirlines Bjt   07-07 0871</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Eastern Airlines, Bjt,0896</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Labor-Management Safety Agreement Received Coolly</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7 of July 6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines unions and management are not
ready to declare peace is at hand, despite an agreement to separate
safety issues from their other disputes.
   ``The key word to use is `guardedly' optimistic because there's
been such an extended period of mistrust,'' said J.B. Stokes, a
spokesman for the Eastern local of the Air Line Pilots Association,
which represents 3,500 pilots. ``You have to be somewhat cautious.''
   The pact announced Wednesday comes a month after federal
investigators warned that safety could be threatened at
financially-troubled Eastern, the nation's sixth-largest airline,
if its labor problems were not resolved quickly.
   The deal spells out procedures for the company and its 32,500
workers to discuss complaints and disagreements.
   ``We are optimistic and hopeful this will represent a
breakthrough in relations,'' said Charles E. Bryan, district
president of the Machinists union, Eastern's largest labor group
with 12,000 members. ``We don't think this is going to be a total
cure for all the problems of Eastern.''
   Judy Coughlin, secretary-treasurer of the Transport Workers
Union local, representing 7,000 Eastern flight attendants, said her
union was skeptical of the deal but supported any attempt to
improve safety.
   ``We're willing to cooperate on anything, but the problems are
not going to be solved until our people can go to work and not
worry about being fired,'' she said.
   Robin Matell, a company spokesman, said Eastern would not
characterize the agreement beyond a statement by President Phil
Bakes, who said the pact would keep safety out of collective
bargaining issues. But Bakes also noted it was essential to
complete negotiations on economic issues with the machinists and
pilots unions.
   Former Labor Secretary William E. Brock, chosen by federal
officials June 2 to find ways to ease Eastern's labor-management
relations, said he found ``tensions were accelerated to an
unbelievable level'' between the two sides.
   Years of disputes, including lawsuits, lobbying in Congress and
negative newspaper advertisements, have made passengers afraid to
fly Eastern and had created a situation where the airline is losing
$1 million daily, Brock said.
   Transportation Secretary James H. Burnley IV called the
agreement ``a good beginning'' and said federal inspectors would
continue stepped-up monitoring of Eastern ``to assure the flying
public that it remains a safe, fit airline.''
   Rank-and-file reaction to the safety agreement seemed mixed as
reports reached Eastern employees in its Miami base.
   A mechanic fired 18 months ago said he was skeptical about how
well the deal would ease tensions.
   ``There have been so many things done to people and their
families, it would be awfully hard to forgive and forget,'' said
the mechanic, who asked that his name not be used because his case
is in federal arbitration.
   A flight attendant arriving at Miami International Airport said
she found it encouraging that ``some agreement, any agreement was
made. You have to start somewhere,'' said the woman, who like many
Eastern employees asked that her name not be used.
   The pact calls for the establishment of a master safety
committee consisting of top company and union officials, which will
help resolve safety problems pointed out by employees.
   Panels will be established throughout the country at which local
managers and union leaders will attempt to resolve issues such as
captains' authority, the handling of calls to the company's
complaint lines, training of maintenance workers and a study of
workplace injuries.
   ``The document is worthless if there is not compliance,'' Bryan
told reporters. ``We have a collective bargaining agreement (which)
has been blatantly violated consistently by this management. So
there was some reservation about putting a lot of confidence in
this document.''
   A measure of the continued mistrust was the inability to get
management and union leaders to appear together at the Washington
news conference.
   Eastern has been marked by labor-management conflicts for more
than a decade, as a period of cooperation under former Chairman
Frank Borman deteriorated and led to the money-losing airline's
sale in 1986 to Houston-based Texas Air Corp.
   Texas Air's management led by Chairman Frank Lorenzo heightened
tensions by saying Eastern had to cut its labor costs by up to 30
percent. Eastern lost $241 million last year, and Texas Air lost
$466 million.
   The Machinists, in federal mediation with management since
January, have refused to take wage concessions of up to 50 percent
for some non-mechanics, such as baggage handlers. Eastern says it
can't reverse its losses without the concessions.
   A group of Eastern pilots testified before Congress last year
that they were pressured repeatedly to fly aircraft they considered
unsafe. The agreement pledges that, ``No employee will be harassed,
threatened or disciplined for reporting or causing to report an
unsafe condition on an aircraft.''
   Federal officials conducted special inspections of aircraft
flown by Eastern and Continental last spring and also examined
Texas Air's management and finances. They announced they had not
found unsafe conditions but warned of possible safety problems
because of the labor-management battles.
   The Federal Aviation Administration in April proposed an
$823,000 fine against Eastern for recordkeeping and maintenance
infractions. Fourteen months earlier, the airline had agreed to pay
a record $9.5 million penalty.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
