<DOCNO> AP880707-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 0143EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-GAFIndicted Bjt   07-07 0676</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-GAF Indicted, Bjt,0696</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GAF, Two Units and Executive Charged in Stock Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal prosecutors say information gathered
from Ivan Boesky and others caught up in the snowballing Wall
Street insider trading scandal led indirectly to unprecedented
stock manipulation charges against GAF Corp.
   GAF, two subsidiaries and the corporation's vice chairman were
indicted on numerous securities law charges Wednesday for an
alleged scheme to manipulate the price of Union Carbide Corp.
common stock.
   GAF made an unsuccessful hostile takeover bid for Union Carbide
in 1985 and kept alive the threat of another attempt until it sold
much of its Carbide stake in late 1986.
   U.S. Attorney Rudolph Giuliani said the indictment marked the
first time ``a corporate entity was charged with stock
manipulation'' in the government's widening probe.
   The 10-count indictment charged GAF, two subsidiaries _ GAF
Chemicals Corp. and Jay & Company Inc. _ and James T. Sherwin,
GAF's vice chairman and chief administrative officer with
conspiracy, stock price manipulation, securities fraud, wire fraud,
causing the creation of false brokerage records and obtaining
improper margin loans to finance stock purchases.
   A spokesman for GAF, a Wayne, N.J.-based chemical and building
products conglomerate, said the board of directors had expressed
its full confidence in Sherwin as well as ``its deep disappointment
in the government's decision to bring these unprecedented charges.''
   The spokesman said the company and Sherwin intended to defend
themselves vigorously against the charges and were ``confident of
complete vindication.''
   The indictment alleged the stock price manipulation was
conducted through the Los Angeles-based brokerage firm of Jefferies
& Co., which was not charged with any wrongdoing.
   The company's founder, Boyd L. Jefferies, has been cooperating
with investigators and pleaded guilty in March 1987 to two felony
charges arising from the Boesky insider trading scandal.
   Jefferies, who faces a maximum 10-year prison term, has yet to
be sentenced.
   ``Ivan Boesky's connection to this matter is indirect,'' said
Giuliani. ``Boesky cooperated and as a result of his cooperation we
were able to develop a case on Jefferies. Jefferies cooperated and
among other things he revealed this particular situation.''
   Giuliani said Jefferies' cooperation and the investigation were
continuing. He declined to say if additional indictments were in
the works.
   The GAF indictment alleged that Sherwin, acting for GAF, had two
unidentified Jefferies & Co. employees make Union Carbide stock
close at or above a specified price over several days in late
October 1986.
   According to Assistant U.S. Attorney Carl Loewenson Jr., the
indictment charged Sherwin with plotting to drive up the price of
Union Carbide's stock ``to attract buyers and to maximize the
profits'' GAF could earn by selling its Carbide stock.
   The indictment further alleged that Sherwin promised GAF would
pay Jefferies & Co. for any losses the brokerage incurred on such
trades. At the time, GAF owned nearly 10 million shares, or 10
percent of Carbide's outstanding common shares.
   Jefferies & Co. bought large amounts of Carbide stock _ and lost
money _ near the close of trading on Oct. 29 and 30, 1986. The
indictment contended that boosted the price of Carbide common stock.
   The indictment said one of Sherwin's alleged co-conspirators at
Jefferies sent him a $40,000 invoice for fictitious advisory
services. Sherwin allegedly approved payment of the invoice, and
GAF made out a check payable to Jefferies & Co.
   On Nov. 10, 1986, GAF sold 5 million shares of Carbide stock to
Salomon Brothers for nearly $115 million. Giuliani said Salomon
Brothers cooperated with investigators.
   According to the indictment, Sherwin never sent the $40,000 GAF
check to Jefferies. After the news media reported that Boyd
Jefferies, chairman of the brokerage, had been subpoenaed by the
Securities and Exchange Commission in the Boesky investigation,
Sherwin allegedly instructed his secretary to void the $40,000
check.
   If convicted on all counts, Sherwin, 54, of Princeton, N.J.,
faces a maximum 50 years in prison and up to $2.5 million in fines.
The charges against corporate defendant carry maximum fines of up
to $5 million each.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880707-0185 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 0145EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-MergerFees     07-07 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Merger Fees,0593</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Atlanta Fed Researchers Say Huge Fees Worth The Price In Big
Mergers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A study of the fees paid to investment bankers in
friendly business mergers concludes that such payments, which may
total millions of dollars, are no more excessive than the
transaction fees paid to real estate agents.
   Researchers William Curt Hunter and Mary Beth Walker of the
Federal Reserve Bank of Atlanta stated their review of 125 friendly
mergers between 1979 and 1985 indicated ``the bankers' fees, though
large in absolute terms, are only a small percentage of the
economic value created by the mergers.''
   ``On average, when measured against the gain that the merger
creates for the new entity, ...the fee approximates that of a
typical real estate transaction,'' said the researchers, who
figured the average fee equalled about 6.6 percent of the economic
gain created by the mergers.
   Furthermore, the investment bankers' fees averaged a ``very
reasonable'' less than 1 percent of the total transaction price,
with the highest being 3.4 percent of the price, Hunter said.
   The study was published in the Atlanta Fed's Economic Review
publication.
   The researchers limited their survey to friendly mergers of
public companies and did not look at those where investment banks
provided only fairness or underwriting services. Walker said it was
the first survey to compare fees with services rendered.
   The mergers ranged in value from $34 million to $6 billion, with
fees ranging from $100,000 to $20 million.
   The two largest fees came from the $2.8 billion deal in 1984
that joined Beatrice Foods Co. and Esmark Inc. and the $5 billion
merger in 1985 of Allied Corp with the Signal Cos. Inc.
   Hunter said each deal paid $20 million to the investment banks
involved _ First Boston Corp. and Lazard Freres and Co. in
Beatrice-Esmark; Lazard, Salomon Brothers and Oppenheimer and Co.
in the Allied-Signal merger.
   The wave of mergers and acquisitions in recent years has brought
more attention to the fees paid investment bankers, with some
critics claiming the fees are excessive.
   Trade publications have discussed the fees in articles with
titles like ``Merger Fees That Bend the Mind'' and ``Wall Street's
Overpaid Young Stars.'' The merger departments of three separate
Wall Street firms each earned $200 million in 1985.
   Hunter said the attention and worry have caused some
merger-minded companies to consider a do-it-yourself approach.
   But Hunter and Ms. Walker argued against bypassing the
investment bankers.
   ``Bringing together of buyer and seller and advising on what
price to pay _ from that point of view, (investment bankers) seem
to be well worth their fee,'' Hunter said in an interview.
   ``Firms contemplating a do-it-yourself approach simply because
fees charged by professional merger intermediaries appear excessive
would do well to scrutinize the costs and benefits of
self-search,'' Hunter and Ms. Walker wrote.
   The researchers note that investment banks traditionally have
provided a range of services, including underwriting, market-making
and advice on capital structure, dividend policy, mergers,
acquisitions and divestitures.
   ``While other financial institutions provide many of these same
services, the investment banks' specialization and expertise in
corporate financial matters, along with their position overlooking
capital markets as a whole, give them a comparative advantage that
permits them to command handsome fees,'' they wrote.
   Hunter also said investment bankers are constantly gathering and
assessing information on corporate assets, research that would have
to be done otherwise by individual suitors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880707-0186 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 0146EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AutoSales Bjt   07-07 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0505</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Domestic And Imported Auto Makers Report Late June Sales Increases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Car shoppers in a healthy economy, lured by
sophisticated incentive programs, are likely to keep on buying at
the higher-than-expected rates of the first half of the year,
industry analysts say.
   The big three domestic automakers on Wednesday reported a jump
in their sales rates during the June 21-30 sales period.
   Combined domestic car and light truck sales totaled 459,918
during the late-June period this year, against 359,784 in the same
period last yera, a jump of 13.6 percent in daily sales rate.
   The late-June period had nine selling days this year and eight
in 1987, so percentage comparisons are made on the basis of daily
sales rates rather than total sales.
   Combined domestic car and light truck sales totaled 1,120,962
for all of June, an 8.5 percent increase in daily sales, and
6,184,576 for the year through June 30, up 11 percent from the
first half of 1987.
   ``We see sales for the rest of the year as pretty good, with a
possible soft spot in October,'' said Thomas O'Grady, an analyst
with Integrated Automotive Resources Inc. in Wayne, Pa.
   A late-year lull might occur as buyers wait to see what
incentives will be offered on newly introduced 1989 models in
dealers' showrooms, he said.
   Among imports, car and light truck sales totaled 333,066 for the
month, down 7.6 percent, and 1,874,004 for the first half, down 1.5
percent.
   For the June 21-30 sales period, Ford Motor Co. sold 89,927
cars, a 27.4 percent jump in daily sales. For the year through June
30, Ford sold 1,161,574 cars, a 12.8 percent increase over the
first half of 1987.
   General Motors sold 144,205 cars in late June, an 18 percent
jump, and 1,952,402 for the first six months, a 4.9 percent
increase.
   Chrysler Corp. sold 40,817 cars in late June, up 8.4 percent a
day, and 574,609 for the first half of 1988, up 14.3 percent.
   O'Grady said sales were helped by the apparent success of new
models at some automakers, such as General Motors GM-10 models. He
also said sales were helped by U.S. automakers' increasing
adeptness at offering incentives, with shorter programs and more
frequent changes in affected models, smoothing sales peaks and
valleys the programs once triggered.
   ``The combination of record employment and a need to replace old
vehicles gave the industry a good start this year,'' Ford vice
president Robert L. Rewey said.
   Honda sold 30,049 domestically made cars and 33,279 imports in
June, up from 25,015 U.S. made cars and 31,078 imports last June.
Toyota sales of U.S.-produced cars for the month reached 3,066, up
from 1,228, and its imports rose to 54,906 from 47,584 last June.
   Nissan sold 49,957 U.S. produced cars in the first half of the
year, down 23.4 percent, and 24,644 imported cars, down 67.3
percent.
</TEXT>
