<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Gillette-Coniston     07-07 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gillette-Coniston,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Rules Gillette Issued Misleading Reports On Proxy Rival</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Assoicated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gillette Co. inaccurately portrayed a New
York-based partnership during a proxy battle earlier this year but
did not mislead shareholders by withholding information about
potential buyers, says a federal judge.
   U.S. District Court Judge Mark L. Wolf issued his ruling
Wednesday but withheld a decision on whether to invalidate an April
shareholder vote that defeated a dissident slate of directors
nominated by the investment group Coniston Partners.
   The judge postponed that decision until after further testimony
by Gillette on alleged proxy violations by Coniston.
   In a prepared statement, Gillette said it was ``surprised and
disappointed'' by the ruling on the advertisements.
   ``While Gillette disagrees with (the) ruling and believes its
conduct was proper, its immediate efforts will be directed
vigorously toward the further critical issues in the case relating
to Coniston's conduct,'' the statement said.
   Coniston principals were not in their New York offices when
called for comment Wednesday.
   During the trial, which began June 20, both sides alleged
violations and misrepresentations occurred during their nearly
three-month proxy battle over four seats on the Gillette board of
directors.
   Wolf ruled that several newspaper advertisements by Gillette
during the proxy solicition contained ``falsely misleading''
information about Coniston. But Wolf said he still was reviewing
whether Coniston violated full disclosure laws in its filings with
the Securities and Exchange Commission.
   He also ruled that Gillette was not required to provide
stockholders with names of companies interested in acquiring the
Boston-based company, including Ralston Purina Co. and Anheuser
Busch Co.
   At least 10 companies have signed agreements not to seek control
of Gillette without first notifying Gillette management, according
to court testimony. Most of the pacts expire in November.
   Gillette on April 14 filed suit seeking to block Coniston's
proxy bid on the grounds Coniston falsified SEC filings and did not
fully acknowledge all of its investors, including Swiss finacier
Tito Tettamanti.
   Judge Rya Zobel allowed the suit but rejected the bid for the
temporary injunction.
   A countersuit by Coniston filed on April 19 alleged Gillette
misrepresented Coniston in advertisements and mailings to the
company's 27,000 shareholders and failed to publicly disclose the
companies that had expressed interest in buying Gillette.
   Gillette shareholders rejected the dissident Coniston slate by a
52 percent to 48 percent vote during the April 21 annual meeting.
The candidates _ Coniston partners Augustus K. Oliver, Paul E.
Tierney Jr., Keith R. Gollust and cable television executive David
Strassler _ had indicated they would urge the 12-member Gillette
board to sell the company.
   Two Coniston subsidiaries own 6.76 million Gillette shares, or
about 5.8 percent of the shares outstanding.
   Zobel withdrew from the case June 11 on the grounds that she and
Gillette Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Colman Mockler are
affiliated with Harvard University.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
