<HEAD>Stocks Fall</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with closing figures.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices on the London Stock Exchange finished lower
Thursday, as price weakness on Wall Street spilled over into the
London market.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index fell 14.5
points, or 0.8 percent, to 1,855.5 after trading below Wednesday's
closing level throughout the session.
   Trading volume was 419.9 million shares, compared with 500.2
million shares traded on Wednesday.
   The Dow Jones industrial average opened 4 points lower Thursday
in New York after losing 28.45 points in the previous session.
   Market players in London were relieved for most of the afternoon
that New York prices did not slide further.
   But prices on Wall Street retreated late in the London trading
day, and the Dow Jones industrial average was off 21.16 points at
2,109.00 by the time trading ended in London.
   ``We're getting bashed by the dominating (Wall) Street,'' one
equity salesman said. ``And we're not doing a very good job of
fending them off.''
   Several London market watchers said dealings were extremely
listless for most of the day. ``It's just a torpid market,'' one
equity salesman said.
