<1ST_LINE>r f AM-NewHiring     07-07 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-New Hiring,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jobs Ads Edged Up in May, Conference Board Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release 6 p.m. EDT _ time set for source</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pace of new hiring slowed during May as the
steady improvement in labor conditions leveled off, a research
group said Thursday.
   The Conference Board, a business-financed research organization,
said its help-wanted advertising index edged up three points in May
to 160. The index measures the monthly volume of classified
advertising in 51 major newspapers in the United States.
   The group said such advertising increased moderately in all
sections of the country, except for Texas, Louisiana and Oklahoma,
which saw a 4.1 percent decline. Elsewhere, the gains ranged from
6.5 percent in the New York-Pennsylvania area to 0.5 percent in the
Nebraska, Minnesota and Missouri region.
   Job growth in the second half of the year is expected to lag
behind the first half of 1988, the Conference Board said.
   ``This should be good news for those still concerned about the
economy overheating and setting off inflation sparks,'' said
Kenneth Goldstein, an economist for the organization.
   With the latest employment data showing little change, new
hiring is unlikely to rise sharply in the next few months,
Goldstein said. May's 5.6 percent unemployment rate matched the
March level.
   ``All of this suggests that the long, steady improvement in
labor market conditions has run its course,'' he said.
</TEXT>
