<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0303</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices headed lower today in a carryover
of selling from Wednesday's drop.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, down 28.45 points on
Wednesday, lost another 12.63 to 2,117.53 by 2 p.m. today on Wall
Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by nearly 9 to 5 in the overall count
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 499 up, 885 down and
516 unchanged.
   Analysts said the market's downturn Wednesday from 1988 highs
reached earlier in the week intensified recent concerns that the
early-summer rally in stock prices might be topping out.
   In addition, interest rates rose today in the credit markets.
Yields on long-term Treasury bonds have climbed of late back above
9 percent, driven in large measure by recurring worries about
inflation.
   The Labor Department is due to report Friday morning on the
employment situation for June. If the data show strong job growth,
brokers say traders might read it as a signal of increasing
inflationary pressures.
   Occidental Petroleum dropped | to 26\ in active trading. The
company owns the oil rig in the North Sea where a fire Wednesday
night resulted in many casualties and extensive damage.
   Carl Karcher Enterprises climbed 2} to 21~ in the
over-the-counter market. The company announced plans to buy back
about 25 percent of its outstanding stock.
   Apollo Computer, another OTC issue, tumbled 4{ to 10}. Thea braid factory
and as a mailman before
joining the police force. His stellar record got him into law
school without benefit of a high school diploma.
   After law school, Biaggi worked for Republican Gov. Nelson
Rockefeller, but was bounced from a post as assistant secretary of
state in 1965 after refusing an order to take unpaid leave instead
of vacation to work on the mayoral campaign of Abraham Beame.
(Beame lost that race to John Lindsay.)
   In 1968, Biaggi was elected to Congress to fill the seat of
Republican Paul Fino, who had been appointed a judge. He has been
re-elected every two years, with overwhelming majorities; he became
known as a law-and-order Democrat, an advocate of hand-gun control
and an opponent of British rule in Northern Ireland.
   But one office always eluded him: he desperately wanted to be
elected mayor of New York City.
   Why did he want to be mayor?
   ``Why do people climb the Himalayas?'' he replied.
   In 1972, he made a run for the job and looked to be a shoo-in
for the Democratic nomination, which in New York City is tantamount
to election. But Biaggi's candidacy was destroyed by a series of
investigations and allegations, which culminated in his being
proven a liar.
   At the time, Biaggi was questioned by a grand jury looking into
allegations of payoffs to congressmen who sponsored certain
immigration legislation. When reports surfaced that Biaggi had
taken the Fifth Amendment before the panel, he vehemently denied it.
   He sued to have some, but not all, of the record made public.
But the tactic backfired when the judge released all the minutes,
proving Biaggi had in fact asserted his right to not to incriminate
himself.
   Beame was elected mayor and Biaggi went back to Congress.
   In 1986, new accusations were leveled at Biaggi and these began
to stick.
   First, he was indicted for illegally accepting paid vacations in
exchange for using his influence to steer federal contracts to
Coastal Dry Dock and Repair, a Brooklyn shipyard. He was convicted
of taking a gratuity, illegal interstate travel and obstruction.
But he wept when he was sentenced to 2{ years in prison and fined
$500,000. Biaggi is appealing the decision.
   A second indictment accused him of using the Wedtech Corp., a
Bronx-based machine company, as a racketeering enterprise. The case
is now on trial in New York and Biaggi is charged with accepting
millions of dollars' worth of company stock, issued in his son's
name, in exchange for helping the company get military contracts.
His son and four others are on trial with Biaggi.
   The House of Representatives forced Biaggi to relinquish his
subcommittee chairmanships after the first indictment last year and
to refrain from voting after his conviction in September, but those
moves were slaps on the wrist compared to what was to come.
   In February, the House Committee on Standards of Official
Conduct recommended that Biaggi be expelled for ``criminal conduct
... going to the heart of his representational responsibilities.''
In an unusual maneuver, however, congressional leaders decided to
delay action while Biaggi defended himself in the Wedtech trial in
New York.
   It is unclear when the resolution may be brought up, but Biaggi
has resolved to fight it. It must pass by a two-thirds vote of the
House. Asked what his defense would be, he said simply, ``Truth.''
   Biaggi has not denied taking the two vacations to a Florida spa,
which were paid for by former Brooklyn Democratic boss Meade
Esposito.
   ``He's a friend of 40 years,'' Biaggi said. ``It boggles the
mind.''
   At the time, however, Coastal owed Esposito's insurance company
$280,000 in premiums. Esposito was himself convicted of paying
illegal gratuities and given a two-year suspended prison term and a
maximum fine of $500,000.
   Biaggi compared his situation to that of former U.S. Labor
Secretary Raymond Donovan, the first sitting Cabinet member to be
indicted. Donovan was acquitted in May 1987 of larceny and fraud
charges that forced him from office in 1985.
   Biaggi, however, was convicted. Still, he bristled at
comparisons to Rep. Michael ``Ozzie'' Myers, D-Pa., the last
congressman to be expelled. Myers, ousted in 1980, was convicted of
bribery after being videotaped taking $50,000 in the Abscam sting.
   ``I don't think the case is comparable,'' Biaggi said. ``His was
for bribery. You're talking about a gratuity.''
   Despite his legal woes and editorials urging him to resign,
Biaggi said he is ``absolutely'' running for an 11th term.
   As a convicted felon, however, he won't even be able to cast a
vote for himself.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tue AMs, July 12</NOTE>
