<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 1420EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Airliner-USAirlines Bjt   07-07 0693</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airliner-US Airlines, Bjt,0720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Airlines Step Up Security in Wake of Persian Gulf Incident</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The big U.S. airlines that fly overseas say they
are taking no chances with retaliation from terrorists and have
stepped up their defenses in response to the U.S. Navy's downing of
an Iran Air jetliner.
   ``We take the threat seriously,'' said Stephen Heckscher, a
spokesman in London for Trans World Airlines' international
division.
   The incident in the Persian Gulf last weekend, which killed
nearly 300 civilians, has raised fears of a retaliatory attack by
Iran.
   Political experts have suggested that revenge could take the
form of a terrorist assault against U.S. military bases or
personnel overseas, or against other American targets _ including
commercial airline flights.
   Bob Kierce, TWA's director of international security, said the
airline has taken steps to ensure that its already tight security
precautions ``are being exercised to the fullest.''
   Kierce said the airline also has added some new measures at
several airports, which he declined to name. Those measures include
having a senior member of management on duty whenever a TWA plane
is on the ground at those locations.
   TWA, the nation's seventh-largest airline, has been the target
of some of the most notorious terrorist attacks against jetliners
in recent years. In June 1985, Lebanese Shiite Moslems hijacked a
TWA flight over the Mediterranean and diverted it to Beirut, where
they killed a passenger. The hostages weren't freed until 17 days
later.
   Terrorists set off a bomb in the passenger cabin of a TWA
jetliner over Greece in April 1986, killing four Americans.
   Other U.S. airlines that carry passengers abroad also have been
on alert following the Iran Air disaster, beefing up security in
the midst of the peak summer travel season, experts say.
   Like TWA, most big carriers have their own security divisions
but also contract with outside security companies for passenger
screening in airports and other protective services.
   Many of the airlines are touchy about security and refuse to
discuss what they're doing. But they emphasize that anti-terrorist
defenses are always intensified after such an incident.
   ``(The airlines) don't need a crystal ball; it's so obvious,''
said Dick Lally, assistant vice president for security at the Air
Transport Association, a Washington-based trade group that
represents the nation's major carriers.
   The airlines have most likely tightened their security in
consultation with the Federal Aviation Administration, Lally
suggested.
   Pamela Hanlon, a spokeswoman for Pan Am Corp., said there is
always ``heightened awareness'' of security when a potential
terrorist attack looms. ``Our security, we believe, is overall
very, very good,'' she said.
   In addition to its World Services subsidiary, which sells
security, maintenance and other services to government agencies and
other airlines, Pan Am also has an internal security division.
   After TWA, Pan Am probably has the highest profile among the
American carriers that are active overseas.
   United Airlines has increased security at some of the foreign
airports it uses, spokesman Dan Sheehy said. United, the nation's
largest carrier with scores of domestic flights, has all its
overseas operations in the Far East.
   In a similar way, Eastern Airlines specializes in Latin America
as its foreign market.
   ``We are taking additional precautions,'' said Eastern
spokeswoman Paula Musto. Eastern, a subsidiary of giant Texas Air
Corp., was the target of several hijackings to Cuba between 1979
and 1981, but drug smuggling is now its biggest security headache.
   Airlines from countries that are identified as close allies of
the United States could also be potential targets of the Iranians'
ire.
   Israel's national El Al Airlines has a reputation as the world's
toughest carrier when it comes to security. In some instances in
Europe, El Al has kept its flight routes secret from passengers
until they actually boarded the plane. El Al also sometimes uses
planes of a subsidiary that do not carry the carrier's bright blue
logo.
   ``We don't talk about our security. We just do it,'' said Aviva
Lavi, a spokeswoman for El Al in its New York office, refusing to
say whether the airline had tightened security as a result of the
Persian Gulf shooting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880707-0194 </DOCNO>
