<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 1526EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-OilRig-Impact 1stLd-Writethru   07-07 0678</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oil Rig-Impact, 1st Ld-Writethru,0700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Jump But Analysts Do Not Expect Big Impact</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with apparent cause of accident,
more closures. Picks up 9th graf pvs, ``There's pressure ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A massive oil rig fire off the coast of Scotland
will worsen a shortage of North Sea oil, but the disaster is not
likely to have a big impact on the industry, experts say.
   The fatal accident, which caused a jump in world oil prices
Thursday, prompted the government's Department of Energy to
postpone the process for granting new off-shore licenses, which
would open up more areas for exploration. The department had been
scheduled to announce on Thursday the blocks for which it was
inviting bids for the licenses.
   ``Because of what happened, we've decided to postpone that at
the moment,'' said a department spokesman, who spoke anonymously in
keeping with British practice.
   The price of Brent Blend, the most widely traded international
crude oil, jumped on Thursday to $15.05 a barrel for September
delivery, up 32 cents from late Wednesday.
   Occidental Petroleum Co., owner of the Piper Alpha rig, said a
gas leak apparently was to blame for the disaster.
   The rig produced 167,200 barrels a day, the company said. A
barrel contains 42 gallons.
   In addition to the Piper oil field, five other fields were shut
down, the department said. They were the Claymore, Tartan,
Highland, Scapa and Petronella fields, it said.
   That meant production was cut by a total of about 220,000
barrels a day to 250,000 barrels a day, or about one-tenth of the
British sector's production, the department and analysts said.
   ``There's pressure on the immediate availability for North Sea
crude,'' said Philip Morgan, an oil analyst with the London
investment firm Warburg Securities.
   Lucy Mullins, an oil analyst with the London investment firm
Barclays de Zoete Wedd Ltd., added, however: ``That's going to be
fairly short-term.''
   The related fields should be back in production in a week, and
Piper Alpha probably will be out of production for up to a year,
Ms. Mullins said.
   Morgan said the industry already was experiencing a shortage
because of regular maintenance, which oil companies generally do in
the summmer when the weather is milder.
   North Sea oil production in the British sector averages 2{
million barrels a day, the Department of Energy says. Production is
down 400,000 barrels a day from that level because of the
maintenance, Morgan said.
   Producers of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries,
of which Britain is not a member, will step in to meet demand, Ms.
Mullins said.
   The oil price also has been boosted by favorable statistics
released this week, Morgan said.
   ``There is starting to be a perception that the glut in world
supplies in general is not as bad as people thought,'' Morgan said.
   Occidental Petroleum's production won't be severely affected by
the fire, because it has other outlets, Ms. Mullins said.
   There were concerns about claims against the company, however,
and Occidental Petroleum's stock fell 50 cents to $26.25 in early
trading on the New York Stock Exchange. The stock price of British
Petroleum Co. PLC, the biggest producer in the British sector, fell
3 cents to $4.49 in afternoon trading on London's Stock Exchange.
   The disaster could prove expensive for the North Sea oil
producers in general, Morgan said.
   ``Obviously, questions are going to be raised about safety which
might involve companies in a lot more expenditure,'' Morgan said.
   The British sector of the North Sea oil fields runs from the
Shetland Islands north of Scotland down to East Anglia on England's
southeast coast, covering hundreds of thousands of square miles.
The first British sector gas fields were discovered in 1964 and oil
production began in 1975, the Department of Energy said.
   The sector employed 28,000 people in offshore facilities at the
end of last year, it said.
   There are 123 fixed installations, including the Piper Alpha
platform, in the British sector, with 40 mobile rigs, the
department said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880707-0196 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 1531EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-FedNominee     07-07 0598</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fed Nominee,0616</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Reserve Nominee Quizzed on `Golden Parachute'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's latest nominee for a seat
on the Federal Reserve Board was accused Thursday of attempting to
dodge taxes in negotiating a $2.5-million ``golden parachute''
compensation agreement with the Boston bank holding company he
heads.
   ``I am concerned about it,'' Sen. William Proxmire, D-Wis.,
chairman of the Senate Banking Committee, said of the agreement at
the end of a confirmation hearing for John P. LaWare, chairman of
Shawmut National Corp.
   LaWare said ``I'm not sure a tax dodge was involved'' in the
compensation agreement, which he said was offered to assure him
that his annual income of about $500,000 would be continued until
he reaches age 65. He turned 60 on Feb. 20.
   Despite Proxmire's concern that the bank _ not LaWare _ is
obligated to pay a special excise tax on a portion of the pay
agreement, there was no indication the issue would affect LaWare's
nomination. In fact, Proxmire told LaWare, ``You are a very
impressive candidate for the job.''
   However, committee aides say some Democrats are reluctant to see
the nomination approved because it would mean that Reagan would
have filled all seven seats on the board, which controls the
nation's money supply.
   These senators are hoping that fellow Democrat Michael Dukakis
will be elected president and could promptly fill the Federal
Reserve seat after taking office next January.
   LaWare, a registered Democrat, would replace Henry G. Wallich,
who resigned. The 14-year term would expire Jan. 31, 2002.
   Proxmire told reporters he will confer with committee members
before deciding whether the panel should vote on the LaWare
nomination this year. Should the panel recommend the nomination, it
would be up to Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., to
determine whether the Senate should consider the nomination this
year.
   The issue of monetary policy was barely mentioned at the
hearing. Most questions were about the federal budget and trade
deficits, the increasing share of U.S. debt held by foreign
investors and Third World debt.
   LaWare said he is little concerned about the fact that only one
of the world's 10 biggest banks is American. ``I don't think that
makes much difference,'' he said. ``It's how well-managed and
profitable they are ... I am more concerned with the
profit-and-loss statement'' than with size.
   None of the other committee members took up Proxmire's line of
questioning about the ``golden parachute'' agreement, which was
negotiated earlier this year as part of the merger that created
Shamut National Corp.
   Similar agreements are used to reward executives when control or
ownership of a corporation changes. In 1984, Congress required
recipients of such arrangements to pay a 20 percent excise tax on
the portion that the law considers excessive. In addition,
corporations were barred from taking a tax deduction for the
excessive payments.
   Under LaWare's agreement, which he acknowledged to be worth
about $500,000 a year, the corporation itself is obligated to pay
the 20 percent tax.
   Proxmire estimated that would save LaWare about $200,000 in
taxes.
   ``How do you justify such an attempt to dodge the tax code?''
Proxmire asked. The idea behind the 1984 law, he said, ``was to
discourage excessive payments which officers and directors vote
themselves.''
   ``I'm not sure it's a dodge,'' LaWare said. ``The tax is being
paid, regardless'' and the federal government is losing no money,
he said.
   LaWare must pay income tax on the full amount of the ``golden
parachute'' payment, including whatever amount the bank chips in to
cover the special excise tax.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
