<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-GeneralMills     07-07 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-General Mills,0370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>General Mills' Profit Up 53 Percent in Fourth Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Mills Inc. said its profit jumped 53
percent in its fourth quarter from a year earlier, boosted by a
lower tax rate, good volume growth in consumer foods, strong
performance by key restaurant chains, and significant productivity
gains.
   The food giant reported Thursday that its profit for the quarter
ended May 29 rose to $54.9 million, or 65 cents a share, from $36.1
million, or 41 cents a share, in the fourth quarter of fiscal 1987.
   Fourth-quarter sales increased to $1.3 billion from $1.2 billion
a year earlier.
   For fiscal 1988, which was one week shorter than fiscal 1987,
earnings rose 27 percent to $283.1 million, or $3.25 a share, from
$222 million, or $2.50 a share.
   Sales in fiscal 1988 were up 10 percent, to $5.2 billion from
$4.7 billion the previous year.
   The earnings report for the fourth quarter includes the
discontinued specialty retailing operations of Talbots and Eddie
Bauer. General Mills will post a $200 million gain after taxes in
the first quarter of fiscal 1989 from the sale of the retailing
companies.
   General Mills Chairman Bruce Atwater said the consumer foods
division achieved a 4 percent increase in domestic packaged food
volume, leading to annual sales and operating profit gains of 9
percent and 11 percent, respectively. The company said the success
of several new microwave food products and growing acceptance of
Yoplait yogurt and other new foods contributed to the earnings
increase.
   Spending on Big G cereals for the fourth quarter was
particularly strong, as both volume and market share grew, Atwater
said.
   In the restaurant division, Red Lobster and Olive Garden
operations were up 16 percent. Both Leeann Chin's and York's
reported losses, including charges of $12.9 million related to
closing unprofitable units, which caused total operating profits to
be down 4 percent.
   During the fiscal year, the company invested $411 million in new
assets, an increase of 25 percent from a year earlier. Major
investments were for new food capacity, new and improved Red
Lobsters, new Olive Gardens, and investments for improved
efficiencies, Atwater said.
</TEXT>
