<1ST_LINE>r f AM-VirginGroup     07-07 0206</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Virgin Group,0213</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Entertainment Company May Go Private</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Virgin Group PLC said Thursday it is considering
buying back the 28-percent stake held by the public in the British
music and entertainment company.
   Virgin Chairman Richard Branson said the company is concerned
that ``the benefits of a listing which (were) anticipated'' when
Virgin shares were sold to the public 1{ years ago ``are not being
realized.''
   Branson noted the drop in Virgin's share price to a recent range
of between $1.46 a share to $1.63 a share from the $2.41 a share
paid when the 50 million shares were sold in November 1986.
   Virgin shares, which are also traded in American Depository
Receipt form in the United States, traded at $2 a share on London's
Stock Exchange on Thursday, up 30 cents from Wednesday's close.
   ``Virgin's strategy of investment for long-term growth, with its
effects on short-term profitability, has had an adverse effect on
its share price,'' Branson said in a statement. He added that he
was not disposed toward altering this strategy for the sake of
improving the stock's performance.
   Virgin Group is separate from Branson's Virgin Atlantic Airways,
the cut-rate trans-Atlantic airline which is owned by privately
held Voyager Group Ltd.
</TEXT>
