<1ST_LINE>u f AM-BankBid Bjt   07-07 0693</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bank Bid, Bjt,0714</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fed To Decide Several Key Issues in Bank Takeover Saga</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Banca Commerciale Italiana SpA, Italy's second
largest bank, may be forced to abandon its friendly merger plans
with Irving Bank Corp. if it fails to win regulatory approval to
pay Irving shareholders a special cash dividend, experts said
Thursday.
   That could be a boon to Bank of New York, which has been bidding
for control of Irving for more than nine months, the analysts said.
   Regulators already have raised serious concerns about special
payouts, with one top official from the Federal Reserve Bank of New
York saying they should be considered only by banks with more than
adequate capital.
   ``It seems a little odd that this (the special dividend) comes
into play right now,'' when the Fed is trying to standardize
international bank capital adequacy requirements by 1992, said
James J. McDermott Jr., a banking analyst with the investment firm
Keefe Bruyette & Woods.
   ``1988 has been a year when most major money-center banks have
been building capital, not paying out extra dividends,'' he said.
   But a proposed $10-a-share special cash dividend is a key
element of Banca Commerciale's offer to buy a majority stake in
Irving as an alternative to Bank of New York's hostile bid.
   The Milan-based bank is offering $80 a share for 51 percent of
Irving's 18.5 million common shares outstanding and the special
dividend for the remaining 49 percent.
   Earlier this week it sweetened the offer to include warrants
entitling shareholders to buy newly issued Irving stock at $65 a
share over the next seven years. Stockholders would receive one
warrant for every four shares they now own. The offer is valued at
a minimum of $79.50 a share.
   Bank of New York, which owns a 4.9 percent stake in Irving, is
offering $15 in cash and 1.575 shares of its own stock for each of
Irving's common shares outstanding. The offer is valued at around
$68 a share or $1.2 billion.
   ``From a practical standpoint I would think if the Fed was to
disallow the (Banca Commerciale) special dividend ... that would
place pressure on BCI to increase its offer in a tangible manner,''
said Michael Starr, a banking analyst with Duff & Phelps Inc.
   ``I wouldn't think it would have to be a dollar-for-dollar
match. I don't think the market expected the full $10 to go through
anyway. That was a major `if.'''
   A number of analysts agreed that at some point it might no
longer be economically feasible for Banca Commerciale to continue
with the deal, leaving Irving alone with Bank of New York's
persistent takeover advances.
   ``I believe it (current offer) already is at the upper end of
the range,'' said McDermott.
   Patricia Skigen, of Willkie, Farr & Gallagher, Banca
Commerciale's legal adviser, said her client remained committed to
the Irving merger.
   ``The offer that we made is outstanding,'' Ms. Skigen said.
   She contended the Fed's reservations about special dividends,
contained in a letter dated Wednesday to all three banks by New
York Fed executive vice president Frederick C. Schadrack, was meant
solely as a ``a spot policy statement to the world at large.''
   The Fed also must determine whether to grant Bank of New York an
extension of conditional approval for its proposed merger with
Irving. Bank of New York asked for 60 more days on Thursday; the
Fed approval was due to expire Saturday.
   In addition, a New York appeals court will be faced with
deciding whether a provison of Irving's anti-takeover ``poison
pill'' is valid. It was struck down by the New York state Supreme
Court on Wednesday, but Irving has vowed to appeal.
   In other developments Thursday, a court-appointed referee
refused to change the outcome of a crucial proxy vote in which
shareholders re-elected Irving's board of directors over Bank of
New York's nominees.
   The referee did decide, however, that a block of 450,000 votes
of Irving shares belonged in Bank of New York's camp and that an
amendment to Irving's bylaws alolowing 10 percent of holders to
call a special shareholder meeting had passed.
</TEXT>
