<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   07-07 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0503</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices lost ground for the second straight
session Thursday, but finished well above their midday lows.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, down more than 20
points at one stage, closed with a 7.47 loss at 2,122.69. The
average fell 28.45 points on Wednesday.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 3 to 2 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
587 up, 850 down and 525 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 156.10 million
shares, against 189.63 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in
those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter
market, totaled 180.67 million shares.
   Analysts said the market's downturn Wednesday from 1988 highs
reached earlier in the week intensified recent concerns that the
early-summer rally in stock prices might be topping out.
   In addition, interest rates rose in the credit markets. Yields
on long-term Treasury bonds have climbed of late back above 9
percent, driven in large measure by recurring worries about
inflation.
   The Labor Department is due to report Friday morning on the
employment situation for June. If the data show strong job growth,
brokers say traders might read it as a signal of increasing
inflationary pressures.
   However, inflation worries were dampened a bit in late trading
Thursday when prices of key agricultural commodities fell on talk
of some approaching rain in the drought-parched Farm Belt.
   Occidental Petroleum dropped | to 26\ in active trading. The
company owns the oil rig in the North Sea where a fire Wednesday
night resulted in many casualties and extensive damage.
   The company said Thursday the disaster was caused by a gas leak,
and added that it wouldn't hurt its finances enough to force a
change in its dividend policy.
   General Electric rose ~ to 44[. The company reported a 16
percent increase in its earnings for the second quarter.
   Wheeling-Pittsburgh Steel gained 1} to 17}. The company said it
couldn't explain the activity.
   Carl Karcher Enterprises climbed 3 to 22[ in the
over-the-counter market. The company announced plans to buy back
about 25 percent of its outstanding stock.
   Apollo Computer, another OTC issue, tumbled 4] to 10~. The
company said it expects to report a loss for the second quarter.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market lost $2.36 billion, or 0.09
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
slipped .14 to 153.62.
   Standard & Poor's industrial index fell .13 to 314.25, and S&P's
500-stock composite index was down .24 at 271.78.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market lost
.02 to 395.43. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 308.95, down .26.
