<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp Bjt   07-07 0787</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp, Bjt,0816</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain Futures Plunge As Weekend Looks Wetter</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting to restore Bjt designtaion</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Most grain and soybean futures prices plummeted their limits for
daily trading Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade, taking some
analysts by surprise and leaving them divided on the reasons for
the move.
   On other markets, gasoline futures soared and other energy
futures also gained; livestock and meat were mixed; precious metals
advanced; and stock-index futures gained.
   ``I'm astounded,'' Katharina Zimmer, New York-based grains
analyst for Merrill Lynch Capital Markets Inc., said after the
grain and soybean markets closed.
   Most corn, soybean and oat contracts plunged their respective
15-, 30- and 10-cent limits for daily trading, and the limitless
contracts for July delivery fell even further. Wheat contracts for
December, March and July 1989 delivery tumbled 20 cents a bushel,
the limit in that market.
   Despite new forecasts for weekend rains in the dry and dusty
Midwest, Ms. Zimmer said the sell-off was technically inspired.
   ``This market has nothing to do with fundamentals any more,''
she said. Instead, she said, Thursday's action was dominated by
so-called technicians, who base their trading decisions on
historical chart patterns.
   On Thursday, the charts indicated it was time to sell, Ms.
Zimmer said.
   More likely, the drop was caused by a combination of technical
and fundamental factors, said Ted Mao, grain specialist with
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   Though prices turned lower shortly after the opening, Mao said
the sharpest drop followed midday news reports that Senate Minority
Leader Robert Dole, R-Kan., had said the Senate may consider
measures allowing farmers to plant soybeans and oats on a portion
of their acreage idled under government crop programs.
   But Dole, speaking to the Commodity Club in Washington, said the
Senate probably would not act on the matter for at least another
month.
   Private forecasts for moderate rainfall this weekend in the
northern Corn Belt also pressured the markets, Mao said.
   ``The market continues to show its sensitivity to prospects of
getting even a little bit of rain,'' he said.
   ``That's nonsense,'' countered Ms. Zimmer, who dismissed the
expected rain as ``sprinkles.''
   ``To tell an Illinois farmer we're locked limit-down because of
the rain we're going to get, I don't know what they'd say, but it
probably would not be printable,'' she said.
   Wheat settled 15{ cents to 20 cents lower with the contract for
delivery in July at $3.78 a bushel; corn was 14{ cents to 22 cents
lower with July at $3.20 a bushel; oats were 10 cents to 22 cents
lower with July at $3.01 a bushel; soybeans were 26 cents to 49{
cents lower with July at $9.34{ a bushel.
   Prices for future delivery of unleaded gasoline and heating oil
soared on the New York Mercantile Exchange in reaction to
Wednesday's weekly American Petroleum Institute report showing a
sharp drawdown in gasoline supplies, analysts said.
   Energy futures were broadly supported by reports that the tragic
explosion of a North Sea oil rig could cause production of North
Sea crude oil to fall by 30,000 barrels a day, said Nauman Barakat,
energy analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Crude-oil futures declined on profit-taking in the second half
of the session, he said.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 43 cents to 55 cents
higher with August at $15.83 a barrel; heating oil was 1.37 cents
to 1.68 cents higher with August at 44.29 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was 1.23 cents to 2.56 cents higher with August at 53.12
cents a gallon.
   The inflationary implications of higher energy prices supported
precious metals futures on New York's Commodity Exchange, analysts
said.
   Gold settled 40 cents to $1.20 higher with August at $441.10 a
troy ounce; silver was 11.5 cents to 13.6 cents higher with July at
$6.935 a troy ounce.
   Livestock and meat futures finished mixed on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
   The drop in grain prices prompted reversals of recent
drought-related trends in the cattle and hog markets, and pork
bellies rebounded sharply after touching 8-year lows on Wednesday,
said Paul Hare, an analyst with Linnco Futures Inc. in Chicago.
   Live cattle were .60 cent lower to .15 cent higher with August
at 64.75 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .38 cent
higher with August at 74.75 cents a pound; hogs were 1.50 cents
lower to .83 cent higher with July at 45.40 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were .70 cent lower to 2 cents higher with July at
34.40 cents a pound.
   Stock-index futures finished higher on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for September delivery of the Standard
& Poor's index settled 1.20 points higher at 273.20.
</TEXT>
