<1ST_LINE>u f AM-MoneySupply     07-07 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Money Supply,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Money Supply Measures Rise in Late June</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three measures of the nation's money supply rose
in the week ended June 27, the Federal Reserve Board reported
Thursday.
   The Fed said the narrowest measure known as M1 rose $400 million
to a seasonally adjusted $778.8 billion from a revised $778.4
billion the previous week.
   A broader measure, M2, rose to a seasonally adjusted $3.020
trillion from $3.018 trillion the previous week.
   An even broader measure, M3, increased to a seasonally adjusted
$3.809 trillion from $3.804 trillion.
   M1 includes cash in circulation, deposits in checking accounts
and non-bank travelers checks. M2 is M1 plus accounts like savings
deposits and money-market mutual funds. M3 is M2 plus less-liquid
accounts, such as certificates of deposit in minimum denominations
of $100,000.
   In judging its monetary policy, the Fed has indicated it is
monitoring the value of the dollar, commodity prices and the
difference between short- and long-term interest rates as well as
money supply trends.
   In other reports:
   _The Federal Reserve Bank of New York reported commercial and
industrial loans at major New York City banks fell $857 million,
compared with a decline of $561 million a week earlier.
   _The Federal Reserve said bank borrowings from the Federal
Reserve System averaged $1.301 billion, up from $541 million.
   _The Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis reprted that the monetary
base, the seasonally adjusted total of member bank reserves held at
Federal Reserve banks and cash in bank vaults and in circulation,
was $2.789 billion in the two-week period ended Wednesday, up from
$2.782 billion two weeks earlier.
</TEXT>
