<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-GE     07-07 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-GE,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GE's Earnings Up 23 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAIRFIELD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Electric Co. on Thursday said
its second quarter profit jumped 16 percent because of strong
performances by the company's plastics, broadcasting and financial
services operations.
   The Fairfield-based company said net earnings totaled $835
million, or 93 cents a share, up from $720 million, or 79 cents a
share originally reported for the the same period a year ago.
   GE's 1987 quarterly earnings were restated at year-end to
reflect adoption of new income tax accounting rules. The company
said in a statement that ongoing operations are not affected by the
change.
   Sales during the second quarter totaled $9.25 billion, off 3
percent from $9.56 billion in the previous quarter when sales of
the company's consumer electronics businesses were included.
   GE-RCA Consumer Electronics, which contributed about $3 billion
a year in sales, was sold to Thomson SA of France late last year.
   ``With these results, GE is well on its way to a second
consecutive full year of strong double-digit increases in
earnings,'' said GE Chairman John F. Welch Jr.
   Welch also said that since the last earnings report, the company
has forged several important agreements, one with labor and two to
expand the plastics business.
   On Wednesday, GE's largest union, the International Union of
Electronic Workers, overwhelmingly ratified a new three-year
national contract.
   GE Plastics formed a joint venture with Union Carbide Corp.'s
silicone business. GE also signed a definitive agreement to
Borg-Warner Corp.'s chemical businesses for about $2.3 billion.
   The company said NBC's television operations posted solid
improvements in profits, while revenue held at last year's levels.
   Earnings for the first six months of 1988 were $1.56 billion, or
$1.73 a share, up 16 percent from $1.34 billion, or $1.47 a share
in the first half of last year.
   Sales during the period totaled $17.22 billion, down 4 percent
from $17.86 billion in the year-ago period, which included the
consumer electronics operations.
</TEXT>
