<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Braniff-GPA     07-07 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Braniff-GPA,0254</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Irish Company Buys Option to Take 10 Percent of Braniff</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   AMSTERDAM _ GPA Group Ltd. said Thursday it has acquired an
option to buy 10 percent of Braniff Inc.
   GPA Group, a privately-owned financial services company based in
Ireland, specializes in aircraft asset management.
   BIA-COR Holdings Inc., a U.S. investment group, recently
acquired Dallas-based Braniff from Dalfort Corp. for $100 million.
   GPA Group said the option is part of a transaction under which
an Irish-Dutch leasing affiliate of GPA will sell Braniff 12
medium-haul aircraft made by the Dutch maker of Fokker planes. The
leasing affiliate will sell 12 new F-100 fanjets to Braniff for a
combination of cash and 12 aging BAC-111 planes now owned by
Braniff.
   GPA Group will also have the option to acquire 10 percent of
Braniff's common stock.
   Under the deal, the leasing affiliate will lease the BAC-111s
back to Braniff for use until the new F-100s are built and
delivered sometime between September 1989 and December 1990.
   The entire transaction is worth around $300 million, according
to analysts.
   American Airlines, a rival of Braniff, recently agreed to lend
Braniff as much as $21 million, according to documents filed
Tuesday by BIA-COR Holdings with the U.S. Securities and Exchange
Commission.
   Fort Worth-based American already has loaned Braniff $14.4
million, the documents showed. American, which competes with
Braniff at Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport, also agreed to
purchase $19 million to $23 million of Braniff's assets.
</TEXT>
