<1ST_LINE>r f AM-GERatification     07-07 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-GE Ratification,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Union Members Approve General Electric Contract</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARJORIE ANDERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Electric Co.'s largest union,
representing 40,000 workers, overwhelmingly ratified a new contract
and 11 smaller unions were expected to follow suit, labor leaders
said Thursday.
   Members of the International Union of Electronic Workers voted
nearly 5-to-1 in favor of the three-year pact with all but two of
the 72 locals reporting, union spokesman Jerry Borstel.
   The two locals who had not reported represent just 20 workers.
   ``It's pretty final,'' Borstel said.
   Sixty-six locals approved the pact, three rejected it, and one
local split evenly. The vote was 33,378 to 6,785 to approve the
pact, he said.
   ``The overwhelming vote to ratify shows that the IUE membership
is satisfied with this settlement, which is worth more than the
1985 contract and is better than any other agreement negotiated in
industry this year,'' said IUE President William Bywater.
   Bywater said he expected the 11 smaller unions that joined the
IUE at the bargaining table to ratify the contract.
   The tentative agreement, reached June 26, calls for a special
early retirement package; three annual wage increases of 2.5
percent, 1.5 percent and 1.5 percent; two cash bonuses; reduced
employee pension contributions; preferential hiring for IUE
members; dependent care aid, and other improvements.
   The average hourly wage of $12.02 would rise to $13.40, assuming
4.5 percent annual inflation, according to GE figures. The average
employee stands to gain about $6,100 over the life of the contract.
   Workers covered by the pact produce everything from light bulbs
to appliances, medical equipment to aerospace products, and
maintain factories and machinery.
   Each union must ratify the pact by Sunday for its terms to be
retroactive, GE spokesman Jack Batty said.
</TEXT>
