<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ReadingDivests     07-07 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reading Divests,0437</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reading & Bates Plans To Sell Subsidiary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIL BROYLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reading & Bates Corp. announced Thursday it
will sell its oil and gas subsidiary and move its corporate
headquarters to Houston, where it will concentrate on offshore
drilling.
   About 30 employees were laid off Thursday, and another 100 will
lose their jobs in the next few months, officials said. The company
has about 2,000 employees worldwide.
   J.W. Bates Jr., chairman and chief executive officer, said the
move to Houston is expected to be completed by the end of the year.
   Another subsidiary, Reading & Bates Drilling Co. has maintained
offices in Houston for more than 30 years.
   ``Obviously, the decision has been a very difficult one,'' said
Bates, who helped start the company in 1955.
   But he said it is necessary because there has been no turnaround
for the oil industry. Reading & Bates has had three years of losses
and a fourth is anticipated, he said.
   ``I think there's no question it'll get better,'' Bates said.
``The question is, when. If the company is to survive as a major
international offshore drilling contractor, which has been our
principal business throughout the years, we have no alternative.''
   Reading & Bates operates a fleet of 18 offshore drilling rigs
throughout the world. The company also owns Resources Conservation
Co., a process engineering company located in Seattle, and Reading
& Bates Coal Co. operating in eastern Kentucky.
   Reading & Bates disposed of its pipeline construction business
in 1985. In 1987, the company completed sale of its foreign oil and
gas production, its horizontal drilling operations and its part of
a land drilling venture in Argentina.
   It reported losses of $191 million, in 1987, $145.8 million in
1986 and $190.6 million in 1985.
   The company is in default of all leases, subject to continuing
negotiations, in an amount estimated at $272.2 million as of Dec.
31, 1987. The company and its lenders are continuing to negotiate
terms of a restructuring agreement, Bates said.
   ``Hopefully, that will be accomplished by the end of the year,
or certainly next year,'' he said.
   Bates said he does not believe the company will have any trouble
finding a buyer for the petroleum company.
   Reading & Bates Petroleum Co. had operating revenues of about
$25 million in 1987, and proved developed reserves in the U.S. of
5.7 million barrels of oil and 70 billion cubic feet of natural gas.
   ``There is intense interest in acquiring reserves,'' Bates said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880707-0217 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 1940EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-SEC-Arbitration     07-07 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SEC-Arbitration,0586</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SEC Backs Down on Plan to Give Investors Right to Sue Brokers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-SEC, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission on
Thursday backed off from recommending legislation that would
guarantee investors the right to sue their stock broker in court.
   The commission had been considering asking Congress to outlaw
clauses in brokerage account agreements requiring customers to
settle disputes through industry-sponsored arbitration panels,
rather than through the courts.
   But, by a 5-0 vote, the commission decided instead to ask stock
exchanges and other organizations that run arbitration systems to
study the matter and report back by Oct. 15.
   Rep. Edward J. Markey, D-Mass., chairman of the House
subcommittee with jurisdiction over the securities markets, said
the SEC had caved in to industry lobbying with its decision.
   ``Apparently there was a full-court press by the industry that
was successful,'' Markey said. ``...I think the industry stared
into the SEC's eyes on this issue and the SEC blinked.''
   When the commission discussed the arbitration clauses last
month, the legislative recommendation looked headed for approval.
It was supported by SEC Chairman David S. Ruder and member Aulana
L. Peters. Commissioner Charles C. Cox said he was inclined to
favor it but wanted to hear from securities firms, which strongly
opposed banning the clauses.
   But, on Thursday, Ruder retreated from his earlier support. He
said he was persuaded to defer action after learning the industry
would at least favor disclosure notices to customers explaining the
meaning of the clauses.
   An SEC survey found that 39 percent of cash accounts carry
arbitration agreements and that firms holding another 40 percent
were considering using such clauses.
   But Ruder said many firms that were once looking into using the
clauses for cash accounts appear to be holding off at least for
now. He also said some regional firms have recently made a point of
advertising that they will open cash accounts without arbitration
clauses.
   However, nearly all firms surveyed, 95 percent, require
arbitration agreements for option and margin accounts, where the
risk of loss is greater.
   Proponents of the clauses argue that customers are free to
negotiate the clauses out of the contract and that firms have a
right to set the conditions under which they're willing to do
business.
   Administration officials, including Beryl Sprinkel, chairman of
the Council of Economic Advisers, had sent letters to the SEC
criticizing staff proposals on arbitration clauses.
   Despite the lack of SEC support, Reps. Rick Boucher, D-Va.; John
D. Dingell, D-Mich., and Edward J. Markey, D-Mass., have introduced
legislation anyway.
   The bill is backed by state securities regulators and others who
say arbitration clauses are unfair because they require customers
to sign away their right to sue before they know the nature of any
disagreement that may arise.
   The head of the North American Securities Administrators
Association, which represents state regulators, called the SEC
decision ``disappointing.''
   ``If the commission's mistake goes uncorrected, investors will
end up having only those rights which the securities industry
chooses to give them. ... Small investors will see the commission
failure to act as another sign that the deck is stacked against
them,'' said James C. Meyer, president of the association and
Tennessee's top securities regulator.
   Ruder, however, said, ``I want to make it clear that (this) ...
is not a decision to de-emphasize consumer interest in the
securities industry.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
