<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Japan-Scandal 1stLd-Writethru f0241 07-07 0752</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Scandal, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0241,0776</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Takeshita Aide Implicated in Political Scandal</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 17th graf pvs, Ko Marita ... with 1 graf to CORRECT
spelling to Morita.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former secretary to Prime Minister Noboru
Takeshita was added Thursday to the list of aides to top
politicians who reportedly profited from questionable stock
dealings in a scandal sweeping Japanese business and politics.
   Takeshita told reporters that his former secretary, Ihei Aoki,
earned profits by trading the shares of the real estate company
Recruit-Cosmos. He said Aoki obtained shares from the company and
then sold them shortly after Recruit-Cosmos went public in October
1986, when Takeshita was finance minister.
   In related developments, the president of Japan's leading
economic newspaper and the chairman of Recruit-Cosmos resigned. The
chairman of Recruit-Cosmos and its parent company also announced he
will step down.
   The dealings were not illegal, but critics said the case
illustrates doubtful ethics in the links between Japan's
politicians and businessmen.
   Takeshita did not elaborate on the number of shares Aoki traded
or his profits from the deal, and refused to take responsibility
for his former aide's action.
   But Takeshita acknowledged that the scandal would seriously
affect an upcoming session of the Diet, Japan's parliament, when
the administration hopes to push through a major tax reform measure.
   The controversy surfaced last month as a bribery case in a local
government, but entered a new phase with revelations that aides to
leaders of the governing Liberal Democratic Party profited with
Recruit-Cosmos stock.
   In addition to Takeshita, the scandal has affected secretaries
of Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa, former Prime Minister Yasuhiro
Nakasone, Liberal Democratic Party Secretary General and former
Foreign Minister Shintaro Abe, former Defense Agency Director
General Koichi Kato, and Michio Watanabe, the former minister of
international trade and industry..
   Of them, only Miyazawa has denied knowing of the stock deals.
The others said they had become aware their aides had received the
stock and made profits.
   ``This involves the most senior (Liberal Democratic Party)
officials, and there is going to be a major outcry from the
Japanese people,'' said Shigeru Ito, a leader of the main
opposition Japan Socialist Party. ``Although they broke no law,
they abused their positions to line their pockets.''
   Saburo Tsukamoto, chairman of Democratic Socialist Party, the
third largest opposition party, also was found on the list of 76
people who reportedly profited from the transactions.
   According to Japanese press reports, Recruit-Cosmos gave or sold
stock at an artificially low price to high-ranking politicians. In
some instances, the company reportedly lent money to politicians to
buy the shares.
   When the company went public in October 1986 and the stock price
soared, the politicians were able to reap large profits, the
reports said.
   It was not clear what, if anything, the politicians did for
Recruit-Cosmos in return.
   ``Whether they are politicians or company heads, those who have
responsibilities must behave prudently, not to be criticized by the
general public,'' Chief Cabinet Secretary Keizo Obuchi said in the
only official comment from the government on the matter.
   Not only politicians are involved in the scandal.
   Ko Morita, president of Japan's leading economic daily, Nihon
Keizai Shimbun, resigned Wednesday after it was revealed that he
had dealt in Recruit-Cosmos shares, violating the rules of his
newspaper.
   Hiromasa Ezoe, chairman of Recruit-Cosmos and its parent company
Recruit Ltd., a giant information service firm, also announced that
he will resign the two chairmanships.
   The president of Recruit, Naotaka Ida, said Ezoe will also
withdraw from the government's tax commission.
   ``Politicians want as much money as they can get, and
businessmen always look for connections with politicians,'' said an
editorial in Asahi Shimbun, the newspaper that broke the story.
   The controversy is the latest in a series of scandals to rock
Japan's long-dominant Liberal Democratic Party.
   Six people have been indicted since May for allegedly arranging
bribes by advertising agencies to gain public relations contracts
with the prime minister's office.
   Last month, five executives of a Tokyo electronics firm who made
large donations to both the Liberal Democratic and Japan Socialist
parties were arrested for evading income taxes of $12 million,
earned from illegal stocks manipulation.
   Former Prime Minister Kakuei Tanaka was found guilty in 1983 of
accepting bribes from the Lockheed Corp. of the United States, but
he remained an important force in Japanese politics until he
suffered a stroke in 1985.
   Takeshita's faction within the ruling party is made up mainly of
former Tanaka followers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
