<1ST_LINE>u f AM-BroadcastMuseum 1stLd-Writethru f0137 07-07 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Broadcast Museum, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0137,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Big, New Museum of Broadcast Planned</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 6th graf to CORRECT to Burgee sted Burgess</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 17-story tower will be built to house the
growing Museum of Broadcasting, board Chairman William S. Paley
announced Thursday.
   ``This wonderful new building gives the museum the space it
needs,'' said Paley, founder of CBS. ``It dramatically marks the
museum's coming of age.''
   Paley said he hopes the extra space can double the 100,000
people a year now drawn to the 12-year-old museum, whose 37-member
board includes Alan Alda, Lucille Ball, Steven Bochco, Norman Lear,
Marlo Thomas and Grant Tinker.
   The groundbreaking on a vacant lot on West 52nd Street, next
door to the 21 Club, is planned for September. Construction should
take two years.
   The building, by design consultant Philip Johnson and architect
John Burgee, features a two-story arch at the sidewalk and a
set-back tower.
   Burgee noted that a museum building must be designed as ``a
civic monument, a dignified place ... and it has to be timeless,
because it's forever and ever.''
   The plans include 200-seat and 90-seat theaters; a screening
room and classroom; a radio listening room; a library with card
catalogs of programs and scripts; and galleries.
   The archives already house cassettes of 30,000 programs.
   Radio buffs can hear President Roosevelt's Fireside Chats,
Gracie Allen and George Burns, or Garrison Keillor's Prairie Home
Companion. TV devotees can revel in ``I Love Lucy,'' ``Roots,''
``Cagney and Lacey'' _ or even their favorite commercials.
   About two-thirds of the estimated $45 million cost has been met
_ including Paley's contribution, a $12 million parcel of land.
   The top four floors will be rented out to businesses to help
defray operating costs, said Paley. He said he also will lease the
old museum building as offices once the new one is finished.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
