<FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 2346EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Perot-Postal 1stLd-Writethru   07-07 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Perot-Postal, 1st Ld-Writethru,0447</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Post Office Takes Contract Dispute to Court</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS grafs 3-4 pvs, `The deal ... the case,' to UPDATE with
contract appeals board ordering temporary freeze on the contract;
SUBS grafs 6-7 pvs, `That argument ... been issued,' with 1 graf to
DELETE outdated material</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Postal Service has turned to a
federal court in an effort to thwart challenges to a contract it
arranged with Texas computer billionaire H. Ross Perot.
   At stake is a potentially multimillion-dollar contract to study
ways to improve postal efficiency.
   The deal is being challenged by would-be competitors who didn't
get to bid. They have asked the General Services Administration's
Board of Contract Appeals to order suspension of the agreement, and
the board complied Thursday, ordering a temporary freeze on the
contract.
   The Postal Service on Wednesday asked the U.S. Court of Appeals
for the Federal Circuit to rule that the contract board doesn't
have jurisdiction in the case.
   The Postal Service contends that it is exempt from the federal
procurement law that calls for the GSA to arrange most government
purchases of data processing services and equipment.
   That argument didn't wash with the Board of Contract Appeals,
however, which declined to drop the case on jurisdictional grounds.
   In a separate case last April, the board concluded that it did
have jurisdiction over the Postal Service and said that agency is
indeed bound by the procurement rules.
   Postal officials, insisting that they are not covered by the
law, declined Tuesday to provide documents or individuals to
testify before the board.
   The Postal Service agreed that it did not follow provisions of
the law, saying that that was because it has its own purchasing
rules, which were followed.
   The deal is being challenged by Electronic Data Systems Corp.,
Perot's former company and now a part of General Motors Corp., and
by Planning Research Corp. of McLean, Va.
   The contract is in two phases. The first is a $500,000 agreement
calling for Perot to analyze postal operations and recommend ways
to save money. It was announced June 2 and immediately drew
criticism from a variety of sources.
   After the first 90-day phase, there is to be a second part, in
which Perot would be paid a percentage of any savings the Postal
Service realized from implementing his recommendations for ways of
improving its systems and procedures.
   The Senate, meanwhile, has requested the General Accounting
Office to investigate terms of the deal, and directed the Postal
Service to delay the second phase in the meantime.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
